ounty, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Hart County, Georgia]]\n", "text_old": "{{highway detail hatnote|U.S. Route 29}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=GA\n|type=US\n|route=29\n|length_mi=207\n|direction_a=South\n|direction_b=North\n|map=US 29 in Georgia map.svg\n|map_notes=Route of US 29 highlighted in red\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=AL|US|29}} at the Alabama state line in [[West Point, Georgia|West Point]]\n|junction={{plainlist|1=\n*{{jct|state=GA|US|27}} in [[LaGrange, Georgia|LaGrange]]\n*{{jct|state=GA|I|85}} in [[Grantville, Georgia|Grantville]] and [[East Newnan, Georgia|East Newnan]]\n*{{jct|state=GA|I|285}} in [[Red Oak, Georgia|Red Oak]] and [[Tucker, Georgia|Tucker]]\n*{{jct|state=GA|US|19|US|41}} in [[Atlanta]]\n*{{jct|state=GA|US|78|US|278}} in Atlanta\n*{{jct|state=GA|I|75|I|85}} in Atlanta\n*{{jct|state=GA|US|129|US|441}} in [[Athens, Georgia|Athens]] }}\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=SC|US|29}} at the South Carolina state line near [[Lake Hartwell]]\n|counties=[[Troup County, Georgia|Troup]], [[Coweta County, Georgia|Coweta]], [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton]], [[Clayton County, Georgia|Clayton]], [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb]], [[Gwinnett County, Georgia|Gwinnett]], [[Barrow County, Georgia|Barrow]], [[Oconee County, Georgia|Oconee]], [[Clarke County, Georgia|Clarke]], [[Madison County, Georgia|Madison]], [[Franklin County, Georgia|Franklin]], [[Hart County, Georgia|Hart]]\n|previous_type=SR\n|previous_route=28\n|browse_route=\n|next_type=SR\n|next_route=29\n}}\n'''U.S. Route 29''' ('''US&nbsp;29''') in the state of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], is a north\u2013south [[United States Numbered Highway]] that runs southwest to northeast from [[West Point, Georgia|West Point]] at the [[Alabama]] state line to the [[South Carolina]] state line, near [[Lake Hartwell]]. From West Point at the  to downtown Atlanta, the [[Georgia Department of Transportation]] (GDOT) has [[concurrency (road)|cosigned]] US 29 with [[Georgia State Route 14|State Route&nbsp;14]] (SR&nbsp;14). North of downtown Atlanta, the route runs along [[Georgia State Route 8|SR&nbsp;8]] to [[Dacula, Georgia|Dacula]] and again from west of [[Statham, Georgia|Statham]] to the South Carolina state line.\n\nConcurrencies of US&nbsp;29 with US routes in Georgia include [[U.S. Route 27 in Georgia|US&nbsp;27]] in [[LaGrange, Georgia|LaGrange]] as well as [[U.S. Route 27 Alternate (Georgia)|US&nbsp;27 ALT]] from [[Moreland, Georgia|Moreland]] to [[Newnan, Georgia|Newnan]]. Others include [[U.S. Route 19 in Georgia|US&nbsp;19]]/[[U.S. Route 41 in Georgia|US&nbsp;41]] from [[Castleberry Hill]] to the vicinity of [[Georgia Tech]] in Atlanta, [[U.S. Route 78 in Georgia|US&nbsp;78]] from Georgia Tech to [[Scottdale, Georgia|Scottdale]], and again from near Bogart to Athens, [[U.S. Route 278 in Georgia|US&nbsp;278]] from Georgia Tech to Druid Hills, [[U.S. Route 23 in Georgia|US&nbsp;23]] from east Atlanta, to Decatur, and [[U.S. Route 129 in Georgia|US&nbsp;129]]/[[U.S. Route 441 in Georgia|US&nbsp;441]] in the vicinity of [[Athens, Georgia|Athens]].\n\n==Route description==\n{{Expand section|date=August 2019}}\nThe following portions of US&nbsp;29 in Georgia are part of the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]], a system of routes determined to be the most important for the nation's economy, mobility, and defense:\n*The concurrency with US&nbsp;27/SR&nbsp;1 in LaGrange\n*From I-85 just south of East Newnan to SR&nbsp;34 in Newnan\n*From SR&nbsp;74 in Fairburn to US&nbsp;29 Alt./SR&nbsp;14 Alt./SR&nbsp;14 Conn. in Red Oak\n*From I-20 in Atlanta to the intersection with Jimmy Carter Boulevard and Mountain Industrial Boulevard in Tucker\n*From US&nbsp;29 Bus./SR&nbsp;8/SR&nbsp;316 just west of Dacula to SR&nbsp;72 in Athens<ref name=\"NHS Georgia\">{{cite map |url=https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/national_highway_system/nhs_maps/georgia/ga_georgia.pdf |title=National Highway System: Georgia |publisher=[[Federal Highway Administration]] |date=May 8, 2019 |access-date=August 11, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"NHS Atlanta\">{{cite map |url=https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/national_highway_system/nhs_maps/georgia/atlanta_ga.pdf |title=National Highway System: Atlanta, GA |publisher=Federal Highway Administration |date=May 9, 2019 |access-date=August 11, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"NHS Athens\">{{cite map |url=https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/national_highway_system/nhs_maps/georgia/athens-clarke_county_ga.pdf |title=National Highway System: Athens-Clarke County, GA |publisher=Federal Highway Administration |date=May 9, 2019 |access-date=August 11, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nFormer sections of the road have included local streets named \"Old Highway 29\" in various locations as well as Broad Street (GA 14 Connector) in LaGrange<ref>{{cite GDOT map |year= 1970 |section= |sections= |access-date= }}{{full citation needed|date=February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite GDOT map |year = 1971 |section= |sections= |access-date= }}{{full citation needed|date=February 2017}}</ref> and [[U.S. Route 29 Business (Lawrenceville\u2013Winder, Georgia)|U.S. Route 29 Business]] between Dacula and west of Statham. Other former segments include Old West Point Road south of LaGrange, Wynne-Russell Drive in Lilburn, Old Athens Road in Lawrenceville, Sam Groves Street in Danielsville, Old Royston Road in Bluestone, and Franklin Springs Circle in Royston.\n\nParts of US 29 to the southwest of Atlanta has been named Roosevelt Highway, since [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] made his final journey northward from Warm Springs along this stretch of highway. Large crowds gathered along US 29 on this day in April 1945 to pay their final respects to the deceased President. Unfortunately for those who waited along the highway they missed seeing the president's body being transported back to Washington on a train that ran on nearby tracks.\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{Mileposts}}\n{{Jcttop|exit|length_ref=}}\n{{ALint|exit\n|county=Chambers\n|location=Lanett\n|mile=0.0\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=AL|US|29|dir1=south|SR|15|dir2=south}}\n|notes=Continuation into Alabama, southern end of [[Georgia State Route 14|SR&nbsp;14]] concurrency\n}}\n{{GAint|exit\n|county=Troup\n|cspan=10\n|location=West Point\n|lspan=2\n|mile=\n|road=John C. Barrow Bridge over the [[Chattahoochee River]]\n|notes=US 29 leaves West 9th Street and becomes East 10th Street\n}}\n{{GAint|exit\n|mile=\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|18|dir1=east|name1=East 10th Street}}\n|notes=Western terminus of SR&nbsp;18\n}}\n{{GAint|exit\n|location=LaGrange\n|lspan=6\n|mile=\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|109|dir1=west|name1=Roanoke Road}}\n|notes=Western end of SR&nbsp;109 concurrency\n}}\n{{GAint|exit\n|mile=\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|14|dab1=LaGrange|dir1=north|name1=Broad Street}}\n|notes=Western terminus of SR&nbsp;14 Connector\n}}\n{{GAint|exit\n|mile=\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=GA|US|27|dir1=south|SR|1|dir2=south|SR|219|dir3=south|SR|109|dir4=east|name4=Martha Berry Highway}}\n|notes=Southern end of US&nbsp;27/SR&nbsp;1/SR&nbsp;219 concurrency, eastern end of SR&nbsp;109 concurrency\n}}\n{{GAint|exit\n|mile=\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|14|dab1=LaGrange|dir1=south|SR|219|dir2=north|name2=Broad Street}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of SR&nbsp;14 Connector; northern end of SR&nbsp;219 concurrency; Broad Street becomes Greenville Street east of US 27/29\n}}\n{{GAint|exit\n|mile=\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=GA|US|27|dir1=north|SR|1|dir2=north|SR|219|dir3=north|name3=Martha Berry Highway}}\n|notes=Northern end of US&nbsp;27/SR&nbsp;1 concurrency\n}}\n{{GAint|exit\n|mile=\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR-Spur|14|dab1=LaGrange|dir1=south|name1=Davis Road}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of SR&nbsp;14 Spur\n}}\n{{GAint|exit\n|location=Hogansville\n|lspan=2\n|mile=\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|54|SR|100|dir2=south|name2=Main Street}}\n|notes=Southern end of SR&nbsp;100 concurrency\n}}\n{{GAint|exit\n|mile=\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|s