{"title_page": "Shaun Smith (defensive lineman)", "text_new": "{{short description|American football player, defensive end}}\n{{For|other football players called Shaun Smith|Shaun Smith (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name=Shaun Smith\n|image=Shaun Smith 2006-11-05.jpg\n|image_size=275px\n|caption=Smith as a member of the Cincinnati Bengals\n|number=99, 66, 91, 71, 90, 93\n|position=[[Defensive End]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1981|08|19}}\n|birth_place=[[New York, New York]]\n|death_date=\n|high_school=[[Midwood High School]]<br>([[Brooklyn, New York]])<br>\n[[Wichita Heights High School|Wichita Heights]]<br>([[Wichita, Kansas]])\n|college=[[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]]\n|undraftedyear=2003\n|pastteams=\n* [[Dallas Cowboys]] ({{NFL Year|2003}})*\n* [[Arizona Cardinals]] ({{NFL Year|2004}})*\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] ({{NFL Year|2004}})\n* [[Cincinnati Bengals]] ({{NFL Year|2004}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2006}})\n* [[Cleveland Browns]] ({{NFL Year|2007}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2008}})\n* [[Detroit Lions]] ({{NFL Year|2009}})*\n* [[Las Vegas Locomotives]] ({{UFL Year|2009}})\n* [[Cincinnati Bengals]] ({{NFL Year|2009}})\n* [[Kansas City Chiefs]] ({{NFL Year|2010}})\n* [[Tennessee Titans]] ({{NFL Year|2011}})\n* [[Kansas City Chiefs]] ([[2012 NFL season|2012]])\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n|highlights=\n* [[United Football League (2009)|UFL]] champion ([[2009 UFL Championship Game|2009]])\n|statlabel1=Games played\n|statvalue1=102\n|statlabel2=[[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n|statvalue2=244\n|statlabel3=[[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n|statvalue3=4.0\n|statlabel4=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n|statvalue4=2\n|nfl=SMI711660\n|pfr=SmitSh20\n}}\n\n'''Shaun Jamel Smith''' (born August 19, 1981) is a former [[American football]] [[defensive end]] in the [[National Football League]] for the [[Dallas Cowboys]], [[Cincinnati Bengals]], [[New Orleans Saints]], [[Cleveland Browns]], [[Kansas City Chiefs]], and [[Tennessee Titans]]. He also was a member of the [[Las Vegas Locomotives]] in the [[United Football League (2009\u20132012)|United Football League]]. He was signed by the [[Dallas Cowboys]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 2003. He played [[college football]] at the [[University of South Carolina]].\n\n==Early years==\nSmith attended [[Midwood High School]] in [[Brooklyn, New York]]. He transfered after his sophomore season to [[Wichita Heights High School]] in [[Wichita, Kansas]]. He played as a [[defensive end]].\n\nHe enrolled at [[Butler Community College]] in [[El Dorado, Kansas]]. As a freshman in 1999, Smith along with teammate [[Rudi Johnson]], contributed to the school winning the national championship by defeating [[Dixie College]]. As a sophomore in 2000, he registered 128 tackles and a school single-season record 20 sacks.\n\nAs a junior in 2001, he transferred to the [[University of South Carolina]], where he was a backup [[defensive end]], making 11 tackles. As a senior in 2002, he started 2 games and posted 38 tackles, one sack and one fumble recovery in 12 games.\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Dallas Cowboys===\nSmith was signed as an [[undrafted free agent]] by the [[Dallas Cowboys]] after the [[2003 NFL Draft]] on May 1. He was signed to the [[practice squad]] on September 1 after being waived on August 31.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire/_/id/1606839 | title=Cowboys cuts include RB Murrell, WR Rambo, TE McGee | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He was released on August 31, 2004.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=1871756 | title=Receiver hurt both knees in game Monday | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Arizona Cardinals===\nSmith was claimed off waivers by the [[Arizona Cardinals]] on September 1, 2004.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire?section=nfl&id=1872993 | title=Cardinals claim 2 off waivers; put Shipp, Hodgins on IR | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He was waived five days later on September 5.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=1875352 | title=All four expected to stay on active roster | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===New Orleans Saints===\nOn September 7, 2004, he was signed to the [[New Orleans Saints]]' [[practice squad]]. He was promoted to the active roster on September 18 and made his debut versus the [[San Francisco 49ers]] on September 19. He finished with 16 tackles and one [[Starting lineup|start]]. He was released on November 30, after getting food from the [[Georgia Dome]] press box, while being deactivated for a game.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=clayton_john&id=1937779 | title=Drafting defensive tackles can be risky | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cincinnati Bengals (first stint)===\nSmith was claimed off waivers by the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] on December 2, 2004.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=1937071 | title=Davis sidelined with turf toe | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He played [[defensive tackle]], while recording six tackles and one start. In 2005, he recorded 38 tackles in 13 games with five starts. In 2006, he registered 14 tackles. In 2007, the Bengals opted not to match the restricted free-agent offer sheet that Smith received from the [[Cleveland Browns]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2801079 | title=Bengals decline to match Browns' offer for Smith | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Browns===\nSmith signed a four-year deal with the [[Cleveland Browns]] as a [[restricted free agent]] on March 16, 2007.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire?id=2800921&section=nfl | title=Browns sign DL Robaire Smith | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He played mostly as a [[defensive end]] in a [[3-4 defense]], started 11 games and made 62 tackles.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.oakridger.com/article/20080723/NEWS/307239931 | title=Former Oak Grove star had early NFL thoughts | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2008, he was tried at [[nose tackle]] during training camp, but was moved back to [[defensive end]]. He started 9 out of 11 games, while making 47 tackles and being limited with a calf injury. On December 23, various media outlets reported that [[Brady Quinn]] had a physical altercation with Smith in the Browns' weight training room, and that Smith punched Quinn in the face. Quinn denied the reports, and coach [[Romeo Crennel]] refused to comment; Browns [[tight end]] [[Darnell Dinkins]] confirmed the fight during a radio interview on [[WQAL]]. Smith did not play in the following game because of a coaches' decision.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=3787518 | title=Cleveland Browns Coach Still Confident of the Future | website=ESPN.com | date=December 23, 2008 | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He was released on August 8, 2009.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=4385725 | title=Browns release lineman Shaun Smith | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Detroit Lions===\nSmith was signed by the [[Detroit Lions]] on August 10, 2009. Smith was released during the final roster cuts on September 5.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/trainingcamp09/news/story?id=4448124 | title=Training Camp Roundup: Sept. 5 | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>  He also was suspended for the first 4 games of the season for violating the league's anabolic steroid policy.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=4461885 | title=Source: Smith suspended four games | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Las Vegas Locomotives (UFL)===\nOn November 19, 2009, he signed with the [[Las Vegas Locomotives]] of the [[United Football League (2009\u20132012)|United Football League]], to replace an injured [[Wendell Bryant]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2009/11/19/shaun-smith-resurfaces-in-ufl/ | title=Shaun Smith resurfaces in UFL | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He contributed to the team winning the UFL Champsionship game against the [[Florida Tuskers]] on November 27.\n\n===Cincinnati Bengals (second stint)===\nSmith was re-signed by the Bengals on December 9, 2009.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/blog/afcnorth/post/_/id/6559/shaun-smith-returning-to-bengals | title=Shaun Smith returning to Bengals | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He was waived on December 12 and re-signed on December 16. He was not re-signed after the season.\n\n===Kansas City Chiefs (first stint)===\nSmith signed with the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] on March 10, 2010.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.columbian.com/news/2010/mar/10/chiefs-sign-defensive-tackle-shaun-smith/ | title=Chiefs sign defensive tackle Shaun Smith | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>  In consecutive weeks, he was accused by players from the opposing team of grabbing them in their private parts during play. [[Alex Mack]] of the [[Cleveland Browns]] made the first claim after the two teams' Week 2 matchup, followed by [[Anthony Davis (offensive tackle, born 1989)|Anthony Davis]] of the [[San Francisco 49ers]], who drew a penalty for retaliating against Smith in Week 3.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/5597659 | title=Alex Mack: Shaun Smith played dirty | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> Although Smith denied both allegations, he was fined by the league.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/blog/afcwest/post/_/id/18035/report-chiefs-shaun-smith-fined | title=Report: Chiefs' Shaun Smith fined | website=ESPN | date=October 1, 2010 | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Tennessee Titans===\nOn July 29 of 2011, he signed with the [[Tennessee Titans]] a three-year, $7.25 million contract, to play as a [[defensive tackle]]. He scored his first career rushing touchdown on Week 12 against the [[Seattle Seahawks]]. He finished with 6 starts, 25 tackles and one sack.\n\nIn 2012, he showed up in training camp out of shape and underperformed. He was released on August 22.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/trainingcamp12/story/_/id/8292290/tennessee-titans-deep-dt-spot-release-veteran-shaun-smith | title=Titans release DT Shaun Smith | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Kansas City Chiefs (second stint)===\nOn November 5, 2012, he re-signed with the [[Kansas City Chiefs]], to serve as insurance in case [[Glenn Dorsey]] missed multiple games with a calf injury.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/8596859/kansas-chiefs-cut-stanford-routt-name-gary-gibbs-new-dc | title=Chiefs make changes on defense | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He was not re-signed for the [[2013 NFL season|2013 season]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2009 Las Vegas Locomotives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Shaun}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American football defensive tackles]]\n[[Category:American football defensive ends]]\n[[Category:Butler Grizzlies football players]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Gamecocks football players]]\n[[Category:Dallas Cowboys players]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Bengals players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions players]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas Locomotives players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Titans players]]\n[[Category:Midwood High School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football player, defensive end}}\n{{For|other football players called Shaun Smith|Shaun Smith (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name=Shaun Smith\n|image=Shaun Smith 2006-11-05.jpg\n|image_size=275px\n|caption=Smith as a member of the Cincinnati Bengals\n|number=99, 66, 91, 71, 90, 93\n|position=[[Defensive End]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1981|08|19}}\n|birth_place=[[New York, New York]]\n|death_date=\n|high_school=[[Midwood High School]]<br>([[Brooklyn, New York]])<br>\n[[Wichita Heights High School|Wichita Heights]]<br>([[Wichita, Kansas]])\n|college=[[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]]\n|undraftedyear=2003\n|pastteams=\n* [[Dallas Cowboys]] ({{NFL Year|2003}})*\n* [[Arizona Cardinals]] ({{NFL Year|2004}})*\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] ({{NFL Year|2004}})\n* [[Cincinnati Bengals]] ({{NFL Year|2004}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2006}})\n* [[Cleveland Browns]] ({{NFL Year|2007}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2008}})\n* [[Detroit Lions]] ({{NFL Year|2009}})*\n* [[Las Vegas Locomotives]] ({{UFL Year|2009}})\n* [[Cincinnati Bengals]] ({{NFL Year|2009}})\n* [[Kansas City Chiefs]] ({{NFL Year|2010}})\n* [[Tennessee Titans]] ({{NFL Year|2011}})\n* [[Kansas City Chiefs]] ([[2012 NFL season|2012]])\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n|highlights=\n* [[United Football League (2009)|UFL]] champion ([[2009 UFL Championship Game|2009]])\n|statlabel1=Games played\n|statvalue1=102\n|statlabel2=[[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n|statvalue2=244\n|statlabel3=[[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n|statvalue3=4.0\n|statlabel4=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n|statvalue4=2\n|nfl=SMI711660\n|pfr=SmitSh20\n}}\n\n'''Shaun Jamel Smith''' (born August 19, 1981) is a former [[American football]] [[defensive end]] in the [[National Football League]] for the [[Dallas Cowboys]], [[Cincinnati Bengals]], [[New Orleans Saints]], [[Cleveland Browns]], [[Kansas City Chiefs]], and [[Tennessee Titans]]. He also was a member of the [[Las Vegas Locomotives]] in the [[United Football League (2009\u20132012)|United Football League]]. He was signed by the [[Dallas Cowboys]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 2003. He played [[college football]] at the [[University of South Carolina]].\n\n==Early years==\nSmith attended [[Midwood High School]] in [[Brooklyn, New York]]. He transfered after his sophomore season to [[Wichita Heights High School]] in [[Wichita, Kansas]]. He played as a [[defensive end]].\n\nHe enrolled at [[Butler Community College]] in [[El Dorado, Kansas]]. As a freshman in 1999, Smith along with teammate [[Rudi Johnson]], contributed to the school winning the national championship by defeating [[Dixie College]]. As a sophomore in 2000, he registered 128 tackles and a school single-season record 20 sacks.\n\nAs a junior in 2001, he transferred to the [[University of South Carolina]], where he was a backup [[defensive end]], making 11 tackles. As a senior in 2002, he started 2 games and posted 38 tackles, one sack and one fumble recovery in 12 games.\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Dallas Cowboys===\nSmith was signed as an [[undrafted free agent]] by the [[Dallas Cowboys]] after the [[2003 NFL Draft]] on May 1. He was signed to the [[practice squad]] on September 1 after being waived on August 31.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire/_/id/1606839 | title=Cowboys cuts include RB Murrell, WR Rambo, TE McGee | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He was released on August 31, 2004.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=1871756 | title=Receiver hurt both knees in game Monday | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Arizona Cardinals===\nSmith was claimed off waivers by the [[Arizona Cardinals]] on September 1, 2004.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire?section=nfl&id=1872993 | title=Cardinals claim 2 off waivers; put Shipp, Hodgins on IR | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He was waived five days later on September 5.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=1875352 | title=All four expected to stay on active roster | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===New Orleans Saints===\nOn September 7, 2004, he was signed to the [[New Orleans Saints]]' [[practice squad]]. He was promoted to the active roster on September 18 and made his debut versus the [[San Francisco 49ers]] on September 19. He finished with 16 tackles and one [[Starting lineup|start]]. He was released on November 30, after getting food from the [[Georgia Dome]] press box, while being deactivated for a game.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=clayton_john&id=1937779 | title=Drafting defensive tackles can be risky | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cincinnati Bengals (first stint)===\nSmith was claimed off waivers by the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] on December 2, 2004.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=1937071 | title=Davis sidelined with turf toe | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He played [[defensive tackle]], while recording six tackles and one start. In 2005, he recorded 38 tackles in 13 games with five starts. In 2006, he registered 14 tackles. In 2007, the Bengals opted not to match the restricted free-agent offer sheet that Smith received from the [[Cleveland Browns]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2801079 | title=Bengals decline to match Browns' offer for Smith | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Browns===\nSmith signed a four-year deal with the [[Cleveland Browns]] as a [[restricted free agent]] on March 16, 2007.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire?id=2800921&section=nfl | title=Browns sign DL Robaire Smith | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He played mostly as a [[defensive end]] in a [[3-4 defense]], started 11 games and made 62 tackles.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.oakridger.com/article/20080723/NEWS/307239931 | title=Former Oak Grove star had early NFL thoughts | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2008, he was tried at [[nose tackle]] during training camp, but was moved back to [[defensive end]]. He started 9 out of 11 games, while making 47 tackles and being limited with a calf injury. On December 23, various media outlets reported that [[Brady Quinn]] had a physical altercation with Smith in the Browns' weight training room, and that Smith punched Quinn in the face. Quinn denied the reports, and coach [[Romeo Crennel]] refused to comment; Browns [[tight end]] [[Darnell Dinkins]] confirmed the fight during a radio interview on [[WQAL]]. Smith did not play in the following game because of a coaches' decision.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=3787518 | title=Cleveland Browns Coach Still Confident of the Future | website=ESPN.com | date=December 23, 2008 | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He was released on August 8, 2009.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=4385725 | title=Browns release lineman Shaun Smith | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Detroit Lions===\nSmith was signed by the [[Detroit Lions]] on August 10, 2009. Smith was released during the final roster cuts on September 5.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/trainingcamp09/news/story?id=4448124 | title=Training Camp Roundup: Sept. 5 | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>  He also was suspended for the first 4 games of the season for violating the league's anabolic steroid policy.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=4461885 | title=Source: Smith suspended four games | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Las Vegas Locomotives (UFL)===\nOn November 19, 2009, he signed with the [[Las Vegas Locomotives]] of the [[United Football League (2009\u20132012)|United Football League]], to replace an injured [[Wendell Bryant]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2009/11/19/shaun-smith-resurfaces-in-ufl/ | title=Shaun Smith resurfaces in UFL | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He contributed to the team winning the UFL Champsionship game against the [[Florida Tuskers]] on November 27.\n\n===Cincinnati Bengals (second stint)===\nSmith was re-signed by the Bengals on December 9, 2009.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/blog/afcnorth/post/_/id/6559/shaun-smith-returning-to-bengals | title=Shaun Smith returning to Bengals | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He was waived on December 12 and re-signed on December 16. He was not re-signed after the season.\n\n===Kansas City Chiefs (first stint)===\nSmith signed with the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] on March 10, 2010.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.columbian.com/news/2010/mar/10/chiefs-sign-defensive-tackle-shaun-smith/ | title=Chiefs sign defensive tackle Shaun Smith | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>  In consecutive weeks, he was accused by players from the opposing team of grabbing them in their private parts during play. [[Alex Mack]] of the [[Cleveland Browns]] made the first claim after the two teams' Week 2 matchup, followed by [[Anthony Davis (offensive tackle, born 1989)|Anthony Davis]] of the [[San Francisco 49ers]], who drew a penalty for retaliating against Smith in Week 3.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/5597659 | title=Alex Mack: Shaun Smith played dirty | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> Altough Smith denied both allegations, he was fined by the league.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/blog/afcwest/post/_/id/18035/report-chiefs-shaun-smith-fined | title=Report: Chiefs' Shaun Smith fined | website=ESPN | date=October 1, 2010 | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Tennessee Titans===\nOn July 29 of 2011, he signed with the [[Tennessee Titans]] a three-year, $7.25 million contract, to play as a [[defensive tackle]]. He scored his first career rushing touchdown on Week 12 against the [[Seattle Seahawks]]. He finished with 6 starts, 25 tackles and one sack.\n\nIn 2012, he showed up in training camp out of shape and underperformed. He was released on August 22.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/trainingcamp12/story/_/id/8292290/tennessee-titans-deep-dt-spot-release-veteran-shaun-smith | title=Titans release DT Shaun Smith | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Kansas City Chiefs (second stint)===\nOn November 5, 2012, he re-signed with the [[Kansas City Chiefs]], to serve as insurance in case [[Glenn Dorsey]] missed multiple games with a calf injury.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/8596859/kansas-chiefs-cut-stanford-routt-name-gary-gibbs-new-dc | title=Chiefs make changes on defense | accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref> He was not re-signed for the [[2013 NFL season|2013 season]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2009 Las Vegas Locomotives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Shaun}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American football defensive tackles]]\n[[Category:American football defensive ends]]\n[[Category:Butler Grizzlies football players]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Gamecocks football players]]\n[[Category:Dallas Cowboys players]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Bengals players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions players]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas Locomotives players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Titans players]]\n[[Category:Midwood High School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Geysirhead", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eKansas City Chiefs (first stint)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shaun_Smith_(defensive_lineman)"}
{"title_page": "Salah El Din Al Tijany", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Salah al-Din al-Tijani|2=Talk:Salah El Din Al Tijany#Requested move 18 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{BLP unsourced|date=April 2017}}{{Infobox religious biography\n|religion     = [[Islam]]\n|image        = Photo High Defintion.jpg\n|caption      = \n|name         = Salah El-Din Al-Tijani|native_name=\u0635\u0644\u0627\u062d \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0646\u064a\n|birth_date   = 25 [[Dhu al-Qi'dah]] 1377 [[Hijri year|AH]] <br/>{{birth-date and age|June 12, 1958}}\n|birth_place  = [[Cairo]]\n|ethnicity    = [[Arab]]\n|occupation   = [[Imam]], [[medical professor]], [[surgeon]]\n|denomination = [[Sunni Islam]]\n|creed        = [[Ash'ari]]\n|Sufi_order   = [[Tijani]]\n|Maddhab      = [[Maliki]]\n|influences   = [[Ahmad al-Tijani]], [[Abu al-Hasan al-Ash'ari]], [[Malik ibn Anas]], [[Ibn Hajar al-Asqalani]], [[al-Suyuti]]\n}}\n\n'''Salah El-Din Mahmud al-Tijani al-Hassani''' ({{lang-ar|\u0635\u0644\u0627\u062d \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u0646\u064a   |\u1e62al\u0101\u1e25 ad-D\u012bn Ma\u1e25m\u016bd al-Tij\u0101n\u012b al-\u1e24asan\u012b }}) is an Egyptian [[Imam]], [[Mujtahid]] and a specialist of [[Hadith]] affiliated to the [[Sunni]] [[Ash'ari]] theological school, the [[Maliki]] school of jurisprudence, and the [[Tijaniyyah|Tijani]] [[Tariqa]]. \n\nHe is also an orthopedic surgeon and Professor of Medicine at the Faculty of Medicine at the [[Qasr El Eyni Hospital]] in [[Cairo]].\n\n== Childhood and learning ==\n\n[[File:Embaba Zawiyah (Cairo).JPG|thumb|Imbaba Zawiyah (Cairo)]]\n\nHe was born June 12, 1958 in Cairo, in the district of Sayyeda Zaynab, within a family of descendants of the Prophet [[Muhammad]] through the lineage of Imam [[Hasan ibn Ali]]. His father, Imam Mahmud al-Hasani, was a scholar and teacher at [[al-Azhar]] University, and taught him the basics of Islamic knowledge, including the [[Quran]] and related sciences. Then at age 15, he performed his [[Hajj]] for the first time, and at 17, he obtained several diplomas and awards in the areas of [[tajwid]], [[tafsir]], [[hadith]] and [[Maliki]] [[fiqh]], and wrote several epistles on these subjects. At 18 years old, he saw the Prophet in a dream who ordered him to join the Tijani tariqa, then again at the age of 20, to build a [[Zawiya (institution)|Zawiyya]] that would enable everyone to learn and practice Islam peacefully. The latter is built in the district of [[Imbaba]] near [[Cairo]], and has an open access library for which Shaykh Salah El Din Al Tijany has striven to identify the great classics of literature, in order to share them with anyone who wishes, making a point that Muslim(s) are reclaiming the knowledge of their religion. It was officially opened on 1 Muharram 1400.\n\nOver the years, he became a master of Sunni jurisprudence in the [[Maliki]], [[Hanafi]], [[Shafi'i]] and [[Hanbali]] [[madhhab|madhhabs]] as well as mastering the legal opinions of the defunct madhabs, like that of [[Thawri|al-Thawri]], [[Awza'i|al-Awza'i]] and [[Zahiri|al-Zahiri]]. Eventually, becoming a [[ijtihad|mujtahid]], able to issue fatwa directly from the Quran and the [[Sunnah]].\n\n== His teachers ==\n\nHis principal teachers include illustrious :\n\n* Muhammad al-H\u0101fiz al-Tij\u0101n\u012b al-Misr\u012b al-Hasan\u012b (died 1978).\n* Abu-l-Fayd Muhammad Y\u0101s\u012bn Ibn Muhammad '\u012bs\u0101 al-F\u0101d\u0101n\u012b al-Makk\u012b (died 1990).\n* Ab\u016b Al 'Al\u0101' Idr\u012bs Ibn al-'\u0101bid al-'Ir\u0101q\u012b al-Husayn\u012b (died 2009).\n* 'Abdull\u0101h Ibn Muhammad Ibn as-Sidd\u012bq al-Ghum\u0101r\u012b al-Hasan\u012b (died 1993).\n* Ibr\u0101h\u012bm S\u0101lih Ibn Y\u016bnus al-Husayn\u012b.\n* Muhammad \u0101dam an-Nafad\u012b al-Tij\u0101n\u012b (died 2014).\n* Muhammad Ibn Ibr\u0101h\u012bm al-Mub\u0101rak al-M\u0101lik\u012b.\n* 'Abdus-Sal\u0101m an-Nabulus\u012b al-Sh\u0101fi'\u012b.\n* Ab\u016b Bakr al-Hanbal\u012b al-Ahs\u0101'\u012b.\n* Ahmad Ibn Muhammad ad-Dahlaw\u012b as-Sagh\u012br al-Hanaf\u012b.\n* Ahmad Ibn 'Abdal 'Az\u012bz Ibn Ahmad Ibn Muhammad az-Zayy\u0101t.\n* Ab\u016b Muhammad Ibn Ibr\u0101h\u012bm al-Hamadan\u012b.\n\n== His books ==\n\nShaykh Salah El Din Al Tijany is a prolific writer, having written books in various fields of science, some in several volumes containing a sum of several letters combined in one book. Among these there are:\n\n* Kun\u016bz al-Qur'\u0101n (3 vol.)\n* Tafs\u012br al-Qur'\u0101n al-Kar\u012bm an-Nash\u0101' (9 vol.)\n* Kun\u016bz al-\u1e24ad\u012bth (2 vol.)\n* al-Anf\u0101s min Kal\u0101m Sayyid an-N\u0101s (2 vol.)\n* An\u0101 Muhammad wa An\u0101 Ahmad (2 vol.)\n* Kun\u016bz al-'Asharah (10 vol.)\n* al-Lu'lu' Wa-l-Marj\u0101n f\u012b Tafs\u012br Is Sunnat al-Qur'\u0101n (3 vol.)\n* an-N\u016br F\u012b 'Aq\u012bdat Il Ak\u0101bir\n* Kun\u016bz al-Haq\u0101'iq (4 vol.)\n* Ashr\u0101t as-S\u0101'ah\n* Kun\u016bz al-Fiqh\n* Kun\u016bz al-Bal\u0101ghah\n* 'Az\u012bm Fadl Il Ummat al-Muhammadiyyah\n* Haw\u0101tif al-Haqq\n* Nahr an-N\u016br (2 vol.)\n* Rah\u012bq al-Makht\u016bm F\u012b Tar\u012bqat Il Qutb al-Makt\u016bm (5 vol.)\n* 'Ayn al-Hay\u0101t\n* D\u012bw\u0101n Sult\u0101n al-'\u0101shiq\u012bn 'Umar Ibn Al F\u0101rid\n* al-Kun\u016bz F\u012b Mas\u0101'il as-S\u016bfiyyah\n* Bahr al-Hubb\n* Maw\u0101kib al-Hubb\n* an-N\u016br F\u012b Tar\u012bqat al-Tij\u0101niyyah\n* Kun\u016bz al-Fiqh\n\nThe entirety of these books was posted on the website of Shaykh Salah El Din Al Tijany, and many of them are also published in paper format.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Sunnism]]\n* [[Ashari]]\n* [[Maliki]]\n* [[Sufism]]\n* [[Tijaniyyah]]\n\n== References ==\n* [http://imamsalah.com/ Website of Shaykh Sal\u00e2h Ud D\u00een At Tij\u00e2n\u00ee] ''(imamsalah.com - Arabic)''\n* [http://www.en.sheikhsalah.com/ Website of Shaykh Sal\u00e2h Ud D\u00een At Tij\u00e2n\u00ee] ''(sheikhsalah.com - English)''\n\n== External links ==\n* {{in lang|ar}} [http://sheikhsalah.com/ Website on Shaykh Sal\u00e2h Ud D\u00een At Tij\u00e2n\u00ee's works]\n{{Maliki scholars}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tijani, Salah Ud Din At}}\n[[Category:Sunni imams]]\n[[Category:21st-century Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:Islamic philosophers]]\n[[Category:Quranic exegesis scholars]]\n[[Category:Hadith scholars]]\n[[Category:Malikis]]\n[[Category:Egyptian Maliki scholars]]\n[[Category:Egyptian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Egyptian jurists]]\n[[Category:Egyptian writers]]\n[[Category:People from Cairo]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century imams]]\n[[Category:21st-century imams]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Salah al-Din al-Tijani|2=Talk:Salah El Din Al Tijany#Requested move 18 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{BLP unsourced|date=April 2017}}{{Infobox religious biography|religion=[[Islam]]\n|image = [[File:Photo High Defintion.jpg|thumb|Photo High Defintion]]\n|caption =Imam Salah El-Din Al-Tijani \n|name = '''Salah El-Din Al-Tijani'''<br/>'''\u0635\u0644\u0627\u062d \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0646\u064a'''\n|birth_date = 25 [[Dhu al-Qi'dah]] 1377 [[Hijri year|AH]] <br/>{{birth-date and age|June 12, 1958}}\n|birth_place      = [[Cairo]]\n|nationality = [[Egypt]]\n|ethnicity = [[Arab]]\n|occupation = [[Imam]], [[Medical Professor]], [[Surgeon]]\n|denomination     =[[Sunni Islam]]\n| creed= [[Ash'ari]]\n|Sufi_order = [[Tijani]]\n|Maddhab = [[Maliki]]\n|influences       = [[Ahmad al-Tijani]], [[Abu al-Hasan al-Ash'ari]], [[Malik ibn Anas]], [[Ibn Hajar al-Asqalani]], [[al-Suyuti]]\n}}\n\n'''Salah El-Din Mahmud al-Tijani al-Hassani''' ({{lang-ar|\u0635\u0644\u0627\u062d \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u0646\u064a   |\u1e62al\u0101\u1e25 ad-D\u012bn Ma\u1e25m\u016bd al-Tij\u0101n\u012b al-\u1e24asan\u012b }}) is an Egyptian [[Imam]], [[Mujtahid]] and a specialist of [[Hadith]] affiliated to the [[Sunni]] [[Ash'ari]] theological school, the [[Maliki]] school of jurisprudence, and the [[Tijaniyyah|Tijani]] [[Tariqa]]. \n\nHe is also an orthopedic surgeon and Professor of Medicine at the Faculty of Medicine at the [[Qasr El Eyni Hospital]] in [[Cairo]].\n\n== Childhood and Learning ==\n\n[[File:Embaba Zawiyah (Cairo).JPG|thumb|Imbaba Zawiyah (Cairo)]]\n\nHe was born June 12, 1958 in Cairo, in the district of Sayyeda Zaynab, within a family of descendants of the Prophet [[Muhammad]] through the lineage of Imam [[Hasan ibn Ali]]. His father, Imam Mahmud al-Hasani, was a scholar and teacher at [[al-Azhar]] University, and taught him the basics of Islamic knowledge, including the [[Quran]] and related sciences. Then at age 15, he performed his [[Hajj]] for the first time, and at 17, he obtained several diplomas and awards in the areas of [[tajwid]], [[tafsir]], [[hadith]] and [[Maliki]] [[fiqh]], and wrote several epistles on these subjects. At 18 years old, he saw the Prophet in a dream who ordered him to join the Tijani tariqa, then again at the age of 20, to build a [[Zawiya (institution)|Zawiyya]] that would enable everyone to learn and practice Islam peacefully. The latter is built in the district of [[Imbaba]] near [[Cairo]], and has an open access library for which Shaykh Salah El Din Al Tijany has striven to identify the great classics of literature, in order to share them with anyone who wishes, making a point that Muslim(s) are reclaiming the knowledge of their religion. It was officially opened on 1 Muharram 1400.\n\nOver the years, he became a master of Sunni jurisprudence in the [[Maliki]], [[Hanafi]], [[Shafi'i]] and [[Hanbali]] [[madhhab|madhhabs]] as well as mastering the legal opinions of the defunct madhabs, like that of [[Thawri|al-Thawri]], [[Awza'i|al-Awza'i]] and [[Zahiri|al-Zahiri]]. Eventually, becoming a [[ijtihad|mujtahid]], able to issue fatwa directly from the Quran and the [[Sunnah]].\n\n== His Teachers ==\n\nHis principal teachers include illustrious :\n\n* Muhammad al-H\u0101fiz al-Tij\u0101n\u012b al-Misr\u012b al-Hasan\u012b (died 1978).\n* Abu-l-Fayd Muhammad Y\u0101s\u012bn Ibn Muhammad '\u012bs\u0101 al-F\u0101d\u0101n\u012b al-Makk\u012b (died 1990).\n* Ab\u016b Al 'Al\u0101' Idr\u012bs Ibn al-'\u0101bid al-'Ir\u0101q\u012b al-Husayn\u012b (died 2009).\n* 'Abdull\u0101h Ibn Muhammad Ibn as-Sidd\u012bq al-Ghum\u0101r\u012b al-Hasan\u012b (died 1993).\n* Ibr\u0101h\u012bm S\u0101lih Ibn Y\u016bnus al-Husayn\u012b.\n* Muhammad \u0101dam an-Nafad\u012b al-Tij\u0101n\u012b (died 2014).\n* Muhammad Ibn Ibr\u0101h\u012bm al-Mub\u0101rak al-M\u0101lik\u012b.\n* 'Abdus-Sal\u0101m an-Nabulus\u012b al-Sh\u0101fi'\u012b.\n* Ab\u016b Bakr al-Hanbal\u012b al-Ahs\u0101'\u012b.\n* Ahmad Ibn Muhammad ad-Dahlaw\u012b as-Sagh\u012br al-Hanaf\u012b.\n* Ahmad Ibn 'Abdal 'Az\u012bz Ibn Ahmad Ibn Muhammad az-Zayy\u0101t.\n* Ab\u016b Muhammad Ibn Ibr\u0101h\u012bm al-Hamadan\u012b.\n\n== His books ==\n\nShaykh Salah El Din Al Tijany is a prolific writer, having written books in various fields of science, some in several volumes containing a sum of several letters combined in one book. Among these there are:\n\n* Kun\u016bz al-Qur'\u0101n (3 vol.)\n* Tafs\u012br al-Qur'\u0101n al-Kar\u012bm an-Nash\u0101' (9 vol.)\n* Kun\u016bz al-\u1e24ad\u012bth (2 vol.)\n* al-Anf\u0101s min Kal\u0101m Sayyid an-N\u0101s (2 vol.)\n* An\u0101 Muhammad wa An\u0101 Ahmad (2 vol.)\n* Kun\u016bz al-'Asharah (10 vol.)\n* al-Lu'lu' Wa-l-Marj\u0101n f\u012b Tafs\u012br Is Sunnat al-Qur'\u0101n (3 vol.)\n* an-N\u016br F\u012b 'Aq\u012bdat Il Ak\u0101bir\n* Kun\u016bz al-Haq\u0101'iq (4 vol.)\n* Ashr\u0101t as-S\u0101'ah\n* Kun\u016bz al-Fiqh\n* Kun\u016bz al-Bal\u0101ghah\n* 'Az\u012bm Fadl Il Ummat al-Muhammadiyyah\n* Haw\u0101tif al-Haqq\n* Nahr an-N\u016br (2 vol.)\n* Rah\u012bq al-Makht\u016bm F\u012b Tar\u012bqat Il Qutb al-Makt\u016bm (5 vol.)\n* 'Ayn al-Hay\u0101t\n* D\u012bw\u0101n Sult\u0101n al-'\u0101shiq\u012bn 'Umar Ibn Al F\u0101rid\n* al-Kun\u016bz F\u012b Mas\u0101'il as-S\u016bfiyyah\n* Bahr al-Hubb\n* Maw\u0101kib al-Hubb\n* an-N\u016br F\u012b Tar\u012bqat al-Tij\u0101niyyah\n* Kun\u016bz al-Fiqh\n\nThe entirety of these books was posted on the website of Shaykh Salah El Din Al Tijany, and many of them are also published in paper format.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Sunnism]]\n* [[Ashari]]\n* [[Maliki]]\n* [[Sufism]]\n* [[Tijaniyyah]]\n\n== References ==\n* [http://imamsalah.com/ Website of Shaykh Sal\u00e2h Ud D\u00een At Tij\u00e2n\u00ee] ''(imamsalah.com - Arabic)''\n* [http://www.en.sheikhsalah.com/ Website of Shaykh Sal\u00e2h Ud D\u00een At Tij\u00e2n\u00ee] ''(sheikhsalah.com - English)''\n\n== External links ==\n* {{in lang|ar}} [http://sheikhsalah.com/ Website on Shaykh Sal\u00e2h Ud D\u00een At Tij\u00e2n\u00ee's works]\n{{Maliki scholars}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tijani, Salah Ud Din At}}\n[[Category:Sunni imams]]\n[[Category:21st-century Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:Islamic philosophers]]\n[[Category:Quranic exegesis scholars]]\n[[Category:Hadith scholars]]\n[[Category:Malikis]]\n[[Category:Egyptian Maliki scholars]]\n[[Category:Egyptian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Egyptian jurists]]\n[[Category:Egyptian writers]]\n[[Category:People from Cairo]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century imams]]\n[[Category:21st-century imams]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salah_El_Din_Al_Tijany"}
{"title_page": "Selena Gomez & the Scene", "text_new": "[[File:3y24a9.gif|thumb|selena gomez showing off those cute toes and hot legs.]]\n{{pp-move-indef|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia: WikiProject Muiuiljuusicians -->\n| name       = Selena Gomez & the Scene\n| background = group_or_band\n| image      = Selena Gomez and the Scene.jpg\n| image_size = 250\n| landscape  = yes\n|caption     = Selena Gomez & the Scene performing on the [[We Own the Night Tour]] in September 2011. From left to right: [[Ethan Roberts]],\n[[Joey Clement]], and [[Selena Gomez]]\n| origin     = [[Hollywood]], [[California]], U.S.\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop rock]]\n* [[electropop]]\n* [[dance-pop]]}}\n| years_active = 2008\u20132012\n| label     = {{flat list|\n* [[Hollywood Records|Hollywood]]\n* [[Fascination Records|Fascination]]\n* [[Avex Group|Avex]]\n* [[Universal Music Group|Universal]]\n}}\n| website   = {{URL|selenagomez.com}}\n| former_members = \n* [[Selena Gomez]]\n* [[Joey Clement]]\n* Dane Forrest\n* Greg Garman\n* Drew Taubenfeld\n* [[Ethan Roberts]]\n* Nick Foxer\n}}\n\n'''Selena Gomez & the Scene''' was an American [[pop rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fusion.net/video/224314/selena-gomez-revival-interview-2015/|title=Selena Gomez talks Revival and what it's like to be a boss|work=[[Fusion (TV channel)|Fusion]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/108430-selena-gomez-talks-new-album-revival-it-sounds-like-it-could-be-her-most-personal|title=Selena Gomez Talks New Album 'Revival' & It Sounds Like It Could Be Her Most Personal Effort Yet\n|work=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2295623/selena-gomez-kmart-clothing-collection/|title=5 Pieces We Want From Selena Gomez's 'Dream Out Loud' Kmart Collection|work=[[MTV News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/music/concert-review-selena-gomez-the-scene-bell-centre-october-30|title=Concert Review: Selena Gomez & the Scene, Bell Centre, October 30|author=News Desk More News Desk|work=[[Montreal Gazette]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first= Emily |last= Goodman |title= Selena Gomez and the Scene rocked out together for more than three years |date= 12 November 2014 |publisher= [[AXS (ticket merchant)|AXS]] |url= http://www.axs.com/selena-gomez-and-the-scene-rocked-out-together-for-more-than-three-yea-27851 |accessdate= 31 October 2015}}</ref> band from [[Hollywood, California]]. Formed in 2008, its last lineup consisted of lead vocalist [[Selena Gomez]], bassist Joey Clement, drummer Greg Garman, keyboardist Dane Forrest, and guitarist Drew Taubenfeld. The band released three [[studio album]]s, seven [[single (music)|singles]] and nine music videos. Their debut album, ''[[Kiss & Tell (Selena Gomez & the Scene album)|Kiss & Tell]]'', was released on September 29, 2009, debuting at No. 9 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and earning the band a Gold certification from the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) in March 2010. The second single from the album, \"[[Naturally (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Naturally]]\", reached the top thirty in the U.S., as well as the top twenty in New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Ireland, Canada, and Germany. The song has been certified Platinum in the U.S. and Canada. As of 2012, ''Kiss & Tell'' has sold over 900,000 copies in the U.S.\n\nThe band's second album, ''[[A Year Without Rain]]'', was released on September 17, 2010, debuting at No. 4 on the U.S. ''Billboard 200'' and earning the band a second RIAA Gold certification in January 2011. Two singles were released from the album, \"[[Round & Round (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Round & Round]]\" and \"[[A Year Without Rain (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|A Year Without Rain]]\". As of 2012, the album has sold over 800,000 copies in the U.S.\n\nThe band's third album, ''[[When the Sun Goes Down (Selena Gomez & the Scene album)|When the Sun Goes Down]]'', was released on June 28, 2011,<ref name=\"jsyk. com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jsyk.com/2011/05/18/selena-gomez-interview/ |title=Selena Gomez Talks About 'Who Says' and Her Upcoming Tour (Video) |author=Cheung, Nadine |date=2011-05-18 |work=Just So You Know |publisher=[[AOL|Aol, Inc.]] |accessdate=2011-05-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723021143/http://www.cambio.com/2011/05/18/selena-gomez-interview/ |archive-date=2012-07-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> debuting at No. 4 on the U.S. ''Billboard 200''. Its lead single \"[[Who Says (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Who Says]]\" received its radio premiere on ''[[On Air with Ryan Seacrest (radio)|On Air with Ryan Seacrest]]'' on March 8, 2011, followed by a music video premiere on Disney Channel on March 11. The song has been certified Platinum in the U.S. The second single from the album, \"[[Love You like a Love Song]]\", was released on June 17, 2011 and was certified 4x Platinum in the U.S. The third and final single from the album was \"[[Hit the Lights (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Hit the Lights]]\".<ref name=\"ask billboard\">{{cite web|first=Gary|last=Trust|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/472033/ask-billboard-from-sm-to-disney-acts|title=Ask Billboard: From 'S&M' To Disney Acts |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=2011-04-15|accessdate=2011-04-17}}</ref> The band disbanded when Gomez began focusing on her acting career and solo music career.\n\nThe band has won numerous awards and accolades since their debut. They have won a total of four Poptastic Awards, including the Best Duo or Group Award. The band has also been nominated for five awards at the [[MuchMusic Video Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Iandoli |first=Kathy |url=http://idolator.com/6474141/2012-muchmusic-video-awards-justin-bieber-drake-carly-rae-jepsen |title=2012 MuchMusic Video Awards: Justin Bieber, Drake & Carly Rae Jepsen Score Nominations &#124; Music News, Reviews, and Gossip on |publisher=Idolator.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmva.muchmusic.com/tag/selena-gomez/ |title=Selena Gomez &#124; 2014 MMVAs |publisher=Mmva.muchmusic.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> and two [[MTV Europe Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Chris |last=Rogers |url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2012/09/17/ema-nominees-2012-nominations-mtv-europe-music-awards/ |title=2012 MTV Europe Music Awards Nominations \u2014 FULL List Of EMA Nominees |publisher=Hollywood Life |date=2012-09-17 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/09/17/mtv-europe-music-awards-nominations-rihanna_n_1889434.html |title=MTV Europe Music Awards: Rihanna Leads Nominations With Six Nods |publisher=Huffingtonpost.co.uk |date=2012-09-17 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> In 2011, the band won its first [[People's Choice Award]] for Breakout Group. In 2012, \"Love You Like a Love Song\" was nominated for an [[MTV Video Music Award]], giving the band their first VMA nomination.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1690827/video-music-awards-nominees-list-2012.jhtml |title=2012 VMA Nominations: The Complete List |publisher=MTV |date=2012-07-30 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=April |last=Chieffo |url=http://thecelebritycafe.com/feature/2012/07/selena-gomez-scores-her-first-vma-nomination |title=Selena Gomez scores her first VMA nomination |publisher=TheCelebrityCafe.com |date=2012-07-31 |accessdate=2015-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107185511/http://thecelebritycafe.com/feature/2012/07/selena-gomez-scores-her-first-vma-nomination |archivedate=2014-11-07 }}</ref> The band has also won a total of six [[Teen Choice Awards]] since 2010, including Choice Music: Group and Choice Music: Love Song for \"Love You like a Love Song\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1411125/awards|title=Selena Gomez: Awards|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-31749_162-57476951-10391698/teen-choice-awards-to-be-handed-out-this-weekend/ |title=Teen Choice Awards to be handed out this weekend |publisher=CBS News |date=2012-07-20 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===2008\u20132009: Formation===\n[[File:Selena Gomez and The Scene.png|thumb|right|The band's logo used for their debut album, ''Kiss & Tell'']]\nGomez first announced plans of forming a band in 2008, citing [[Paramore]] as an inspiration for the decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7B_Xg0ClSwQ |title=ep 4 band tryouts |publisher=YouTube |date=2009-09-28 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> In an interview with Jocelyn Vena of [[MTV News]], Gomez said: \"I'm going to be in a band. I'm not going to be a solo artist ... I don't want my name attached to it. I will be singing...\"<ref name=MTVband>{{cite web |first=Jocelyn |last=Vena |date=2009-08-07 |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1592286/20080806/id_0.jhtml |title=Selena Gomez forming a band |work=[[MTV|MTV.com]] |accessdate=2009-10-27}}</ref> Gomez later announced on Twitter that her band would be called The Scene,<ref name=\"Newsroom.mtv. com\">{{cite web |url=http://newsroom.mtv.com/2009/08/13/selena-gomez/ |title=Selena Gomez's the Scene And Six More Of The Most Boring Band Names Of All Time |publisher=MTV |date=2009-08-13 |accessdate=2010-03-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110908103157/http://newsroom.mtv.com/2009/08/13/selena-gomez/ |archivedate=2011-09-08 }}</ref> an \"ironic jab\" at people who called Gomez a \"wannabe [[Scene kids|scene]]\".<ref name=\"Newsroom.mtv. com\"/> Gomez stated that her label, [[Hollywood Records]], did not want her to have a band due to Gomez already having a \"fan base\", leading her to name the band Selena Gomez & the Scene to keep both herself and the label happy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7B_Xg0ClSwQ |title=YouTube \u2013 ep 4 band tryouts |publisher=Youtube.com |date=2009-09-28 |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1618671/selena-gomez-names-her-band-scene.jhtml |title=Selena Gomez Names Her Band The Scene |publisher=MTV |date=2009-08-13 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> In an interview with Z100 New York, Gomez stated that the band was formed through a long and exhausting audition process,<ref name=\"autogeneratedcc\">{{cite web |url=http://www.z100.com/cc-common/mediaplayer/player.html?redir=yes&mps=jj.php&mid=http://a1135.g.akamai.net/f/1135/18227/1h/cchannel.download.akamai.com/18227/podcast/NEWYORK-NY/WHTZ-FM/Selena%20int.mp3?CPROG=PCAST?CCOMRRMID&CPROG=RICHMEDIA&MARKET=NEWYORK-NY&NG_FORMAT=chr&NG_ID=whtz100fm&OR_NEWSFORMAT=&OWNER=&SERVER_NAME=www.z100.com&SITE_ID=1793&STATION_ID=WHTZ-FM&TRACK= |title=Media Player |publisher=Z100.com |accessdate=2015-02-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724062633/http://www.z100.com/cc-common/mediaplayer/player.html?redir=yes&mps=jj.php&mid=http%3A%2F%2Fa1135.g.akamai.net%2Ff%2F1135%2F18227%2F1h%2Fcchannel.download.akamai.com%2F18227%2Fpodcast%2FNEWYORK-NY%2FWHTZ-FM%2FSelena%20int.mp3%3FCPROG%3DPCAST%3FCCOMRRMID&CPROG=RICHMEDIA&MARKET=NEWYORK-NY&NG_FORMAT=chr&NG_ID=whtz100fm&OR_NEWSFORMAT=&OWNER=&SERVER_NAME=www.z100.com&SITE_ID=1793&STATION_ID=WHTZ-FM&TRACK= |archivedate=2011-07-24 }}</ref> saying: \"I would like all guys in the band. I'm looking for someone who's very passionate about music and can show me that they can rock out. I like having people with me to lean on and write with and have fun with.\"\n\nThe band's original line-up featured Gomez on vocals, Ethan Roberts on lead guitar and backing vocals, Greg Garman on drums, Joey Clement on bass guitar, and Nick Foxer on keyboard and backing vocals. Gomez posted a video of the audition and interview process for band members as the fourth episode of a vlog series on her official [[YouTube]] channel titled ''Under Pressure''. Shortly after the band was formed, Foxer left for unknown reasons, and was replaced by Dane Forrest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/selena-gomez|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022163412/http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/selena-gomez-the-scene|url-status=dead|title=Selena Gomez &#124; MTV UK|archivedate=October 22, 2012|website=Mtv.co.uk|accessdate=2020-03-28}}</ref> During a live performance for UNICEF in 2012, Gomez confirmed that Ethan Roberts would be leaving the group to pursue solo projects, with Gomez wishing him luck.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://anythingdiz.livejournal.com/6190809.html?thread=932235225 |title=AnythingDiz - Selena Arriving at the UNICEF Charity Concert |publisher=Anythingdiz.livejournal.com |date=2012-01-21 |accessdate=2015-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129024730/http://anythingdiz.livejournal.com/6190809.html?thread=932235225 |archivedate=2016-01-29 }}</ref> He was replaced with Drew Taubenfeld that same year, though Taubenfeld does not provide backing vocals like Roberts did.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://celebcenter.us/drew-taubenfeld/ |title=Drew Taubenfeld &#124; Official celebrity websites &#124; Facebook, Twitter, Youtube, fan page, website |publisher=Celebcenter.us |accessdate=2015-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303224053/http://celebcenter.us/drew-taubenfeld/ |archivedate=2016-03-03 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/selena-gomez |title=Selena Gomez: Information from |publisher=Answers.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> The group has also featured various back-up singers during tours, including [[YouTube]] star [[Christina Grimmie]], who toured with Gomez & the Scene in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1665684/selena-gomez-christina-grimmie-tour.jhtml |title=Selena Gomez Is 'Doing Well', Says Tour Opener Christina Grimmie |publisher=MTV |date=2011-06-13 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2011/06/15/selena-gomez-christina-grimmie-style/ |title=Selena Gomez Tourmate Christina Grimmie Is Punk Rock Stylish |publisher=Hollywoodcrush.mtv.com |date=2011-06-15 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref>\n\n===2009\u20132010: ''Kiss & Tell'' and ''A Year Without Rain''===\nThe band's debut studio album, ''[[Kiss & Tell (Selena Gomez & the Scene album)|Kiss & Tell]]'', was released on September 29, 2009. It includes collaborations with writers and producers such as [[Gina Schock]] of the [[Go-Go's]] and [[Rock Mafia]]. Predominantly a [[pop rock]] album, ''Kiss & Tell'' also incorporates a combination of other styles, including [[dance music]].<ref name=\"amazon1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B001QXE0OC |title=Kiss and Tell: Selena Gomez and the Scene: Music|website=Amazon.com |accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> Being compared to releases by fellow [[Disney]] stars [[Miley Cyrus]] and [[Demi Lovato]],<ref name=\"digitalspy.com\">{{cite web|last=Copsey |first=Robert |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/albumreviews/a216152/selena-gomez--the-scene-kiss--tell.html |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene: 'Kiss & Tell' - Music Review |publisher=Digital Spy |date=2010-04-25 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> the album was met with mixed reception, with some critics praising the album for its \"fun\" nature, and others criticizing Gomez's vocal performance.<ref>{{cite web|first=Michael |last=Slezak |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20307626,00.html |title=Kiss & Tell &#124; Music |publisher=EW.com |date=September 23, 2009 |accessdate=June 19, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nochelatina.com/Articles/5729/Selena-Gomez-Kiss-and-Tell-Album-Review|title=Selena Gomez Kiss & Tell review |publisher=Nochelatina.com |accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Released on Monday, April 19, 2010 |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/albumreviews/a216152/selena-gomez--the-scene-kiss--tell.html |title=Music \u2013 Album Review \u2013 Selena Gomez & The Scene: 'Kiss & Tell' |publisher=Digital Spy |date=April 19, 2010 |accessdate=June 19, 2010}}</ref> ''Kiss & Tell'' debuted at number 9 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] in the US.<ref name=\"CHART info billboard. com\">{{cite web|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|author2=Herrera, Monica |title=Barbra Streisand Surprises With Ninth No. 1 On Billboard 200|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/267159/barbra-streisand-surprises-with-ninth-no-1-on-billboard-200|date=2009-10-07|accessdate=2009-10-07}}</ref> It was later certified [[Gold certification|Gold]] in the country for sales exceeding 500,000 copies.<ref name=\"RIAA Gold Platinum\">{{cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=selena%20gomez%20&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=8&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |title=Riaa \u2013 Gold & Platinum |publisher=Riaa.com |accessdate=2011-09-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924152637/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=selena%20gomez%20&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=8&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |archivedate=2015-09-24 }}</ref> It was successful in other territories as well, entering the Top 10 in Greece and Poland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/album/50959 |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene - Kiss And Tell - Music Charts |publisher=Acharts.us |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> as well as entering the Top 20 in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://greekcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Selena+Gomez+%26+The+Scene&titel=Kiss+%26+Tell&cat=a |title=SELENA GOMEZ & THE SCENE - KISS & TELL (ALBUM) |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024111523/http://greekcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Selena+Gomez+&+The+Scene&titel=Kiss+&+Tell&cat=a |archive-date=October 24, 2012 |url-status=dead |access-date=January 31, 2013}}</ref> To promote the album, Gomez & the Scene made numerous televised performances on shows such as season nine of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'',<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://neonlimelight.com/2009/09/29/selena-gomez-the-scene-perform-on-dancing-with-the-stars-results-show/ |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene Perform On Dancing With The Stars Results Show &#124; Neon Limelight \u2013 Exclusive Music News, Artist Interviews, Reviews, Photos! |publisher=Neon Limelight |date=2009-09-29 |accessdate=2010-05-29}}</ref> ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'',<ref name=\"performance discussed\">{{cite web|url=http://ellen.warnerbros.com/2009/12/selena_gomez_the_scene_1211.php?adid=selena_gomez_the_scene_1211_sphere_ellen|title=Watch Selena Gomez & The Scene Perform \"Naturally\" -- and More!|publisher=Warner Bros|work=The Ellen DeGeneres Show|date=2009-12-11<!-- 6:00 AM -->|accessdate=2010-01-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308122341/http://ellen.warnerbros.com/2009/12/selena_gomez_the_scene_1211.php?adid=selena_gomez_the_scene_1211_sphere_ellen|archive-date=2012-03-08|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"actual performance\">{{cite web|url=http://ellen.warnerbros.com/music/selena-gomez.php|title=Ellen's Music: Selena Gomez|publisher=Warner Bros|work=The Ellen DeGeneres Show|date=2009-12-11<!-- this date as mentioned in prior reference -->|accessdate=2010-01-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116174232/http://ellen.warnerbros.com/music/selena-gomez.php|archive-date=2010-01-16|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latenightwithjimmyfallon.com/video/selena-gomez-interview-21210/1201192/ |title=Selena Gomez Interview (2/12/10) - Video - NBC.com |publisher=Late Night with Jimmy Fallon |accessdate=2010-05-29}}</ref> and ''[[Dick Clark's New Year's Rockin' Eve with Ryan Seacrest]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nt2099.com/J-ENT/news/american-entertainment/dick-clarks-new-years-rockin-eve-1231/ |title=DICK CLARK'S NEW YEAR'S ROCKIN' EVE (12/31): J!-ENT entertainment news pop culture TV music DVD Blu-ray reviews fashion celebrity USA Asia UK |publisher=Nt2099.com |date=2009-12-08 |accessdate=2010-03-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104224050/http://www.nt2099.com/J-ENT/news/american-entertainment/dick-clarks-new-years-rockin-eve-1231/ |archivedate=2010-01-04 }}</ref> among other shows. The band also promoted the album with the concert tour, [[Selena Gomez & the Scene: Live in Concert]].<ref name=\"myspace1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.myspace.com/selenagomez |title=Selena Gomez op MySpace Music \u2013 Gratis gestreamde MP3's, foto's en Videoclips |publisher=Myspace.com |date=1992-07-22 |accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> The band also contributed to [[Radio Disney|Disney's]] ''[[All Wrapped Up Vol. 2]]''. The EP includes the band's cover of \"Winter Wonderland\" as well as Christmas covers by other successful artists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B002SQJ3ZW |title=All Wrapped Up, Vol. 2: Jordan Pruitt, Jesse McCartney, Jonas Brothers, Honor Society, Selena Gomez & The Scene, Steve Rushton, Anna Margaret: Music |accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref>\n\nThe band's [[lead single]], \"[[Falling Down (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Falling Down]]\" had minor commercial success, peaking at number 82 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/song/49198 |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene \u2013 Falling Down \u2013 Music Charts |publisher=Acharts.us |accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/falling-down-single/id332070884 |title=iTunes - Music - Falling Down - Single by Selena Gomez & The Scene |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=September 22, 2009 |accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Falling-Down/dp/B002LRKJII ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091121114043/http://www.amazon.com/Falling-Down/dp/B002LRKJII |date=November 21, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/song/49198 |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene \u2013 Falling Down \u2013 Music Charts |publisher=Acharts.us |accessdate=March 14, 2010}}</ref> The music video premiered after the world premiere of Gomez' TV-movie ''[[Wizards of Waverly Place: The Movie]]'' on August 28, 2009. The single was described as being \"pop-rock\" by Bill Lamb of [[About.com]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://top40.about.com/od/singles/gr/selenagomezfallingdown.htm |title=Selena Gomez and the Scene - Falling Down - Review of the Falling Down Single by Selena Gomez |publisher=Top40.about.com |date=2009-09-29 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> while [[Digital Spy]] compared it to music released by American singer [[Pink (singer)|Pink]].<ref name=\"digitalspy.com\"/> Their single \"Falling Down\" was featured on ''[[Radio Disney Jams, Vol. 12]]'', along with songs by other popular artists. ''Jams 12'' was officially released on March 30, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0038M61CS |title=Radio Disney Jams 12: Various Artists: Music|website=Amazon.com |accessdate=2010-05-29}}</ref> The second single from the album, \"Naturally\" was released on December 11, 2009 along with a music video for digital download. The music video was shot on November 14, 2009 and premiered on [[Disney Channel]] following the premiere of ''[[Phineas and Ferb Christmas Vacation]]'' on December 11, 2009. The single debuted at number 39 and later peaked at number 29 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and has peaked at number 18 on the [[Canadian Hot 100]]. It is the band's biggest hit to date and first top 40<!-- industry usage term is \"top 40\" --> hit beating out their first single \"Falling Down\" and also their first number 1 hit on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Dance Club Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/song/52715 |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene - Naturally - Music Charts |publisher=Acharts.us |accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> \"Naturally\" had its highest peak in Hungary where it peaked at number 4 on the singles chart, becoming the band's first top five hit anywhere in the world. On July 15, 2010, the single was certified Platinum by the RIAA for sales of 1,000,000 in the US.<ref name=\"RIAA Gold Platinum\"/>\n\n[[File:Selena Gomez December 2010 3.jpg|thumb|right|Selena Gomez & the Scene performing live at KISS 108 Jingle Ball December 2010]]\nFollowing the success of ''Kiss & Tell'', work on the band's second studio album began in 2010. The finished product, ''[[A Year Without Rain]]'', was released on September 17, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empik.com/year-without-rain-pl-gomez-selena,prod58634942,muzyka-p|title=Year Without Rain PL Wykonawca: Gomez Selena Data|language=Polish|accessdate=2010-09-21}}</ref> The album continues the [[dance-pop]]/[[electropop]] style of the group's hit single \"Naturally\". \"I think we wanted to do something a little fun. We wanted to do a techno vibe, \" said lead singer Selena Gomez. Gomez said in an interview with Z100 New York<ref name=\"autogeneratedcc\"/> that it would feature some songs that did not make it onto the first album and that the rest of the band would be much more included on it. In an interview with MTV, Gomez said, \"I'm really proud of this record, it's very different, and kind of shows [our] growth a little bit in music... I think if anything the lyrics are more powerful, in a way.\" The record was dedicated to her fans to thank them for their support.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/1068589/selena-gomez-the-scene-a-year-without-rain|title = Selena Gomez & The Scene: A Year without Rain|date = October 1, 2010|accessdate = October 4, 2015|website = Billboard |last = Vick|first = Megan}}</ref> It debuted on the US ''Billboard'' 200 at number 4 with sales of a little over 66,000, barely selling more than ''Kiss & Tell''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/956020/zac-brown-band-bows-at-no-1-on-billboard-200 |title=Zac Brown Band Bows At No. 1 on Billboard 200 |magazine=Billboard |date=2010-09-29 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> Much like the band's previous album, ''A Year Without Rain'' was certified Gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] for sales exceeding 500,000 copies in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=selena%20gomez%20&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=8&startYear=2009&endYear=2011&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |title=Gold & Platinum Searchable Database - February 19, 2015 |publisher=RIAA |accessdate=2015-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725004244/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=selena+gomez+&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=8&startYear=2009&endYear=2011&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |archivedate=July 25, 2013 }}</ref> The album received a mixed to positive reviews where some noticed that Gomez's vocals contain the [[Auto-Tune]] effect.<ref name=\"clothinglinemtv\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.washingtonpost.com/clicktrack/2010/09/album_review_selena_gomez_a_ye.html |title=Album review: Selena Gomez, \"A Year Without Rain\" |first=Allison |last=Stewart |work=[[Washington Post]] |accessdate=September 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511205242/http://blog.washingtonpost.com/clicktrack/2010/09/album_review_selena_gomez_a_ye.html |archivedate=May 11, 2012 }}</ref> The record's two singles both receiving moderate success.<ref name=\"US release\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/round-round-single/id376899592 |title=Round & Round&nbsp;\u2013 Single by Selena Gomez & the Scene |work=[[iTunes Store|iTunes]] |accessdate=June 30, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626032510/http://itunes.apple.com/us/album/round-round-single/id376899592 |archivedate=June 26, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"US Digital\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/a-year-without-rain-single/id387935992 |title=A Year Without Rain&nbsp;\u2013 Single by Selena Gomez & the Scene |work=[[iTunes Store|iTunes]] |accessdate=September 16, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100910084649/http://itunes.apple.com/us/album/a-year-without-rain-single/id387935992 |archivedate=September 10, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> The record's first single, \"Round & Round\", premiered on June 18, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oceanup.com/2010/05/26/selena-gomez-round-and-round |title=Selena Gomez ROUND AND ROUND |publisher=oceanUP.com |accessdate=2010-05-29}}</ref> The accompanying music video, which was filmed in Budapest, premiered two days later.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.twitvid.com/TGCOF |title=Selena Gomez \u2013 Selena Gomez \u2013 Round & Round Sneakpeak 3 |publisher=TwitVid |accessdate=2010-09-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621132646/http://www.twitvid.com/TGCOF |archivedate=2010-06-21 }}</ref> The single was released on June 22, 2010. The song has been certified Gold in the United States by the Recording Industry Association of America for shipments of 500,000 copies.<ref name=\"US release\"/> It debuted at number 24 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, and 76 on the Canadian Hot 100. It also debuted at number 15 on the ''Billboard'' Hot Digital Songs chart<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=selena gomez|chart=all}}|title=Top 100 Music Hits, Top 100 Music Charts, Top 100 Songs & The Hot 100|magazine=Billboard.com|date=|accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> and at number 47 in the UK. The album's second single and title track \"A Year Without Rain\" was released on September 7, 2010. The music video premiered on September 3, 2010, after the world premiere of ''[[Camp Rock 2: The Final Jam]]''. The Spanish version of \"A Year Without Rain\" (\"Un A\u00f1o Sin Lluvia\") was released three months after the English version. On July 13, Selena Gomez & the Scene's song \"[[Live Like There's No Tomorrow (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Live Like There's No Tomorrow]]\" was released as a single from the movie ''[[Ramona and Beezus]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/live-like-theres-no-tomorrow/id380017649 |title=Live Like There's No Tomorrow (From \"Ramona and Beezus\") - Single by Selena Gomez & The Scene \u2013 Download Live Like There's No Tomorrow (From \"Ramona and Beezus\") \u2013 Single on iTunes |publisher=Itunes. apple.com |date=2010-07-13 |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> The song is also a track on ''A Year Without Rain''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B003YCI1PM/ |title=A Year Without Rain: Selena Gomez & The Scene: Music|website=Amazon.com |date=2009-09-09 |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B003Y66MTA/ |title=A Year Without Rain [Deluxe Edition&#93;: Selena Gomez & The Scene: Music|website=Amazon.com |date=2009-09-09 |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> Despite the success of the film, the song failed to chart on any major charts worldwide. As of 2012, the album has sold an estimated 609,000 copies in the United States, according to ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/features/selena-gomez-the-billboard-cover-story-1005227022.story?page=2#/features/selena-gomez-the-billboard-cover-story-1005227022.story?page=2 |title=Selena Gomez: The Billboard Cover Story |magazine=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref>\n\nThe album and subsequent singles were promoted mainly through televised performances and concert tours, much like with their previous album. Gomez & the Scene performed \"Round & Round\" live on shows such as ''[[America's Got Talent]]'',<ref>{{cite web |last=Reiher |first=Andrea |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/07/americas-got-talent-welcomes-selena-gomez-rock-of-ages-special-guest.html |title='America's Got Talent' welcomes Selena Gomez, 'Rock of Ages', special guest - Zap2it &#124; News & Features |publisher=Blog.zap2it.com |date=2010-07-13 |accessdate=2015-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917060208/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/07/americas-got-talent-welcomes-selena-gomez-rock-of-ages-special-guest.html |archivedate=2010-09-17 }}</ref> ''[[Blue Peter]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Iandoli |first=Kathy |url=http://idolator.com/5639711/selena-gomez-blue-peter |title=Selena Gomez Answers Some Kiddie Questions On 'Blue Peter' &#124; Music News, Reviews, and Gossip on |publisher=Idolator.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> ''[[Daybreak (2010 TV programme)|Daybreak]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/daybreak/ |title=Good Morning Britain &#124; GMB |publisher=Itv.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> and MTV's ''The Seven'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2010/10/01/selena-gomez-round-and-round-the-7-mtv/ |title=VIDEO: Selena Gomez Performs 'Round & Round' On MTV's 'The Seven' |publisher=Buzzworthy.mtv.com |date=2010-10-01 |accessdate=2015-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226215804/http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2010/10/01/selena-gomez-round-and-round-the-7-mtv/ |archivedate=2014-12-26 }}</ref> while performing \"A Year Without Rain\" on ''[[Good Morning America]]'', ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latina.com/entertainment/music/selena-gomezs-new-album-year-without-rain-drops-today |title=Selena Gomezs New Album A Year Without Rain Drops Today! |publisher=Latina.com |date=2010-09-21 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> and ''[[Lopez Tonight]]'' among other shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lopeztonight.com/episode_recaps_and_highlights/selena_gomez_sings.php |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722082823/http://www.lopeztonight.com/episode_recaps_and_highlights/selena_gomez_sings.php |archivedate=2011-07-22 |title=Selena Gomez Really Has Had a Year Without Rain &#124; Lopez Tonight |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> On October 27, 2010, the band played an acoustic set for charity ([[UNICEF]]). They were also part of the [[KIIS-FM Jingle Ball|Jingle Ball]] tour during December.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bostonherald.com/entertainment/music/general/view/20101210pop-happy_jingle_ball_rocks/srvc=home&position=also |title=Pop-happy Jingle Ball rocks |author=Carter, Lauren |date=10 December 2010 |work=[[Boston Herald]] |publisher=Herald Media Inc. |accessdate=5 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112170638/http://news.bostonherald.com/entertainment/music/general/view/20101210pop-happy_jingle_ball_rocks/srvc%3Dhome%26position%3Dalso |archivedate=12 January 2012 }}</ref> In 2011, the band performed \"A Year Without Rain\" and won Favorite Breakout Artist on the [[37th People's Choice Awards|Peoples Choice Awards]], against [[Justin Bieber]].<ref name=\"37th PCA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.peopleschoice.com/pca/awards/nominees/index.jsp|title=People's Choice Awards 2011 Nominees & Winners|publisher=People's Choice Awards|accessdate=2011-01-18}}</ref> The album was further promoted through the band's [[A Year Without Rain Tour]], which was both critically and commercially successful. During a backstage interview, Gomez remarked that she was conceptualizing the tour as far as stage and production and promised an amazing show with an \"epic\" stage for 2011.<ref>{{cite video|people=[[Selena Gomez|Gomez, Selena]] |title=Selena Gomez backstage with JJ |url=http://www.z100.com/pages/events/jingle-ball/2010.html?uri=channels/449656/1106113 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703205432/http://www.z100.com/pages/events/jingle-ball/2010.html?uri=channels%2F449656%2F1106113 |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 July 2013 |publisher=[[WHTZ]] |location=[[New York City]] |accessdate=5 January 2011 |time=2:09 }}</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132012: ''When the Sun Goes Down'', hiatus, and disbandment===\n[[File:Selena Gomez 3, 2011.jpg|thumb|200px|Selena Gomez & The Scene at [[We Own the Night Tour]] in 2011|left]]\nOn February 15, 2011, [[Hollywood Records]] confirmed that a new album was in the works.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/UniversalMusicPortugal#!/UniversalMusicPortugal/posts/179076442135107 |title=F\u00e3s da Selena Gomez |publisher=Facebook.com |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref><ref name=\"ryanseacrest. com\"/> Though the album was initially titled ''Otherside'',<ref name=\"jsyk. com\"/> it was later changed to ''[[When the Sun Goes Down (Selena Gomez & the Scene album)|When the Sun Goes Down]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/Selena |title=Selena Gomez |publisher=Facebook |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref> the album was released on June 28, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/canadianpress/article/ALeqM5iOXDtATkNTvatj0wY0UaySBveStw?docId=6864258 |title=Selena Gomez says she's starting a new chapter, now that 'Wizards' has wrapped |author=Baillie, Andrea|agency=[[Canadian Press Enterprises Inc.|The Canadian Press]] |date=2011-05-17 |accessdate=2011-05-19}}</ref> The album expanded on the pop and dance elements found on the band's last album, and features a more electropop and synthpop sound.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tim |last=Sendra |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/when-the-sun-goes-down-mw0002152176 |title=When the Sun Goes Down - Selena Gomez,Selena Gomez & the Scene &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date=2011-06-28 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref><ref name=\"top40.about.com\">{{cite web|url=http://top40.about.com/od/albums/fr/Selena-Gomez-And-The-Scene-When-The-Sun-Goes-Down.htm |title=Selena Gomez and the Scene - When the Sun Goes Down |publisher=Top40.about.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20355856_20504533,00.html | work=Entertainment Weekly | title=Music Review: When the Sun Goes Down, by Selena Gomez | date=2011-07-10}}</ref> The album also explores organic instrumentation.<ref name=\"Sendra\">{{cite web|last=Sendra |first=Tim |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/when-the-sun-goes-down-r2204393 |title=When the Sun Goes Down - Selena Gomez & the Scene |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=2011-06-30}}</ref> The sound of the album was compared to recent releases by artists such as [[Kelly Clarkson]] among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/selena-gomez-talks-when-the-sun-goes-down-1005253192.story#/news/selena-gomez-talks-when-the-sun-goes-down-1005253192.story |title=Selena Gomez Talks 'When the Sun Goes Down': Video Track-By-Track |magazine=Billboard |accessdate=2015-02-19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626032143/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/469719/selena-gomez-talks-when-the-sun-goes-down-video-track-by-track|archivedate=2015-06-26}}</ref> ''When the Sun Goes Down'' featured writing credits from writers and producers such as pop icon [[Britney Spears]],<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1661743/britney-spears-selena-gomez.jhtml |title=Britney Spears Penned Track For Selena Gomez |publisher=MTV |date=2011-11-04 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> pop singer [[Katy Perry]],<ref name=\"top40.about.com\"/> and [[Rock Mafia]], among others. The album received a mixed reviews<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/when-the-sun-goes-down-2011 |title=When the Sun Goes Down Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More at Metacritic |publisher=Metacritic.com |date= |accessdate=December 1, 2011}}</ref> with the album's second single receiving a 4x Platinum certification from the RIAA.,<ref name=\"RIAA Platinum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=selena%20gomez%20&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=8&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=Artist&perPage=25|title=RIAA - Gold & Platinum Searchable Database - November 01, 2015|work=riaa.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924152637/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=selena%20gomez%20&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=8&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=Artist&perPage=25|archivedate=September 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/when-the-sun-goes-down-2011 |title=Reviews for When the Sun Goes Down by Selena Gomez |publisher=Metacritic |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> The record debuted at number 4 on the ''Billboard'' 200 with sales of 78,000 copies in its first week of release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/469358/beyonce-notches-4th-billboard-200-no-1-with-4 |title=Beyonce Notches 4th Billboard 200 No. 1 with '4' |magazine=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jordan |first=Chris |url=http://www.sheknows.com/entertainment/articles/835589/selena-gomez-posts-best-album-debut-numbers-of-career |title=Selena Gomez posts best album debut numbers of career |publisher=Sheknows.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> This marked the highest first week sales for the band to date, outselling their first two albums by nearly 12,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wete |first=Brad |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2011/07/06/beyonce-4-billboard-200-chart/ |title=Beyonce tops Billboard albums chart - but marks her lowest debut as a solo star &#124; EW.com |publisher=Music-mix.ew.com |date=2011-07-06 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> As of 2012, ''When the Sun Goes Down'' has sold an estimated 642,000 copies in the US alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474163/selena-gomezs-next-album-due-in-march |title=Selena Gomez's Next Album Due In March |magazine=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref>\n\nThe album's lead single \"Who Says\" had its world premiere on ''[[On Air with Ryan Seacrest (radio)|On Air with Ryan Seacrest]]'' on March 8. The accompanying music video, which was directed by Chris Applebaum, premiered on [[VEVO]] March 11.<ref name=\"ryanseacrest. com\">{{cite web|url=http://ryanseacrest.com/2011/02/23/selena-gomez-to-world-premiere-new-single-who-says-with-ryan-seacrest/ |title=Selena Gomez To World Premiere New Single 'Who Says' with Ryan Seacrest |website=Ryanseacrest.com |date=2011-02-23 |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref> The single follows in succession of other self-empowerment singles such as \"[[Firework (song)|Firework]]\" by [[Katy Perry]], \"[[Fuckin' Perfect]]\" by [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], and \"[[Born This Way (song)|Born This Way]]\" by [[Lady Gaga]].<ref name=\"Vena2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1660139/selena-gomez-who-says.jhtml|title=Selena Gomez 'Inspired' By Latest Single, 'Who Says'|work=[[MTV News]]|publisher=MTV. [[MTV Networks]]|accessdate=2011-03-17|date=2011-03-17|first=Jocelyn|last=Vena}}</ref> \"Who Says\" was a critical success but was only successful in US, receiving a moderate success worldwide, becoming the band's highest peaking song on the Hot 100 chart to date, where it peaked at number 21.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/song/selena-gomez-the-scene/who-says/143752160#/song/selena-gomez-the-scene/who-says/25590983Z] {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The song has also been certified Platinum by the RIAA, becoming their second single to achieve this feat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |title=Recording Industry Association of America |publisher=RIAA |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref> On May 28, Gomez announced on her official Twitter that one of the songs from the album, \"[[Bang Bang Bang (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Bang Bang Bang]]\" would be released as part of an iTunes album countdown on June 7, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/americantop40?ref=ts#!/americantop40?sk=app_11007063052 |title=American Top 40 |publisher=Facebook |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref> Gomez later announced in an interview that the second single from the album would be \"[[Love You Like a Love Song]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dose.ca/music/4709734/story.html |title=Q&A: 2011 MMVAs Co-Host Selena Gomez |author=Collins, Leah |date=2011-05-02 |work=[[Dose (magazine)|Dose]] |publisher=[[Postmedia Network]] |accessdate=2011-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120630030706/http://www.dose.ca/music/4709734/story.html |archivedate=2012-06-30 }}</ref> The song was serviced to [[contemporary hit radio]] airplay on August 16, 2011 in the United States.<ref name=\"airplay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239 |title=Airplay Archive |work=[[FMQB]] |publisher=Friday Morning Quarterback Album Report, Inc. and Mediaspan Online Services |accessdate=2011-11-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602195200/http://fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239 |archivedate=2013-06-02 }}</ref> The single later went on to become the band's highest performing single in the U.S. to date, where it peaked at number 22 on the Hot 100 chart, their second highest peaking single to date.<ref name=\"music.yahoo.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007014705/http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/week-ending-july-10-2011-songs-rolling-over-everybody.html|title=Week Ending July 10, 2011. Songs: Rolling Over Everybody &#124; Chart Watch - Archives - Yahoo! Music|date=October 7, 2012|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=2020-03-28}}</ref> The song became their highest charting single on the [[Pop Songs]] chart based on radio airplay, where it peaked at No. 6.<ref name=\"music.yahoo.com\"/> The single was later certified 4x Platinum in the U.S., making it the band's first song to achieve this feat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?artist=%22Love+You+Like+a+Love+Song%22 |title=Gold & Platinum Searchable Database - February 19, 2015 |publisher=RIAA |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> \"[[Hit the Lights (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Hit the Lights]]\" was released as the third and final single in 2012, but it failed to have much success. On March 23, 2011, [[Hollywood Records]] announced the [[We Own the Night Tour]], which began on July 24, 2011<ref>{{cite press release |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene Announce Summer Headline Tour |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/selena-gomez--the-scene-announce-summer-headline-tour-118517139.html |publisher=PR Newswire |date=2011-03-23 |accessdate=2011-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/scene-stealer-selena-gomez-co-hosts-and-performs-at-the-2011-muchmusic-video-awards-live-sunday-june-19-at-9-pm-et-121075789.html |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] |date=2011-05-02 |title=Scene Stealer Selena Gomez Co-Hosts and Performs at The 2011 MUCHMUSIC VIDEO AWARDS, Live Sunday, June 19 at 9 p. m. ET |accessdate=2011-05-07 \n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110505063220/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/scene-stealer-selena-gomez-co-hosts-and-performs-at-the-2011-muchmusic-video-awards-live-sunday-june-19-at-9-pm-et-121075789.html |url-status=live |archivedate=2011-05-05}}</ref> and ended on February 11, 2012.\n\nIn January 7, 2012, Gomez announced that the band was on hiatus and that they would not release a new album in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Collins|first=Leah|title=Selena Gomez takes 'a break' from music|url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/Selena+Gomez+takes+break+from+music/5962976/story.html|work=[[Vancouver Sun]]|accessdate=February 12, 2012|date=January 7, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215091441/http://www.vancouversun.com/entertainment/Selena%2BGomez%2Btakes%2Bbreak%2Bfrom%2Bmusic/5962976/story.html|archivedate=February 15, 2012}}</ref> On July 22, 2012, Selena Gomez & the Scene won \"Choice Music: Group\" for the third time in a row at the [[2012 Teen Choice Awards]].<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20613936,00.html \"Selena Gomez Celebrates 20th Birthday with a Win at Teen Choice Awards\"]. ''People''. July 22, 2012.</ref> As of 2020, the band has not reformed to release any new material, with Selena Gomez focusing solely on her solo career.\n\n==Members==\n<!-- NOTE: They are on a \"hiatus\" right now NOT a break-up. Do not put all the current band-members as \"Formers\" please. They didn't disband. -->\n\n;Final line-up\n* [[Selena Gomez]] \u2013 [[Lead vocalist|lead vocals]] (2008\u20132012)\n* Greg Garman \u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boomdrum.com/artist-feature/artist-feature-greg-garman-selena-gomez-scene |title=Artist Feature: Greg Garman of Selena Gomez and the Scene |publisher=Boom Drum |date=2010-03-23 |accessdate=2010-09-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208114225/http://boomdrum.com/artist-feature/artist-feature-greg-garman-selena-gomez-scene |archivedate=2010-12-08 }}</ref> (2008\u20132012)\n* [[Joey Clement]] \u2013 [[bass guitar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.takamine.com/?fa=artist&id=977 |title=Takamine Guitars |publisher=Takamine.com |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref> (2008\u20132012)\n* Drew Taubenfeld \u2013 [[lead guitar]] (2012)\n* Dane Forrest \u2013 [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]] (2008\u20132012)\n\n;Former members\n* Nick Foxer \u2013 [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Idolator |url=http://soundmaven.com/artist/Selena%2BGomez%2B%2526%2BThe%2BScene/ |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene |publisher=soundmaven.com |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> (2008\u20132009)\n* [[Ethan Roberts]] \u2013 [[lead guitar]], backing vocals<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.takamine.com/?fa=artist&id=974 |title=Takamine Guitars |publisher=Takamine.com |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref> (2008\u20132012)\n\n;Touring members\n* Lindsey Harper \u2013 [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]] (2010\u20132012)\n* Katelyn Clampett \u2013 backing vocals (2011\u20132012)\n* Ashleigh Haney \u2013 backing vocals (2011)\n* [[Christina Grimmie]] \u2013 backing vocals (2010\u20132011)\n\n===Timeline===\n{{Empty section|date=February 2019|section=}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Selena Gomez & the Scene discography}}\n\n* ''[[Kiss & Tell (Selena Gomez & the Scene album)|Kiss & Tell]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[A Year Without Rain]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[When the Sun Goes Down (Selena Gomez & the Scene album)|When the Sun Goes Down]]'' (2011)\n\n==Tours==\n* [[Selena Gomez & the Scene: Live in Concert|Live in Concert]] (2009\u20132010)\n* [[A Year Without Rain Tour]] (2010\u20132011)\n* [[We Own the Night Tour]] (2011\u20132012)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{See also|List of awards and nominations received by Selena Gomez}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Association\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Work\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2010\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Music: Group\n| rowspan=\"5\"|Selena Gomez & the Scene\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Choice Music: Breakout Artist\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n|[[MTV Europe Music Awards]]\n|Best Push Act\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\" | 2011\n| [[Kids' Choice Awards Argentina]]\n| Favorite International Singer\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[People's Choice Awards]]\n| [[People's Choice Award for Favorite Breakout Artist|Favorite Breakout Artist]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[MuchMusic Video Awards]]\n|International Video of the Year \u2013 Artist\n|rowspan=\"3\"|\"[[A Year Without Rain (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|A Year Without Rain]]\"\n|rowspan=3 {{nom}}\n|-\n|Ur Fave International Video\n|-\n|MuchMusic.com Most Watched Video of the Year\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[2011 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Music: Group\n|Selena Gomez & The Scene\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Choice Music: Single\n| [[Who Says (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Who Says]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Music - Love Song#2010s|Choice Music: Love Song]]\n| [[Love You like a Love Song]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"9\"|2012\n|[[MuchMusic Video Awards]]\n|International Video of the Year \u2013 Group\n|[[Love You like a Love Song]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[2012 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Music: Group\n| Selena Gomez & the Scene\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Choice Music: Single by a Group\n| [[Hit the Lights]]\n| rowspan=3 {{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Kids' Choice Awards Mexico]]\n|Canci\u00f3n Favorita\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Love You like a Love Song]]\n|-\n|[[MTV Video Music Awards]]\n|Best Female Video\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Vevo Certified]] Awards\n|rowspan=\"4\"|Vevo Certified 100 Million Views\n|\"[[Naturally (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Naturally]]\"\n|rowspan=4 {{won}}\n|-\n|\"[[A Year Without Rain (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|A Year Without Rain]]\"\n|-\n|\"[[Who Says (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Who Says]]\"\n|-\n|\"[[Love You like a Love Song]]\"\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of artists who reached number one on the U.S. dance chart]]\n* [[List of artists who reached number one on the U.S. dance airplay chart]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Selena Gomez & the Scene}}\n{{Selena Gomez}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Selena Gomez and The Scene}}\n[[Category:Selena Gomez & the Scene| ]]\n[[Category:Selena Gomez]]\n[[Category:American pop rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Hollywood Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language singers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2012]]\n[[Category:Electropop groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-indef|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia: WikiProject Muiuiljuusicians -->\n| name       = Selena Gomez & the Scene\n| background = group_or_band\n| image      = Selena Gomez and the Scene.jpg\n| image_size = 250\n| landscape  = yes\n|caption     = Selena Gomez & the Scene performing on the [[We Own the Night Tour]] in September 2011. From left to right: [[Ethan Roberts]],\n[[Joey Clement]], and [[Selena Gomez]]\n| origin     = [[Hollywood]], [[California]], U.S.\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop rock]]\n* [[electropop]]\n* [[dance-pop]]}}\n| years_active = 2008\u20132012\n| label     = {{flat list|\n* [[Hollywood Records|Hollywood]]\n* [[Fascination Records|Fascination]]\n* [[Avex Group|Avex]]\n* [[Universal Music Group|Universal]]\n}}\n| website   = {{URL|selenagomez.com}}\n| former_members = \n* [[Selena Gomez]]\n* [[Joey Clement]]\n* Dane Forrest\n* Greg Garman\n* Drew Taubenfeld\n* [[Ethan Roberts]]\n* Nick Foxer\n}}\n\n'''Selena Gomez & the Scene''' was an American [[pop rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fusion.net/video/224314/selena-gomez-revival-interview-2015/|title=Selena Gomez talks Revival and what it's like to be a boss|work=[[Fusion (TV channel)|Fusion]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/108430-selena-gomez-talks-new-album-revival-it-sounds-like-it-could-be-her-most-personal|title=Selena Gomez Talks New Album 'Revival' & It Sounds Like It Could Be Her Most Personal Effort Yet\n|work=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2295623/selena-gomez-kmart-clothing-collection/|title=5 Pieces We Want From Selena Gomez's 'Dream Out Loud' Kmart Collection|work=[[MTV News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/music/concert-review-selena-gomez-the-scene-bell-centre-october-30|title=Concert Review: Selena Gomez & the Scene, Bell Centre, October 30|author=News Desk More News Desk|work=[[Montreal Gazette]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first= Emily |last= Goodman |title= Selena Gomez and the Scene rocked out together for more than three years |date= 12 November 2014 |publisher= [[AXS (ticket merchant)|AXS]] |url= http://www.axs.com/selena-gomez-and-the-scene-rocked-out-together-for-more-than-three-yea-27851 |accessdate= 31 October 2015}}</ref> band from [[Hollywood, California]]. Formed in 2008, its last lineup consisted of lead vocalist [[Selena Gomez]], bassist Joey Clement, drummer Greg Garman, keyboardist Dane Forrest, and guitarist Drew Taubenfeld. The band released three [[studio album]]s, seven [[single (music)|singles]] and nine music videos. Their debut album, ''[[Kiss & Tell (Selena Gomez & the Scene album)|Kiss & Tell]]'', was released on September 29, 2009, debuting at No. 9 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and earning the band a Gold certification from the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) in March 2010. The second single from the album, \"[[Naturally (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Naturally]]\", reached the top thirty in the U.S., as well as the top twenty in New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Ireland, Canada, and Germany. The song has been certified Platinum in the U.S. and Canada. As of 2012, ''Kiss & Tell'' has sold over 900,000 copies in the U.S.\n\nThe band's second album, ''[[A Year Without Rain]]'', was released on September 17, 2010, debuting at No. 4 on the U.S. ''Billboard 200'' and earning the band a second RIAA Gold certification in January 2011. Two singles were released from the album, \"[[Round & Round (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Round & Round]]\" and \"[[A Year Without Rain (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|A Year Without Rain]]\". As of 2012, the album has sold over 800,000 copies in the U.S.\n\nThe band's third album, ''[[When the Sun Goes Down (Selena Gomez & the Scene album)|When the Sun Goes Down]]'', was released on June 28, 2011,<ref name=\"jsyk. com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jsyk.com/2011/05/18/selena-gomez-interview/ |title=Selena Gomez Talks About 'Who Says' and Her Upcoming Tour (Video) |author=Cheung, Nadine |date=2011-05-18 |work=Just So You Know |publisher=[[AOL|Aol, Inc.]] |accessdate=2011-05-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723021143/http://www.cambio.com/2011/05/18/selena-gomez-interview/ |archive-date=2012-07-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> debuting at No. 4 on the U.S. ''Billboard 200''. Its lead single \"[[Who Says (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Who Says]]\" received its radio premiere on ''[[On Air with Ryan Seacrest (radio)|On Air with Ryan Seacrest]]'' on March 8, 2011, followed by a music video premiere on Disney Channel on March 11. The song has been certified Platinum in the U.S. The second single from the album, \"[[Love You like a Love Song]]\", was released on June 17, 2011 and was certified 4x Platinum in the U.S. The third and final single from the album was \"[[Hit the Lights (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Hit the Lights]]\".<ref name=\"ask billboard\">{{cite web|first=Gary|last=Trust|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/472033/ask-billboard-from-sm-to-disney-acts|title=Ask Billboard: From 'S&M' To Disney Acts |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=2011-04-15|accessdate=2011-04-17}}</ref> The band disbanded when Gomez began focusing on her acting career and solo music career.\n\nThe band has won numerous awards and accolades since their debut. They have won a total of four Poptastic Awards, including the Best Duo or Group Award. The band has also been nominated for five awards at the [[MuchMusic Video Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Iandoli |first=Kathy |url=http://idolator.com/6474141/2012-muchmusic-video-awards-justin-bieber-drake-carly-rae-jepsen |title=2012 MuchMusic Video Awards: Justin Bieber, Drake & Carly Rae Jepsen Score Nominations &#124; Music News, Reviews, and Gossip on |publisher=Idolator.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmva.muchmusic.com/tag/selena-gomez/ |title=Selena Gomez &#124; 2014 MMVAs |publisher=Mmva.muchmusic.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> and two [[MTV Europe Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Chris |last=Rogers |url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2012/09/17/ema-nominees-2012-nominations-mtv-europe-music-awards/ |title=2012 MTV Europe Music Awards Nominations \u2014 FULL List Of EMA Nominees |publisher=Hollywood Life |date=2012-09-17 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/09/17/mtv-europe-music-awards-nominations-rihanna_n_1889434.html |title=MTV Europe Music Awards: Rihanna Leads Nominations With Six Nods |publisher=Huffingtonpost.co.uk |date=2012-09-17 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> In 2011, the band won its first [[People's Choice Award]] for Breakout Group. In 2012, \"Love You Like a Love Song\" was nominated for an [[MTV Video Music Award]], giving the band their first VMA nomination.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1690827/video-music-awards-nominees-list-2012.jhtml |title=2012 VMA Nominations: The Complete List |publisher=MTV |date=2012-07-30 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=April |last=Chieffo |url=http://thecelebritycafe.com/feature/2012/07/selena-gomez-scores-her-first-vma-nomination |title=Selena Gomez scores her first VMA nomination |publisher=TheCelebrityCafe.com |date=2012-07-31 |accessdate=2015-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107185511/http://thecelebritycafe.com/feature/2012/07/selena-gomez-scores-her-first-vma-nomination |archivedate=2014-11-07 }}</ref> The band has also won a total of six [[Teen Choice Awards]] since 2010, including Choice Music: Group and Choice Music: Love Song for \"Love You like a Love Song\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1411125/awards|title=Selena Gomez: Awards|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-31749_162-57476951-10391698/teen-choice-awards-to-be-handed-out-this-weekend/ |title=Teen Choice Awards to be handed out this weekend |publisher=CBS News |date=2012-07-20 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===2008\u20132009: Formation===\n[[File:Selena Gomez and The Scene.png|thumb|right|The band's logo used for their debut album, ''Kiss & Tell'']]\nGomez first announced plans of forming a band in 2008, citing [[Paramore]] as an inspiration for the decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7B_Xg0ClSwQ |title=ep 4 band tryouts |publisher=YouTube |date=2009-09-28 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> In an interview with Jocelyn Vena of [[MTV News]], Gomez said: \"I'm going to be in a band. I'm not going to be a solo artist ... I don't want my name attached to it. I will be singing...\"<ref name=MTVband>{{cite web |first=Jocelyn |last=Vena |date=2009-08-07 |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1592286/20080806/id_0.jhtml |title=Selena Gomez forming a band |work=[[MTV|MTV.com]] |accessdate=2009-10-27}}</ref> Gomez later announced on Twitter that her band would be called The Scene,<ref name=\"Newsroom.mtv. com\">{{cite web |url=http://newsroom.mtv.com/2009/08/13/selena-gomez/ |title=Selena Gomez's the Scene And Six More Of The Most Boring Band Names Of All Time |publisher=MTV |date=2009-08-13 |accessdate=2010-03-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110908103157/http://newsroom.mtv.com/2009/08/13/selena-gomez/ |archivedate=2011-09-08 }}</ref> an \"ironic jab\" at people who called Gomez a \"wannabe [[Scene kids|scene]]\".<ref name=\"Newsroom.mtv. com\"/> Gomez stated that her label, [[Hollywood Records]], did not want her to have a band due to Gomez already having a \"fan base\", leading her to name the band Selena Gomez & the Scene to keep both herself and the label happy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7B_Xg0ClSwQ |title=YouTube \u2013 ep 4 band tryouts |publisher=Youtube.com |date=2009-09-28 |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1618671/selena-gomez-names-her-band-scene.jhtml |title=Selena Gomez Names Her Band The Scene |publisher=MTV |date=2009-08-13 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> In an interview with Z100 New York, Gomez stated that the band was formed through a long and exhausting audition process,<ref name=\"autogeneratedcc\">{{cite web |url=http://www.z100.com/cc-common/mediaplayer/player.html?redir=yes&mps=jj.php&mid=http://a1135.g.akamai.net/f/1135/18227/1h/cchannel.download.akamai.com/18227/podcast/NEWYORK-NY/WHTZ-FM/Selena%20int.mp3?CPROG=PCAST?CCOMRRMID&CPROG=RICHMEDIA&MARKET=NEWYORK-NY&NG_FORMAT=chr&NG_ID=whtz100fm&OR_NEWSFORMAT=&OWNER=&SERVER_NAME=www.z100.com&SITE_ID=1793&STATION_ID=WHTZ-FM&TRACK= |title=Media Player |publisher=Z100.com |accessdate=2015-02-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724062633/http://www.z100.com/cc-common/mediaplayer/player.html?redir=yes&mps=jj.php&mid=http%3A%2F%2Fa1135.g.akamai.net%2Ff%2F1135%2F18227%2F1h%2Fcchannel.download.akamai.com%2F18227%2Fpodcast%2FNEWYORK-NY%2FWHTZ-FM%2FSelena%20int.mp3%3FCPROG%3DPCAST%3FCCOMRRMID&CPROG=RICHMEDIA&MARKET=NEWYORK-NY&NG_FORMAT=chr&NG_ID=whtz100fm&OR_NEWSFORMAT=&OWNER=&SERVER_NAME=www.z100.com&SITE_ID=1793&STATION_ID=WHTZ-FM&TRACK= |archivedate=2011-07-24 }}</ref> saying: \"I would like all guys in the band. I'm looking for someone who's very passionate about music and can show me that they can rock out. I like having people with me to lean on and write with and have fun with.\"\n\nThe band's original line-up featured Gomez on vocals, Ethan Roberts on lead guitar and backing vocals, Greg Garman on drums, Joey Clement on bass guitar, and Nick Foxer on keyboard and backing vocals. Gomez posted a video of the audition and interview process for band members as the fourth episode of a vlog series on her official [[YouTube]] channel titled ''Under Pressure''. Shortly after the band was formed, Foxer left for unknown reasons, and was replaced by Dane Forrest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/selena-gomez|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022163412/http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/selena-gomez-the-scene|url-status=dead|title=Selena Gomez &#124; MTV UK|archivedate=October 22, 2012|website=Mtv.co.uk|accessdate=2020-03-28}}</ref> During a live performance for UNICEF in 2012, Gomez confirmed that Ethan Roberts would be leaving the group to pursue solo projects, with Gomez wishing him luck.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://anythingdiz.livejournal.com/6190809.html?thread=932235225 |title=AnythingDiz - Selena Arriving at the UNICEF Charity Concert |publisher=Anythingdiz.livejournal.com |date=2012-01-21 |accessdate=2015-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129024730/http://anythingdiz.livejournal.com/6190809.html?thread=932235225 |archivedate=2016-01-29 }}</ref> He was replaced with Drew Taubenfeld that same year, though Taubenfeld does not provide backing vocals like Roberts did.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://celebcenter.us/drew-taubenfeld/ |title=Drew Taubenfeld &#124; Official celebrity websites &#124; Facebook, Twitter, Youtube, fan page, website |publisher=Celebcenter.us |accessdate=2015-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303224053/http://celebcenter.us/drew-taubenfeld/ |archivedate=2016-03-03 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/selena-gomez |title=Selena Gomez: Information from |publisher=Answers.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> The group has also featured various back-up singers during tours, including [[YouTube]] star [[Christina Grimmie]], who toured with Gomez & the Scene in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1665684/selena-gomez-christina-grimmie-tour.jhtml |title=Selena Gomez Is 'Doing Well', Says Tour Opener Christina Grimmie |publisher=MTV |date=2011-06-13 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2011/06/15/selena-gomez-christina-grimmie-style/ |title=Selena Gomez Tourmate Christina Grimmie Is Punk Rock Stylish |publisher=Hollywoodcrush.mtv.com |date=2011-06-15 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref>\n\n===2009\u20132010: ''Kiss & Tell'' and ''A Year Without Rain''===\nThe band's debut studio album, ''[[Kiss & Tell (Selena Gomez & the Scene album)|Kiss & Tell]]'', was released on September 29, 2009. It includes collaborations with writers and producers such as [[Gina Schock]] of the [[Go-Go's]] and [[Rock Mafia]]. Predominantly a [[pop rock]] album, ''Kiss & Tell'' also incorporates a combination of other styles, including [[dance music]].<ref name=\"amazon1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B001QXE0OC |title=Kiss and Tell: Selena Gomez and the Scene: Music|website=Amazon.com |accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> Being compared to releases by fellow [[Disney]] stars [[Miley Cyrus]] and [[Demi Lovato]],<ref name=\"digitalspy.com\">{{cite web|last=Copsey |first=Robert |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/albumreviews/a216152/selena-gomez--the-scene-kiss--tell.html |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene: 'Kiss & Tell' - Music Review |publisher=Digital Spy |date=2010-04-25 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> the album was met with mixed reception, with some critics praising the album for its \"fun\" nature, and others criticizing Gomez's vocal performance.<ref>{{cite web|first=Michael |last=Slezak |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20307626,00.html |title=Kiss & Tell &#124; Music |publisher=EW.com |date=September 23, 2009 |accessdate=June 19, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nochelatina.com/Articles/5729/Selena-Gomez-Kiss-and-Tell-Album-Review|title=Selena Gomez Kiss & Tell review |publisher=Nochelatina.com |accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Released on Monday, April 19, 2010 |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/albumreviews/a216152/selena-gomez--the-scene-kiss--tell.html |title=Music \u2013 Album Review \u2013 Selena Gomez & The Scene: 'Kiss & Tell' |publisher=Digital Spy |date=April 19, 2010 |accessdate=June 19, 2010}}</ref> ''Kiss & Tell'' debuted at number 9 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] in the US.<ref name=\"CHART info billboard. com\">{{cite web|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|author2=Herrera, Monica |title=Barbra Streisand Surprises With Ninth No. 1 On Billboard 200|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/267159/barbra-streisand-surprises-with-ninth-no-1-on-billboard-200|date=2009-10-07|accessdate=2009-10-07}}</ref> It was later certified [[Gold certification|Gold]] in the country for sales exceeding 500,000 copies.<ref name=\"RIAA Gold Platinum\">{{cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=selena%20gomez%20&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=8&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |title=Riaa \u2013 Gold & Platinum |publisher=Riaa.com |accessdate=2011-09-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924152637/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=selena%20gomez%20&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=8&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |archivedate=2015-09-24 }}</ref> It was successful in other territories as well, entering the Top 10 in Greece and Poland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/album/50959 |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene - Kiss And Tell - Music Charts |publisher=Acharts.us |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> as well as entering the Top 20 in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://greekcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Selena+Gomez+%26+The+Scene&titel=Kiss+%26+Tell&cat=a |title=SELENA GOMEZ & THE SCENE - KISS & TELL (ALBUM) |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024111523/http://greekcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Selena+Gomez+&+The+Scene&titel=Kiss+&+Tell&cat=a |archive-date=October 24, 2012 |url-status=dead |access-date=January 31, 2013}}</ref> To promote the album, Gomez & the Scene made numerous televised performances on shows such as season nine of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'',<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://neonlimelight.com/2009/09/29/selena-gomez-the-scene-perform-on-dancing-with-the-stars-results-show/ |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene Perform On Dancing With The Stars Results Show &#124; Neon Limelight \u2013 Exclusive Music News, Artist Interviews, Reviews, Photos! |publisher=Neon Limelight |date=2009-09-29 |accessdate=2010-05-29}}</ref> ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'',<ref name=\"performance discussed\">{{cite web|url=http://ellen.warnerbros.com/2009/12/selena_gomez_the_scene_1211.php?adid=selena_gomez_the_scene_1211_sphere_ellen|title=Watch Selena Gomez & The Scene Perform \"Naturally\" -- and More!|publisher=Warner Bros|work=The Ellen DeGeneres Show|date=2009-12-11<!-- 6:00 AM -->|accessdate=2010-01-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308122341/http://ellen.warnerbros.com/2009/12/selena_gomez_the_scene_1211.php?adid=selena_gomez_the_scene_1211_sphere_ellen|archive-date=2012-03-08|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"actual performance\">{{cite web|url=http://ellen.warnerbros.com/music/selena-gomez.php|title=Ellen's Music: Selena Gomez|publisher=Warner Bros|work=The Ellen DeGeneres Show|date=2009-12-11<!-- this date as mentioned in prior reference -->|accessdate=2010-01-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116174232/http://ellen.warnerbros.com/music/selena-gomez.php|archive-date=2010-01-16|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latenightwithjimmyfallon.com/video/selena-gomez-interview-21210/1201192/ |title=Selena Gomez Interview (2/12/10) - Video - NBC.com |publisher=Late Night with Jimmy Fallon |accessdate=2010-05-29}}</ref> and ''[[Dick Clark's New Year's Rockin' Eve with Ryan Seacrest]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nt2099.com/J-ENT/news/american-entertainment/dick-clarks-new-years-rockin-eve-1231/ |title=DICK CLARK'S NEW YEAR'S ROCKIN' EVE (12/31): J!-ENT entertainment news pop culture TV music DVD Blu-ray reviews fashion celebrity USA Asia UK |publisher=Nt2099.com |date=2009-12-08 |accessdate=2010-03-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104224050/http://www.nt2099.com/J-ENT/news/american-entertainment/dick-clarks-new-years-rockin-eve-1231/ |archivedate=2010-01-04 }}</ref> among other shows. The band also promoted the album with the concert tour, [[Selena Gomez & the Scene: Live in Concert]].<ref name=\"myspace1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.myspace.com/selenagomez |title=Selena Gomez op MySpace Music \u2013 Gratis gestreamde MP3's, foto's en Videoclips |publisher=Myspace.com |date=1992-07-22 |accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> The band also contributed to [[Radio Disney|Disney's]] ''[[All Wrapped Up Vol. 2]]''. The EP includes the band's cover of \"Winter Wonderland\" as well as Christmas covers by other successful artists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B002SQJ3ZW |title=All Wrapped Up, Vol. 2: Jordan Pruitt, Jesse McCartney, Jonas Brothers, Honor Society, Selena Gomez & The Scene, Steve Rushton, Anna Margaret: Music |accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref>\n\nThe band's [[lead single]], \"[[Falling Down (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Falling Down]]\" had minor commercial success, peaking at number 82 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/song/49198 |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene \u2013 Falling Down \u2013 Music Charts |publisher=Acharts.us |accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/falling-down-single/id332070884 |title=iTunes - Music - Falling Down - Single by Selena Gomez & The Scene |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=September 22, 2009 |accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Falling-Down/dp/B002LRKJII ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091121114043/http://www.amazon.com/Falling-Down/dp/B002LRKJII |date=November 21, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/song/49198 |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene \u2013 Falling Down \u2013 Music Charts |publisher=Acharts.us |accessdate=March 14, 2010}}</ref> The music video premiered after the world premiere of Gomez' TV-movie ''[[Wizards of Waverly Place: The Movie]]'' on August 28, 2009. The single was described as being \"pop-rock\" by Bill Lamb of [[About.com]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://top40.about.com/od/singles/gr/selenagomezfallingdown.htm |title=Selena Gomez and the Scene - Falling Down - Review of the Falling Down Single by Selena Gomez |publisher=Top40.about.com |date=2009-09-29 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> while [[Digital Spy]] compared it to music released by American singer [[Pink (singer)|Pink]].<ref name=\"digitalspy.com\"/> Their single \"Falling Down\" was featured on ''[[Radio Disney Jams, Vol. 12]]'', along with songs by other popular artists. ''Jams 12'' was officially released on March 30, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0038M61CS |title=Radio Disney Jams 12: Various Artists: Music|website=Amazon.com |accessdate=2010-05-29}}</ref> The second single from the album, \"Naturally\" was released on December 11, 2009 along with a music video for digital download. The music video was shot on November 14, 2009 and premiered on [[Disney Channel]] following the premiere of ''[[Phineas and Ferb Christmas Vacation]]'' on December 11, 2009. The single debuted at number 39 and later peaked at number 29 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and has peaked at number 18 on the [[Canadian Hot 100]]. It is the band's biggest hit to date and first top 40<!-- industry usage term is \"top 40\" --> hit beating out their first single \"Falling Down\" and also their first number 1 hit on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Dance Club Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/song/52715 |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene - Naturally - Music Charts |publisher=Acharts.us |accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> \"Naturally\" had its highest peak in Hungary where it peaked at number 4 on the singles chart, becoming the band's first top five hit anywhere in the world. On July 15, 2010, the single was certified Platinum by the RIAA for sales of 1,000,000 in the US.<ref name=\"RIAA Gold Platinum\"/>\n\n[[File:Selena Gomez December 2010 3.jpg|thumb|right|Selena Gomez & the Scene performing live at KISS 108 Jingle Ball December 2010]]\nFollowing the success of ''Kiss & Tell'', work on the band's second studio album began in 2010. The finished product, ''[[A Year Without Rain]]'', was released on September 17, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empik.com/year-without-rain-pl-gomez-selena,prod58634942,muzyka-p|title=Year Without Rain PL Wykonawca: Gomez Selena Data|language=Polish|accessdate=2010-09-21}}</ref> The album continues the [[dance-pop]]/[[electropop]] style of the group's hit single \"Naturally\". \"I think we wanted to do something a little fun. We wanted to do a techno vibe, \" said lead singer Selena Gomez. Gomez said in an interview with Z100 New York<ref name=\"autogeneratedcc\"/> that it would feature some songs that did not make it onto the first album and that the rest of the band would be much more included on it. In an interview with MTV, Gomez said, \"I'm really proud of this record, it's very different, and kind of shows [our] growth a little bit in music... I think if anything the lyrics are more powerful, in a way.\" The record was dedicated to her fans to thank them for their support.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/1068589/selena-gomez-the-scene-a-year-without-rain|title = Selena Gomez & The Scene: A Year without Rain|date = October 1, 2010|accessdate = October 4, 2015|website = Billboard |last = Vick|first = Megan}}</ref> It debuted on the US ''Billboard'' 200 at number 4 with sales of a little over 66,000, barely selling more than ''Kiss & Tell''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/956020/zac-brown-band-bows-at-no-1-on-billboard-200 |title=Zac Brown Band Bows At No. 1 on Billboard 200 |magazine=Billboard |date=2010-09-29 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> Much like the band's previous album, ''A Year Without Rain'' was certified Gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] for sales exceeding 500,000 copies in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=selena%20gomez%20&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=8&startYear=2009&endYear=2011&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |title=Gold & Platinum Searchable Database - February 19, 2015 |publisher=RIAA |accessdate=2015-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725004244/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=selena+gomez+&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=8&startYear=2009&endYear=2011&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |archivedate=July 25, 2013 }}</ref> The album received a mixed to positive reviews where some noticed that Gomez's vocals contain the [[Auto-Tune]] effect.<ref name=\"clothinglinemtv\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.washingtonpost.com/clicktrack/2010/09/album_review_selena_gomez_a_ye.html |title=Album review: Selena Gomez, \"A Year Without Rain\" |first=Allison |last=Stewart |work=[[Washington Post]] |accessdate=September 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511205242/http://blog.washingtonpost.com/clicktrack/2010/09/album_review_selena_gomez_a_ye.html |archivedate=May 11, 2012 }}</ref> The record's two singles both receiving moderate success.<ref name=\"US release\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/round-round-single/id376899592 |title=Round & Round&nbsp;\u2013 Single by Selena Gomez & the Scene |work=[[iTunes Store|iTunes]] |accessdate=June 30, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626032510/http://itunes.apple.com/us/album/round-round-single/id376899592 |archivedate=June 26, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"US Digital\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/a-year-without-rain-single/id387935992 |title=A Year Without Rain&nbsp;\u2013 Single by Selena Gomez & the Scene |work=[[iTunes Store|iTunes]] |accessdate=September 16, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100910084649/http://itunes.apple.com/us/album/a-year-without-rain-single/id387935992 |archivedate=September 10, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> The record's first single, \"Round & Round\", premiered on June 18, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oceanup.com/2010/05/26/selena-gomez-round-and-round |title=Selena Gomez ROUND AND ROUND |publisher=oceanUP.com |accessdate=2010-05-29}}</ref> The accompanying music video, which was filmed in Budapest, premiered two days later.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.twitvid.com/TGCOF |title=Selena Gomez \u2013 Selena Gomez \u2013 Round & Round Sneakpeak 3 |publisher=TwitVid |accessdate=2010-09-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621132646/http://www.twitvid.com/TGCOF |archivedate=2010-06-21 }}</ref> The single was released on June 22, 2010. The song has been certified Gold in the United States by the Recording Industry Association of America for shipments of 500,000 copies.<ref name=\"US release\"/> It debuted at number 24 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, and 76 on the Canadian Hot 100. It also debuted at number 15 on the ''Billboard'' Hot Digital Songs chart<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=selena gomez|chart=all}}|title=Top 100 Music Hits, Top 100 Music Charts, Top 100 Songs & The Hot 100|magazine=Billboard.com|date=|accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> and at number 47 in the UK. The album's second single and title track \"A Year Without Rain\" was released on September 7, 2010. The music video premiered on September 3, 2010, after the world premiere of ''[[Camp Rock 2: The Final Jam]]''. The Spanish version of \"A Year Without Rain\" (\"Un A\u00f1o Sin Lluvia\") was released three months after the English version. On July 13, Selena Gomez & the Scene's song \"[[Live Like There's No Tomorrow (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Live Like There's No Tomorrow]]\" was released as a single from the movie ''[[Ramona and Beezus]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/live-like-theres-no-tomorrow/id380017649 |title=Live Like There's No Tomorrow (From \"Ramona and Beezus\") - Single by Selena Gomez & The Scene \u2013 Download Live Like There's No Tomorrow (From \"Ramona and Beezus\") \u2013 Single on iTunes |publisher=Itunes. apple.com |date=2010-07-13 |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> The song is also a track on ''A Year Without Rain''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B003YCI1PM/ |title=A Year Without Rain: Selena Gomez & The Scene: Music|website=Amazon.com |date=2009-09-09 |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B003Y66MTA/ |title=A Year Without Rain [Deluxe Edition&#93;: Selena Gomez & The Scene: Music|website=Amazon.com |date=2009-09-09 |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> Despite the success of the film, the song failed to chart on any major charts worldwide. As of 2012, the album has sold an estimated 609,000 copies in the United States, according to ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/features/selena-gomez-the-billboard-cover-story-1005227022.story?page=2#/features/selena-gomez-the-billboard-cover-story-1005227022.story?page=2 |title=Selena Gomez: The Billboard Cover Story |magazine=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref>\n\nThe album and subsequent singles were promoted mainly through televised performances and concert tours, much like with their previous album. Gomez & the Scene performed \"Round & Round\" live on shows such as ''[[America's Got Talent]]'',<ref>{{cite web |last=Reiher |first=Andrea |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/07/americas-got-talent-welcomes-selena-gomez-rock-of-ages-special-guest.html |title='America's Got Talent' welcomes Selena Gomez, 'Rock of Ages', special guest - Zap2it &#124; News & Features |publisher=Blog.zap2it.com |date=2010-07-13 |accessdate=2015-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917060208/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/07/americas-got-talent-welcomes-selena-gomez-rock-of-ages-special-guest.html |archivedate=2010-09-17 }}</ref> ''[[Blue Peter]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Iandoli |first=Kathy |url=http://idolator.com/5639711/selena-gomez-blue-peter |title=Selena Gomez Answers Some Kiddie Questions On 'Blue Peter' &#124; Music News, Reviews, and Gossip on |publisher=Idolator.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> ''[[Daybreak (2010 TV programme)|Daybreak]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/daybreak/ |title=Good Morning Britain &#124; GMB |publisher=Itv.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> and MTV's ''The Seven'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2010/10/01/selena-gomez-round-and-round-the-7-mtv/ |title=VIDEO: Selena Gomez Performs 'Round & Round' On MTV's 'The Seven' |publisher=Buzzworthy.mtv.com |date=2010-10-01 |accessdate=2015-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226215804/http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2010/10/01/selena-gomez-round-and-round-the-7-mtv/ |archivedate=2014-12-26 }}</ref> while performing \"A Year Without Rain\" on ''[[Good Morning America]]'', ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latina.com/entertainment/music/selena-gomezs-new-album-year-without-rain-drops-today |title=Selena Gomezs New Album A Year Without Rain Drops Today! |publisher=Latina.com |date=2010-09-21 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> and ''[[Lopez Tonight]]'' among other shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lopeztonight.com/episode_recaps_and_highlights/selena_gomez_sings.php |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722082823/http://www.lopeztonight.com/episode_recaps_and_highlights/selena_gomez_sings.php |archivedate=2011-07-22 |title=Selena Gomez Really Has Had a Year Without Rain &#124; Lopez Tonight |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> On October 27, 2010, the band played an acoustic set for charity ([[UNICEF]]). They were also part of the [[KIIS-FM Jingle Ball|Jingle Ball]] tour during December.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bostonherald.com/entertainment/music/general/view/20101210pop-happy_jingle_ball_rocks/srvc=home&position=also |title=Pop-happy Jingle Ball rocks |author=Carter, Lauren |date=10 December 2010 |work=[[Boston Herald]] |publisher=Herald Media Inc. |accessdate=5 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112170638/http://news.bostonherald.com/entertainment/music/general/view/20101210pop-happy_jingle_ball_rocks/srvc%3Dhome%26position%3Dalso |archivedate=12 January 2012 }}</ref> In 2011, the band performed \"A Year Without Rain\" and won Favorite Breakout Artist on the [[37th People's Choice Awards|Peoples Choice Awards]], against [[Justin Bieber]].<ref name=\"37th PCA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.peopleschoice.com/pca/awards/nominees/index.jsp|title=People's Choice Awards 2011 Nominees & Winners|publisher=People's Choice Awards|accessdate=2011-01-18}}</ref> The album was further promoted through the band's [[A Year Without Rain Tour]], which was both critically and commercially successful. During a backstage interview, Gomez remarked that she was conceptualizing the tour as far as stage and production and promised an amazing show with an \"epic\" stage for 2011.<ref>{{cite video|people=[[Selena Gomez|Gomez, Selena]] |title=Selena Gomez backstage with JJ |url=http://www.z100.com/pages/events/jingle-ball/2010.html?uri=channels/449656/1106113 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703205432/http://www.z100.com/pages/events/jingle-ball/2010.html?uri=channels%2F449656%2F1106113 |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 July 2013 |publisher=[[WHTZ]] |location=[[New York City]] |accessdate=5 January 2011 |time=2:09 }}</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132012: ''When the Sun Goes Down'', hiatus, and disbandment===\n[[File:Selena Gomez 3, 2011.jpg|thumb|200px|Selena Gomez & The Scene at [[We Own the Night Tour]] in 2011|left]]\nOn February 15, 2011, [[Hollywood Records]] confirmed that a new album was in the works.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/UniversalMusicPortugal#!/UniversalMusicPortugal/posts/179076442135107 |title=F\u00e3s da Selena Gomez |publisher=Facebook.com |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref><ref name=\"ryanseacrest. com\"/> Though the album was initially titled ''Otherside'',<ref name=\"jsyk. com\"/> it was later changed to ''[[When the Sun Goes Down (Selena Gomez & the Scene album)|When the Sun Goes Down]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/Selena |title=Selena Gomez |publisher=Facebook |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref> the album was released on June 28, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/canadianpress/article/ALeqM5iOXDtATkNTvatj0wY0UaySBveStw?docId=6864258 |title=Selena Gomez says she's starting a new chapter, now that 'Wizards' has wrapped |author=Baillie, Andrea|agency=[[Canadian Press Enterprises Inc.|The Canadian Press]] |date=2011-05-17 |accessdate=2011-05-19}}</ref> The album expanded on the pop and dance elements found on the band's last album, and features a more electropop and synthpop sound.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tim |last=Sendra |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/when-the-sun-goes-down-mw0002152176 |title=When the Sun Goes Down - Selena Gomez,Selena Gomez & the Scene &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date=2011-06-28 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref><ref name=\"top40.about.com\">{{cite web|url=http://top40.about.com/od/albums/fr/Selena-Gomez-And-The-Scene-When-The-Sun-Goes-Down.htm |title=Selena Gomez and the Scene - When the Sun Goes Down |publisher=Top40.about.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20355856_20504533,00.html | work=Entertainment Weekly | title=Music Review: When the Sun Goes Down, by Selena Gomez | date=2011-07-10}}</ref> The album also explores organic instrumentation.<ref name=\"Sendra\">{{cite web|last=Sendra |first=Tim |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/when-the-sun-goes-down-r2204393 |title=When the Sun Goes Down - Selena Gomez & the Scene |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=2011-06-30}}</ref> The sound of the album was compared to recent releases by artists such as [[Kelly Clarkson]] among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/selena-gomez-talks-when-the-sun-goes-down-1005253192.story#/news/selena-gomez-talks-when-the-sun-goes-down-1005253192.story |title=Selena Gomez Talks 'When the Sun Goes Down': Video Track-By-Track |magazine=Billboard |accessdate=2015-02-19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626032143/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/469719/selena-gomez-talks-when-the-sun-goes-down-video-track-by-track|archivedate=2015-06-26}}</ref> ''When the Sun Goes Down'' featured writing credits from writers and producers such as pop icon [[Britney Spears]],<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1661743/britney-spears-selena-gomez.jhtml |title=Britney Spears Penned Track For Selena Gomez |publisher=MTV |date=2011-11-04 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> pop singer [[Katy Perry]],<ref name=\"top40.about.com\"/> and [[Rock Mafia]], among others. The album received a mixed reviews<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/when-the-sun-goes-down-2011 |title=When the Sun Goes Down Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More at Metacritic |publisher=Metacritic.com |date= |accessdate=December 1, 2011}}</ref> with the album's second single receiving a 4x Platinum certification from the RIAA.,<ref name=\"RIAA Platinum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=selena%20gomez%20&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=8&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=Artist&perPage=25|title=RIAA - Gold & Platinum Searchable Database - November 01, 2015|work=riaa.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924152637/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=selena%20gomez%20&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=8&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=Artist&perPage=25|archivedate=September 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/when-the-sun-goes-down-2011 |title=Reviews for When the Sun Goes Down by Selena Gomez |publisher=Metacritic |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> The record debuted at number 4 on the ''Billboard'' 200 with sales of 78,000 copies in its first week of release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/469358/beyonce-notches-4th-billboard-200-no-1-with-4 |title=Beyonce Notches 4th Billboard 200 No. 1 with '4' |magazine=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jordan |first=Chris |url=http://www.sheknows.com/entertainment/articles/835589/selena-gomez-posts-best-album-debut-numbers-of-career |title=Selena Gomez posts best album debut numbers of career |publisher=Sheknows.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> This marked the highest first week sales for the band to date, outselling their first two albums by nearly 12,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wete |first=Brad |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2011/07/06/beyonce-4-billboard-200-chart/ |title=Beyonce tops Billboard albums chart - but marks her lowest debut as a solo star &#124; EW.com |publisher=Music-mix.ew.com |date=2011-07-06 |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> As of 2012, ''When the Sun Goes Down'' has sold an estimated 642,000 copies in the US alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474163/selena-gomezs-next-album-due-in-march |title=Selena Gomez's Next Album Due In March |magazine=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref>\n\nThe album's lead single \"Who Says\" had its world premiere on ''[[On Air with Ryan Seacrest (radio)|On Air with Ryan Seacrest]]'' on March 8. The accompanying music video, which was directed by Chris Applebaum, premiered on [[VEVO]] March 11.<ref name=\"ryanseacrest. com\">{{cite web|url=http://ryanseacrest.com/2011/02/23/selena-gomez-to-world-premiere-new-single-who-says-with-ryan-seacrest/ |title=Selena Gomez To World Premiere New Single 'Who Says' with Ryan Seacrest |website=Ryanseacrest.com |date=2011-02-23 |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref> The single follows in succession of other self-empowerment singles such as \"[[Firework (song)|Firework]]\" by [[Katy Perry]], \"[[Fuckin' Perfect]]\" by [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], and \"[[Born This Way (song)|Born This Way]]\" by [[Lady Gaga]].<ref name=\"Vena2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1660139/selena-gomez-who-says.jhtml|title=Selena Gomez 'Inspired' By Latest Single, 'Who Says'|work=[[MTV News]]|publisher=MTV. [[MTV Networks]]|accessdate=2011-03-17|date=2011-03-17|first=Jocelyn|last=Vena}}</ref> \"Who Says\" was a critical success but was only successful in US, receiving a moderate success worldwide, becoming the band's highest peaking song on the Hot 100 chart to date, where it peaked at number 21.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/song/selena-gomez-the-scene/who-says/143752160#/song/selena-gomez-the-scene/who-says/25590983Z] {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The song has also been certified Platinum by the RIAA, becoming their second single to achieve this feat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |title=Recording Industry Association of America |publisher=RIAA |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref> On May 28, Gomez announced on her official Twitter that one of the songs from the album, \"[[Bang Bang Bang (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Bang Bang Bang]]\" would be released as part of an iTunes album countdown on June 7, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/americantop40?ref=ts#!/americantop40?sk=app_11007063052 |title=American Top 40 |publisher=Facebook |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref> Gomez later announced in an interview that the second single from the album would be \"[[Love You Like a Love Song]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dose.ca/music/4709734/story.html |title=Q&A: 2011 MMVAs Co-Host Selena Gomez |author=Collins, Leah |date=2011-05-02 |work=[[Dose (magazine)|Dose]] |publisher=[[Postmedia Network]] |accessdate=2011-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120630030706/http://www.dose.ca/music/4709734/story.html |archivedate=2012-06-30 }}</ref> The song was serviced to [[contemporary hit radio]] airplay on August 16, 2011 in the United States.<ref name=\"airplay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239 |title=Airplay Archive |work=[[FMQB]] |publisher=Friday Morning Quarterback Album Report, Inc. and Mediaspan Online Services |accessdate=2011-11-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602195200/http://fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239 |archivedate=2013-06-02 }}</ref> The single later went on to become the band's highest performing single in the U.S. to date, where it peaked at number 22 on the Hot 100 chart, their second highest peaking single to date.<ref name=\"music.yahoo.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007014705/http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/week-ending-july-10-2011-songs-rolling-over-everybody.html|title=Week Ending July 10, 2011. Songs: Rolling Over Everybody &#124; Chart Watch - Archives - Yahoo! Music|date=October 7, 2012|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=2020-03-28}}</ref> The song became their highest charting single on the [[Pop Songs]] chart based on radio airplay, where it peaked at No. 6.<ref name=\"music.yahoo.com\"/> The single was later certified 4x Platinum in the U.S., making it the band's first song to achieve this feat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?artist=%22Love+You+Like+a+Love+Song%22 |title=Gold & Platinum Searchable Database - February 19, 2015 |publisher=RIAA |date= |accessdate=2015-02-19}}</ref> \"[[Hit the Lights (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Hit the Lights]]\" was released as the third and final single in 2012, but it failed to have much success. On March 23, 2011, [[Hollywood Records]] announced the [[We Own the Night Tour]], which began on July 24, 2011<ref>{{cite press release |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene Announce Summer Headline Tour |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/selena-gomez--the-scene-announce-summer-headline-tour-118517139.html |publisher=PR Newswire |date=2011-03-23 |accessdate=2011-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/scene-stealer-selena-gomez-co-hosts-and-performs-at-the-2011-muchmusic-video-awards-live-sunday-june-19-at-9-pm-et-121075789.html |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] |date=2011-05-02 |title=Scene Stealer Selena Gomez Co-Hosts and Performs at The 2011 MUCHMUSIC VIDEO AWARDS, Live Sunday, June 19 at 9 p. m. ET |accessdate=2011-05-07 \n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110505063220/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/scene-stealer-selena-gomez-co-hosts-and-performs-at-the-2011-muchmusic-video-awards-live-sunday-june-19-at-9-pm-et-121075789.html |url-status=live |archivedate=2011-05-05}}</ref> and ended on February 11, 2012.\n\nIn January 7, 2012, Gomez announced that the band was on hiatus and that they would not release a new album in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Collins|first=Leah|title=Selena Gomez takes 'a break' from music|url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/Selena+Gomez+takes+break+from+music/5962976/story.html|work=[[Vancouver Sun]]|accessdate=February 12, 2012|date=January 7, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215091441/http://www.vancouversun.com/entertainment/Selena%2BGomez%2Btakes%2Bbreak%2Bfrom%2Bmusic/5962976/story.html|archivedate=February 15, 2012}}</ref> On July 22, 2012, Selena Gomez & the Scene won \"Choice Music: Group\" for the third time in a row at the [[2012 Teen Choice Awards]].<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20613936,00.html \"Selena Gomez Celebrates 20th Birthday with a Win at Teen Choice Awards\"]. ''People''. July 22, 2012.</ref> As of 2020, the band has not reformed to release any new material, with Selena Gomez focusing solely on her solo career.\n\n==Members==\n<!-- NOTE: They are on a \"hiatus\" right now NOT a break-up. Do not put all the current band-members as \"Formers\" please. They didn't disband. -->\n\n;Final line-up\n* [[Selena Gomez]] \u2013 [[Lead vocalist|lead vocals]] (2008\u20132012)\n* Greg Garman \u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boomdrum.com/artist-feature/artist-feature-greg-garman-selena-gomez-scene |title=Artist Feature: Greg Garman of Selena Gomez and the Scene |publisher=Boom Drum |date=2010-03-23 |accessdate=2010-09-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208114225/http://boomdrum.com/artist-feature/artist-feature-greg-garman-selena-gomez-scene |archivedate=2010-12-08 }}</ref> (2008\u20132012)\n* [[Joey Clement]] \u2013 [[bass guitar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.takamine.com/?fa=artist&id=977 |title=Takamine Guitars |publisher=Takamine.com |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref> (2008\u20132012)\n* Drew Taubenfeld \u2013 [[lead guitar]] (2012)\n* Dane Forrest \u2013 [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]] (2008\u20132012)\n\n;Former members\n* Nick Foxer \u2013 [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Idolator |url=http://soundmaven.com/artist/Selena%2BGomez%2B%2526%2BThe%2BScene/ |title=Selena Gomez & The Scene |publisher=soundmaven.com |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> (2008\u20132009)\n* [[Ethan Roberts]] \u2013 [[lead guitar]], backing vocals<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.takamine.com/?fa=artist&id=974 |title=Takamine Guitars |publisher=Takamine.com |accessdate=2011-09-23}}</ref> (2008\u20132012)\n\n;Touring members\n* Lindsey Harper \u2013 [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]] (2010\u20132012)\n* Katelyn Clampett \u2013 backing vocals (2011\u20132012)\n* Ashleigh Haney \u2013 backing vocals (2011)\n* [[Christina Grimmie]] \u2013 backing vocals (2010\u20132011)\n\n===Timeline===\n{{Empty section|date=February 2019|section=}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Selena Gomez & the Scene discography}}\n\n* ''[[Kiss & Tell (Selena Gomez & the Scene album)|Kiss & Tell]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[A Year Without Rain]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[When the Sun Goes Down (Selena Gomez & the Scene album)|When the Sun Goes Down]]'' (2011)\n\n==Tours==\n* [[Selena Gomez & the Scene: Live in Concert|Live in Concert]] (2009\u20132010)\n* [[A Year Without Rain Tour]] (2010\u20132011)\n* [[We Own the Night Tour]] (2011\u20132012)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{See also|List of awards and nominations received by Selena Gomez}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Association\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Work\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2010\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Music: Group\n| rowspan=\"5\"|Selena Gomez & the Scene\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Choice Music: Breakout Artist\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n|[[MTV Europe Music Awards]]\n|Best Push Act\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\" | 2011\n| [[Kids' Choice Awards Argentina]]\n| Favorite International Singer\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[People's Choice Awards]]\n| [[People's Choice Award for Favorite Breakout Artist|Favorite Breakout Artist]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[MuchMusic Video Awards]]\n|International Video of the Year \u2013 Artist\n|rowspan=\"3\"|\"[[A Year Without Rain (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|A Year Without Rain]]\"\n|rowspan=3 {{nom}}\n|-\n|Ur Fave International Video\n|-\n|MuchMusic.com Most Watched Video of the Year\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[2011 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Music: Group\n|Selena Gomez & The Scene\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Choice Music: Single\n| [[Who Says (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Who Says]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Music - Love Song#2010s|Choice Music: Love Song]]\n| [[Love You like a Love Song]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"9\"|2012\n|[[MuchMusic Video Awards]]\n|International Video of the Year \u2013 Group\n|[[Love You like a Love Song]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[2012 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Music: Group\n| Selena Gomez & the Scene\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Choice Music: Single by a Group\n| [[Hit the Lights]]\n| rowspan=3 {{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Kids' Choice Awards Mexico]]\n|Canci\u00f3n Favorita\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Love You like a Love Song]]\n|-\n|[[MTV Video Music Awards]]\n|Best Female Video\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Vevo Certified]] Awards\n|rowspan=\"4\"|Vevo Certified 100 Million Views\n|\"[[Naturally (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Naturally]]\"\n|rowspan=4 {{won}}\n|-\n|\"[[A Year Without Rain (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|A Year Without Rain]]\"\n|-\n|\"[[Who Says (Selena Gomez & the Scene song)|Who Says]]\"\n|-\n|\"[[Love You like a Love Song]]\"\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of artists who reached number one on the U.S. dance chart]]\n* [[List of artists who reached number one on the U.S. dance airplay chart]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Selena Gomez & the Scene}}\n{{Selena Gomez}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Selena Gomez and The Scene}}\n[[Category:Selena Gomez & the Scene| ]]\n[[Category:Selena Gomez]]\n[[Category:American pop rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Hollywood Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language singers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2012]]\n[[Category:Electropop groups]]\n", "name_user": "Yeaman7765", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Selena_Gomez_%26_the_Scene"}
