_Noticias\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boasnoticias.pt/index.aspx?p=MenuDetail&MenuId=1429&ParentId=20|title=P\u00e1gina n\u00e3o encontrada|access-date=2010-06-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910224644/http://www.boasnoticias.pt/index.aspx?p=MenuDetail&MenuId=1429&ParentId=20|archive-date=2011-09-10|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Qualidade_Online\"/><ref name=\"Convergence\"/><ref name=\"Universia\">[http://www.universia.pt/servicos_net/informacao/noticia.jsp?noticia=59968 ]{{dead link|date=July 2018}}</ref> but has since been located at its present campus.<ref name=\"OIS_website\"/>\n\nOIS has ambitious plans to become an tensor [[Eco-Schools|Eco-School]] and intends to promote Environmental Awareness and Social Responsibility with the provision of scholarships and community service.<ref name=\"Qualidade_Online\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.qualidadeonline.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2122&Itemid=1 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-05-29 |archive-url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20100529123425/http://www.qualidadeonline.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2122&Itemid=1 |archive-date=2010-05-29 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Convergence\">{{Cite web |url=http://convergence.com.pt/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=452%3A1o-escola-internacional-de-oeiras-abre-em-setembro&catid=42%3Aoff-topic&Itemid=50 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-06-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813233055/http://convergence.com.pt/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=452:1o-escola-internacional-de-oeiras-abre-em-setembro&catid=42:off-topic&Itemid=50 |archive-date=2011-08-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt a launch event held at Hotel Palacio in Estoril in 2010, the school's Principal described the school saying \"OIS is committed to promoting quality education and values in a changing world, encouraging students to become responsible for their own learning. We will focus on intellectual rigour, helping all students to achieve their full potential\".<ref name=\"Portugal_News\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theportugalnews.com/cgi-bin/article.pl?id=1061-49|title=New International School to open in Oeiras|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Motto==\nThe school motto is [[Sapere aude|Sapere Aude]] (Dare to Learn).<ref name=\"OIS_website\"/>\n\n==Location==\nQuinta de Nossa Senhora da Concei\u00e7\u00e3o,\n\u00e0 Rua Antero de Quental,\nBarcarena,\n2780-001 Oeiras,\nPortugal <ref name=\"HotFrog\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hotfrog.pt/Empresas/Oeiras-International-School|title=Oeiras International School, Oeiras Lisboa - Ensino  - Hotfrog Portugal|website=www.hotfrog.pt}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Portugal|Schools}}\n*[[Education in Portugal]]\n*[[Eco-Schools]]\n*[[Afrixalus osorioi]]\n*[[Bulbophyllum xanthophaeum]]\n*[[Rhuma thiobapta]]\n*[[Bittium watsoni]]\n*[[Tippmannia olivascens]]\n*[[Amphicnaeia brevivittis]]\n\n==References==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using  tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.oeirasinternationalschool.com/ Official School Website]\n{{International schools in Portugal}}\n\n[[Category:International schools in Portugal]]<!--not in the Lisbon city limits-->\n[[Category:Education in Oeiras]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lisbon District]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2010]]\n[[Category:Education in Lisbon]]\n[[Category:2010 establishments in Portugal]]\n", "name_user": "Xxcringewizardxx", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oeiras_International_School"}
{"title_page": "Carol A. Barnes", "text_new": "{{For|the British broadcaster|Carol Barnes}}\n{{short description|American neuroscientist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Carol A. Barnes\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| residence = United States\n| citizenship = \n| nationality = \n| fields = [[Neuroscience]], [[memory]], [[learning]]\n| workplaces = [[University of Arizona]]\n| alma_mater = B.A., [[University of California, Riverside]] <br />\nM.A., [[University of Ottawa]] <br />Ph.D. [[Carleton University]] <br />postdoctoral training in neurophysiology at [[Dalhousie University]], [[University of Oslo]], and the Cerebral Functions Group at [[University College London]] \n| doctoral_advisor = Peter Fried\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = \n| signature = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n[[File:Carol_A_Barnes.png|thumb|Carol A Barnes, PhD]]\n'''Carol A. Barnes, Ph.D.''' is a [[neuroscientist]] and a Regents' [[Professor]] of [[psychology]] at the [[University of Arizona]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=http://psychology.arizona.edu/carol |title=Carol Barnes |publisher=Department of Psychology, University of Arizona |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525213406/http://psychology.arizona.edu/carol# |archive-date=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Since 2006, she has been the Evelyn F. McKnight Chair for Learning and Memory in Aging<ref>{{cite web |url=http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/endowed-chair.html |title=Evelyn F. McKnight Endowed Chair for Learning and Memory in Aging |publisher=Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute, University of Arizona |date=2006-12-11 |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919034703/http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/endowed-chair.html |archive-date=2013-09-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and is director of the Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/ |title=McKnight Brain Institute at the University of Arizona |publisher=Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute, University of Arizona |date= |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525195119/http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/ |archive-date=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Barnes has been president of the [[Society for Neuroscience]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfn.org/about/volunteer-leadership/sfn-presidents |title=Society for Neuroscience - SfN Presidents |publisher=Society for Neuroscience |date=2013-11-26 |accessdate=2014-05-25}}</ref> and is a [[Fellow of the AAAS|Fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows?LastName=B&Section=V |title=Fellows &#124; AAAS MemberCentral |publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525202502/http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows?LastName=B&Section=V# |archive-date=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and foreign member of the [[Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Letters]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dknvs.no/akademimedlemmer/medlemmer/utenlandske-medlemmer-naturvitenskapelig-klasse/ |title=Utenlandske medlemmer naturvitenskapelig klass |publisher=Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Letters |accessdate=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222003839/http://www.dknvs.no/akademimedlemmer/medlemmer/utenlandske-medlemmer-naturvitenskapelig-klasse/ |archivedate=2013-12-22 }}</ref> She was elected to the [[National Academy of Sciences]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nasonline.org/news-and-multimedia/news/May-1-2018-NAS-Election.html|title=May 1 2018 NAS Election|first=National Academy of Sciences -|last=http://www.nasonline.org|website=www.nasonline.org}}</ref>\n\nBarnes has produced over 170 peer reviewed publications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gruberprizes.org/SelectingRecipients/SelectionAdvisoryBoard_Bio.php?id=23 |title=The Gruber Foundation Homepage &#124; The Gruber Foundation |publisher=Gruberprizes.org |date=2014-03-03 |accessdate=2014-05-25}}</ref> Broadly, her research is focused on the neurophysiological and behavioral changes that occur in the brain during aging. Understanding of these changes may shed light on the processes that contribute to age-related neurodegenerative disorders such as [[Alzheimer's Disease]]. Barnes also developed the [[Barnes maze]], a spatial navigation memory task that is used to assess hippocampal-dependent memory.<ref name=\":1\" />\n[[File:University of Arizona Student Union.jpg|thumb|Old Main, University of Arizona in Pheonix]]\n\n== Education ==\n[[File:Carleton_University_River.jpg|thumb|Carleton University River]]\nCarol Barnes received a Bachelors of Arts in Psychology with honors at the [[University of California]], riverside, in 1971. She continued her education at [[Carleton University]] located in Ottawa Ontario, Canada, earning her Masters of Arts degree in Psychology in 1972. While pursuing a PhD in Psychology, Barnes took a temporary position as a postdoctoral researcher researching [[neuropsychology]] and [[neurophysiology]] in the department of psychology at [[Dalhousie University]], another at the institute of neurophysiology of [[University of Oslo]]as, as well as in Cerebral function at [[University College London|University College of London]]. In 1977 she graduated with Cum Laude in psychology at [[Carleton University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gruber.yale.edu/carol-barnes|title=Carol A. Barnes {{!}} Gruber Foundation|website=gruber.yale.edu|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBarnes currently holds the positions of director for two organizations; [https://www.embi.arizona.edu/ The Evelyn F McKnight Brain Institute] and the Division of Neural Systems, Memory and Aging. She holds the position of the Endowed Chair of the Evelyn F McKnight Brain Institute for Learning-Memory in Aging. Today she is a regents professor at the [[University of Arizona]] in Tucson, Arizona. Barnes is apart\u00a0of the [https://bio5.org/ BIO5 Institute] that is funded by the Technology and Research Fund (TRIF).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bio5.org/about/why|title=Why BIO5 {{!}} BIO5 Institute|website=bio5.org|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> At the BIO5 institute she works with students addressing [[Alzheimer's disease]] and other age-related brain diseases. Barnes also teaches cancer biology, neuroscience, psychology, and physiological sciences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.arizona.edu/users/carol-barne|title=College of Science, Psychology|last=|first=|date=2020|website=The University of Arizona|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nBarnes is involved with the [[neuroscience]] research community on a national and local level. Barnes research spans 4 decades aiming to better understand the aging of the brain in relation to cognitive diseases. Her research is conducted by utilizing animal models such as primates and rats to explore and understand how memory is impacted in the normal aging process of the brain through means of neurobiological mechanisms that are involved. The use of animal models in Barnes research is translated into treatments used for abnormal functioning of the brain aimed at prolonging the cognitive lifespan of older individuals. The nature of Barnes research entails the use of behavioral, anatomical, [[Electrophysiology|electrophysiological]] and molecular techniques\u00a0 to further examine the implications of normal aging on the brain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.arizona.edu/users/carol-barnes|title=Carol Barnes {{!}} Department of Psychology|website=psychology.arizona.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Most areas of her research involves examining and observing the [[hippocampus]] structure in the brains of rats and monkeys, observing and recording\u00a0synaptic transmission in cell to cell signaling, and genomic sequencing.\n\n=== [[Barnes maze|Barnes Maze]] ===\nTo study spatial learning and memory, Carol Barnes created her own maze to test whether rodents, specifically mice, could remember the location of an escape box on a platform. This test has become a standard method of memory testing in laboratories. Designed in 1979, Barnes' maze was an alternative to study memory without the use of external reward or punishment, while also reducing the stress put on the animal throughout the process.\n[[File:Barnes_maze.jpg|thumb|The Barnes maze]]\nThe original study consisted of a platform (122&nbsp;cm diameter) raised 91&nbsp;cm above the floor with 18 circular holes (9.5&nbsp;cm diameters) spaced evenly around the perimeter. Under one of the holes is a black escape box, or any dark color in contrast to the color of the platform; the rest of the holes lead to false escape boxes. The study consisted of 3 variations of the experiment. First, the mouse simply had to find the escape chamber that was placed under one of the holes. Second, the escape chamber was moved to a hole rotated 120-140 degrees from the original hole; the original hole was covered. Third, the same method as the second variation was used except the original hole was not covered. Barnes and her team found that overall, male mice performed better in all variations of the experiment. Further, they found younger mice also performed better in all variations, while older mice demonstrated notable difficulties in variations 2 and 3. This showed aging impairment in [[spatial memory]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gawel|first=Kinga|last2=Gibula|first2=Ewa|last3=Marszalek-Grabska|first3=Marta|last4=Filarowska|first4=Joanna|last5=Kotlinska|first5=Jolanta H.|date=2019-01-01|title=Assessment of spatial learning and memory in the Barnes maze task in rodents\u2014methodological consideration|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s00210-018-1589-y|journal=Naunyn-Schmiedeberg's Archives of Pharmacology|language=en|volume=392|issue=1|pages=1\u201318|doi=10.1007/s00210-018-1589-y|issn=1432-1912|pmc=6311199|pmid=30470917}}</ref>\n[[File:Hippocampus.png|thumb|Hippocampus]]\nSpatial memory corresponds to the functioning of the [[hippocampus]], while route learning involves the [[Striatum|striatal]] systems. Overall, rodents of various ages learned T-mazes within the same number of trials, but the strategies used to learn and remember mazes differed with age. Young rats predominately utilized \u201cplace\u201d strategies which rely upon [[Hippocampus|hippocampal]] functioning, while older rats relied upon \u201cresponse\u201d strategies. Using [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] imaging techniques, Barnes and her team were able to see that in normally aged brains of rodents, the size of the [[hippocampus]] did not change while the volume of [[Grey matter|cortical grey matter]] did. This animal model allowed an understanding of what the brain looks like during normal human functioning to compare it to brains that have been degenerated due to [[Alzheimer's disease|Alzheimer\u2019s disease]] (rodents do not exhibit AD). These findings demonstrate that while during normal aging the [[hippocampus]] remains the same size, its function may decrease in comparison to functions of other areas of the brain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Samson|first=Rachel D.|last2=Barnes|first2=Carol A.|date=2013|title=Impact of Aging Brain Circuits on Cognition|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3694726/|journal=The European journal of neuroscience|volume=37|issue=12|pages=1903\u20131915|doi=10.1111/ejn.12183|issn=0953-816X|pmc=3694726|pmid=23773059|via=}}</ref>\n\nLooking deeper into the tissue affected, single-cell imaging showed there were 3 main types of cells that make up the [[hippocampus]]. When observing cell activity and the number of cells of the hippocampus of rats, it was found that the [[CA1 neuron|CA1]] and [[CA3 region|CA3]] [[pyramidal cell]]s continued to be active and of the same volume. However, the number of [[granule cell]]s of the [[dentate gyrus]] continuously decreased with age; the function of these cells also declined leading Carol and her team to conclude these gyrus cells are the weak link of the hippocampal circuit involved in memory.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Barnes|first=Carol A.|date=2011-10-03|title=Secrets of aging: What does a normally aging brain look like?|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3186042/|journal=F1000 Biology Reports|volume=3|doi=10.3410/B3-22|issn=1757-594X|pmc=3186042|pmid=22003369}}</ref>\n\nA few of Barnes\u2019s latest research publication was published in 2017 are:\u00a0 \u201c[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S016643281630420X Attentional updating and monitoring and affective shifting are impacted independently by aging in the macaque monkeys]\u201d, \u201c[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28174334 Evidence for an evolutionarily conserved memory coding scheme in the mammalian hippocampus]\u201d, and \u201c[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627317305615 The aging navigational system]\u201d.\n\n=== Primate Research ===\n[[File:Brain_regions_involved_in_memory_formation.jpg|thumb|Brain regions involved in memory formation]]\nIn addition to work on rodent models, Dr. Barnes has helped advance the field of normative aging research using nonhuman primate models, specifically [[Macaque|macaque monkeys]].\u00a0 Primarily, Barnes\u2019 early work in macaques helped to tie together neurobiological data collected from rodents and functional imaging data from older humans. In the paper \u201c[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4848213/ Memory impairment in aged primates is associated with region-specific network dysfunction]\u201d Barnes and her team showed that older monkeys had significant impairment on object recognition. In addition, older monkeys displayed a lower density of inhibitory somatostatin positive [[interneuron]]s in the [[CA3 region|CA3]] sub-region of the [[hippocampus]]. These [[interneuron]]s are responsible for regulating the activity of excitatory neurons in the [[hippocampus]]. With less [[interneuron]] density, the baseline firing rate of [[CA3 region|CA3]] excitatory neurons was elevated. This finding relates to the increased hippocampal activity shown in imaging studies of older human adults. Both a decrease in [[interneuron]] density and increase baseline firing rates in the [[hippocampus]] have been associated with poor cognition.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gray|first=Daniel T.|last2=Barnes|first2=Carol A.|date=2019-12-26|title=Experiments in macaque monkeys provide critical insights into age-associated changes in cognitive and sensory function|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6936691/|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=116|issue=52|pages=26247\u201326254|doi=10.1073/pnas.1902279116|issn=0027-8424|pmc=6936691|pmid=31871147}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, in the paper \u201cEvidence for an evolutionarily conserved memory coding scheme in the mammalian hippocampus\u201d Dr. Barnes and her team found evidence that all mammals require the same quantity of neurons in the hippocampus to encode memory of a single experience. This finding suggests that tall mammals use a stable amount of neurons to encode a similar virtual reality experience. However, due to variable hippocampus size, the proportion of neurons used for the encoding of experience differ. Rodents have the smallest [[hippocampus]] and thus use 40% of their [[hippocampus]] neurons for encoding, nonhuman primates have larger hippocampus and use 4%, and finally humans have the largest [[hippocampus]] and use an estimated 2.5% for experiential encoding.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wixted|first=John T.|last2=Goldinger|first2=Stephen D.|last3=Squire|first3=Larry R.|last4=Kuhn|first4=Joel R.|last5=Papesh|first5=Megan H.|last6=Smith|first6=Kris A.|last7=Treiman|first7=David M.|last8=Steinmetz|first8=Peter N.|date=2018-01-30|title=Coding of episodic memory in the human hippocampus|url=https://www.pnas.org/content/115/5/1093|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=115|issue=5|pages=1093\u20131098|doi=10.1073/pnas.1716443115|issn=0027-8424|pmid=29339476|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nDr. Barnes has also done research to see how executive function changes with normative aging. [[Executive functions]] are the higher order process humans take part in such as attention, decision making, impulse control, and emotional control. These functions are mediated by the activity of the [[Prefrontal cortex|Prefrontal Cortex]]. Once again studying [[macaque]]s, Barnes and her team focused on two aspects of executive function, attentional monitoring and updating as well as [[Cognitive flexibility|set shifting]]. Attentional monitoring and updating allow for behavior changes with corresponding rule changes. For example, when two options are presented one is the correct choice initially; however, when the correct choice changes to the second option, attentional monitoring and updating help correct for the rule change and alter behavior in order to choose correctly. The change in behavior is mediated through a process of trial and error, which helps associate the right choice with certain behaviors. Barnes and her team found that older monkeys needed a greater number of trials to accurately account for a rule change. Suggesting, the executive system behind attentional monitoring and updating is impaired with aging. Secondly, [[Cognitive flexibility|set shifting]] is the ability to unconsciously shift attention between tasks while maintaining accuracy. In her research, Barnes presented macaque monkeys with an object recognition test of previously learned objects. She then presented interfering objects which required shifts between the object choice and evaluation of novel objects. Her results showed that older monkeys performed better on object recognition with this interference than younger monkeys. Thus set shifting abilities seem to be maintained if not enhanced with aging. The most important discovery out of these studies, however, is that the two aspects of executive function, monitoring and updating and set shifting, were shown to be independent systems that are affected differently with age. Thus, Barnes and her team suggest that changes in the [[Prefrontal cortex|Prefrontal Cortex]] can result from aging but different sub-regions within it show different patterns of aging.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gray|first=Daniel T.|last2=Smith|first2=Anne C.|last3=Burke|first3=Sara N.|last4=Gazzaley|first4=Adam|last5=Barnes|first5=Carol A.|date=2017-03-30|title=Attentional updating and monitoring and affective shifting are impacted independently by aging in macaque monkeys|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5493156/|journal=Behavioural brain research|volume=322|issue=Pt B|pages=329\u2013338|doi=10.1016/j.bbr.2016.06.056|issn=0166-4328|pmc=5493156|pmid=27368416}}</ref>\n\nA final research contribution of Carol A Barnes involves the study of spatial networks and spatial memories in aging [[macaque]]s. Barnes and her team studied brain activity in four different conditions for movement: cages, sitting, walking on a treadmill, and freely walking in space. The study found that younger macaques have distinct spatial networks for all four distinct conditions. However, older monkeys displayed less discrete activity of spatial networks. Meaning, all conditions evoked activation of the same undifferentiated network. This finding suggests dynamic network changes as a possible explanation for spatial cognition deficits. In other words, the spatial processing networks become less precise with age and may contribute to spatial memory loss or confusion.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Engle|first=James R.|last2=Machado|first2=Christopher J.|last3=Permenter|first3=Michele R.|last4=Vogt|first4=Julie A.|last5=Maurer|first5=Andrew P.|last6=Bulleri|first6=Alicia M.|last7=Barnes|first7=Carol A.|date=2016-11-30|title=Network Patterns Associated with Navigation Behaviors Are Altered in Aged Nonhuman Primates|url=https://www.jneurosci.org/content/36/48/12217|journal=Journal of Neuroscience|language=en|volume=36|issue=48|pages=12217\u201312227|doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.4116-15.2016|issn=0270-6474|pmid=27903730|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nBarnes interest of normative aging in the brain stems from her grandfather when she and her family noticed that his memory was declining.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Sherva|first=Kara|date=2015|title=Carol Barnes: A Prominent Voice in the Neuroscience of Aging, and a Proponent of Women in Neuroscience|url=https://soundideas.pugetsound.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1045&context=soundneuroscience|journal=Sound Neuroscience: An Undergraduate Neuroscience Journal|volume=2|pages=|via=}}</ref> Furthermore, Barnes is included in the [https://neurotree.org/beta/tree.php?pid=547 Neuroscience Academic Family Tree] . Listed there are her mentors and mentees.\n\n== Supporting Women and the Underprivileged in Neuroscience ==\nCarol A Barnes has been recognized by her peers and the public for her work in promoting opportunities for women and the underprivileged in neuroscience. In 2010, she received the Mika Salpeter Lifetime Achievement Award<ref name=\":0\" /> which \u201crecognizes individuals with outstanding career achievements in neuroscience who have also actively promoted the professional advancement of women in neuroscience.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfn.org/initiatives/awards|title=Awards|website=www.sfn.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore she is an active participant in the [https://msrp.medicine.arizona.edu/programs/disadvantaged-high-school-student-research-program NIH Disadvantaged High School Student Research Program], [https://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/pa-files/PAR-99-091.html Minority Access to Research Careers], and the [https://mcnair.njit.edu/ McNair Achievement Program]. Finally, in 2013 Barnes gave a keynote address at the [https://www.sfn.org/cwinrsvp Celebration of Women in Neuroscience] entitled \u201cThe Evolving Face of Neuroscience: Role of Women and Globalization.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Awards and Honors<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://embi.arizona.edu/barnes/honors-awards|title=Dr. Carol A. Barnes - Honors and Awards {{!}} Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute|website=embi.arizona.edu|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>==\n{{external|section|date=April 2020}}\n<br />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! !! Year  !! Awards and Honors !! Description\n|-\n| 1||1969 || [[https://www.nsf.gov/funding/education.jsp?fund_type=1 National science Foundation Summer Research Fellowship|National Science Foundation Summer Research Fellowship]] ||  This fellowship funds student or identity programs that are focused on education developments\n|-\n| 2|| 1972-74 || [[https://osap.gov.on.ca/OSAPPortal/en/A-ZListofAid/PRDR019245.html Ontario Graduate Fellowship|Ontario Graduate Fellowship]] || For students pursuing their graduate studies at Master\u2019s and doctoral levels. This is a merit-based scholarship for students a part of the Ontario Graduate program\n|-\n| 3 || 1979-81 ||[https://www.nlm.nih.gov/ep/NRSAFellowshipGrants.html%20NIH%20National%20Research%20Service%20Award NIH National Research Service Award] ||  For Postdoctoral students gaining research and clinical training in both MD/Ph.D. or other dual-doctoral degree training program\n|-\n| 4 || 1981-82 ||[https://www.nsf.gov/pubs/2002/nsf02178/nsf02178.htm%20NATO%20Postdoctoral%20Fellowship%20in%20Science NATO Postdoctoral Fellowship in Science] || \n|-\n| 5 || 1984-89 || [https://researchtrain