rd] || \n|-\n| 16 || 2011-Present || [https://www.lpl.arizona.edu/graduate/awards/galileo Galileo Fellow, College of Science, University of Arizona] ||  \n|-\n| 17 || 2013 ||  [[Ralph_W._Gerard_Prize_in_Neuroscience|Ralph W Gerard Prize in Neuroscience]] ||\n|-\n| 18 || 2014 ||  APA Award for Distinguished Scientific Contributions\u00a0 || Barnes received this award as her role as director of the McKnight Brain Institute, the role in which she currently holds. This award is considered to be one of the highest awards of the Society for Neuroscience.\n|-\n| 19 || 2017 || Quad-L Award  || Barnes being one of the 7 people (including herself) who hold this award. This award is for distinguished contemporary scientists actively involved in research in regard to learning, memory or cognition\n|-\n| 20 || 2017 ||  MOCA Local Genius Award ||\n|-\n| 21 || 2018 || [[National_Academy_of_Sciences|Elected to\u00a0National Academy of Science]] || This award is one of the highest honors. Barnes received this award for the distinguished and continuation of her original research\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnes, Carol A.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of California, Riverside alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa alumni]]\n[[Category:Carleton University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona faculty]]\n[[Category:American neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:American women neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n[[Category:Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Letters]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the British broadcaster|Carol Barnes}}\n{{short description|American neuroscientist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Carol A. Barnes\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| residence = United States\n| citizenship = \n| nationality = \n| fields = [[Neuroscience]], [[memory]], [[learning]]\n| workplaces = [[University of Arizona]]\n| alma_mater = B.A., [[University of California, Riverside]] <br />\nM.A., [[University of Ottawa]] <br />Ph.D. [[Carleton University]] <br />postdoctoral training in neurophysiology at [[Dalhousie University]], [[University of Oslo]], and the Cerebral Functions Group at [[University College London]] \n| doctoral_advisor = Peter Fried\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = \n| signature = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n[[File:Carol_A_Barnes.png|thumb|Carol A Barnes, PhD]]\n'''Carol A. Barnes, Ph.D.''' is a [[neuroscientist]] and a Regents' [[Professor]] of [[psychology]] at the [[University of Arizona]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=http://psychology.arizona.edu/carol |title=Carol Barnes |publisher=Department of Psychology, University of Arizona |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525213406/http://psychology.arizona.edu/carol# |archive-date=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Since 2006, she has been the Evelyn F. McKnight Chair for Learning and Memory in Aging<ref>{{cite web |url=http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/endowed-chair.html |title=Evelyn F. McKnight Endowed Chair for Learning and Memory in Aging |publisher=Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute, University of Arizona |date=2006-12-11 |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919034703/http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/endowed-chair.html |archive-date=2013-09-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and is director of the Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/ |title=McKnight Brain Institute at the University of Arizona |publisher=Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute, University of Arizona |date= |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525195119/http://embi.nsma.arizona.edu/ |archive-date=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Barnes has been president of the [[Society for Neuroscience]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfn.org/about/volunteer-leadership/sfn-presidents |title=Society for Neuroscience - SfN Presidents |publisher=Society for Neuroscience |date=2013-11-26 |accessdate=2014-05-25}}</ref> and is a [[Fellow of the AAAS|Fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows?LastName=B&Section=V |title=Fellows &#124; AAAS MemberCentral |publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] |accessdate=2014-05-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525202502/http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows?LastName=B&Section=V# |archive-date=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and foreign member of the [[Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Letters]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dknvs.no/akademimedlemmer/medlemmer/utenlandske-medlemmer-naturvitenskapelig-klasse/ |title=Utenlandske medlemmer naturvitenskapelig klass |publisher=Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Letters |accessdate=2014-05-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222003839/http://www.dknvs.no/akademimedlemmer/medlemmer/utenlandske-medlemmer-naturvitenskapelig-klasse/ |archivedate=2013-12-22 }}</ref> She was elected to the [[National Academy of Sciences]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nasonline.org/news-and-multimedia/news/May-1-2018-NAS-Election.html|title=May 1 2018 NAS Election|first=National Academy of Sciences -|last=http://www.nasonline.org|website=www.nasonline.org}}</ref>\n\nBarnes has produced over 170 peer reviewed publications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gruberprizes.org/SelectingRecipients/SelectionAdvisoryBoard_Bio.php?id=23 |title=The Gruber Foundation Homepage &#124; The Gruber Foundation |publisher=Gruberprizes.org |date=2014-03-03 |accessdate=2014-05-25}}</ref> Broadly, her research is focused on the neurophysiological and behavioral changes that occur in the brain during aging. Understanding of these changes may shed light on the processes that contribute to age-related neurodegenerative disorders such as [[Alzheimer's Disease]]. Barnes also developed the [[Barnes maze]], a spatial navigation memory task that is used to assess hippocampal-dependent memory.<ref name=\":1\" />\n[[File:University of Arizona Student Union.jpg|thumb|Old Main, University of Arizona in Pheonix]]\n\n== Education ==\n[[File:Carleton_University_River.jpg|thumb|Carleton University River]]\nCarol Barnes received a Bachelors of Arts in Psychology with honors at the [[University of California]], riverside, in 1971. She continued her education at [[Carleton University]] located in Ottawa Ontario, Canada, earning her Masters of Arts degree in Psychology in 1972. While pursuing a PhD in Psychology, Barnes took a temporary position as a postdoctoral researcher researching [[neuropsychology]] and [[neurophysiology]] in the department of psychology at [[Dalhousie University]], another at the institute of neurophysiology of [[University of Oslo]]as, as well as in Cerebral function at [[University College London|University College of London]]. In 1977 she graduated with Cum Laude in psychology at [[Carleton University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gruber.yale.edu/carol-barnes|title=Carol A. Barnes {{!}} Gruber Foundation|website=gruber.yale.edu|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBarnes currently holds the positions of director for two organizations; [https://www.embi.arizona.edu/ The Evelyn F McKnight Brain Institute] and the Division of Neural Systems, Memory and Aging. She holds the position of the Endowed Chair of the Evelyn F McKnight Brain Institute for Learning-Memory in Aging. Today she is a regents professor at the [[University of Arizona]] in Tucson, Arizona. Barnes is apart\u00a0of the [https://bio5.org/ BIO5 Institute] that is funded by the Technology and Research Fund (TRIF).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bio5.org/about/why|title=Why BIO5 {{!}} BIO5 Institute|website=bio5.org|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> At the BIO5 institute she works with students addressing [[Alzheimer's disease]] and other age-related brain diseases. Barnes also teaches cancer biology, neuroscience, psychology, and physiological sciences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.arizona.edu/users/carol-barne|title=College of Science, Psychology|last=|first=|date=2020|website=The University of Arizona|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nBarnes is involved with the [[neuroscience]] research community on a national and local level. Barnes research spans 4 decades aiming to better understand the aging of the brain in relation to cognitive diseases. Her research is conducted by utilizing animal models such as primates and rats to explore and understand how memory is impacted in the normal aging process of the brain through means of neurobiological mechanisms that are involved. The use of animal models in Barnes research is translated into treatments used for abnormal functioning of the brain aimed at prolonging the cognitive lifespan of older individuals. The nature of Barnes research entails the use of behavioral, anatomical, [[Electrophysiology|electrophysiological]] and molecular techniques\u00a0 to further examine the implications of normal aging on the brain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.arizona.edu/users/carol-barnes|title=Carol Barnes {{!}} Department of Psychology|website=psychology.arizona.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Most areas of her research involves examining and observing the [[hippocampus]] structure in the brains of rats and monkeys, observing and recording\u00a0synaptic transmission in cell to cell signaling, and genomic sequencing.\n\n=== [[Barnes maze|Barnes Maze]] ===\nTo study spatial learning and memory, Carol Barnes created her own maze to test whether rodents, specifically mice, could remember the location of an escape box on a platform. This test has become a standard method of memory testing in laboratories. Designed in 1979, Barnes' maze was an alternative to study memory without the use of external reward or punishment, while also reducing the stress put on the animal throughout the process.\n[[File:Barnes_maze.jpg|thumb|The Barnes maze]]\nThe original study consisted of a platform (122&nbsp;cm diameter) raised 91&nbsp;cm above the floor with 18 circular holes (9.5&nbsp;cm diameters) spaced evenly around the perimeter. Under one of the holes is a black escape box, or any dark color in contrast to the color of the platform; the rest of the holes lead to false escape boxes. The study consisted of 3 variations of the experiment. First, the mouse simply had to find the escape chamber that was placed under one of the holes. Second, the escape chamber was moved to a hole rotated 120-140 degrees from the original hole; the original hole was covered. Third, the same method as the second variation was used except the original hole was not covered. Barnes and her team found that overall, male mice performed better in all variations of the experiment. Further, they found younger mice also performed better in all variations, while older mice demonstrated notable difficulties in variations 2 and 3. This showed aging impairment in [[spatial memory]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gawel|first=Kinga|last2=Gibula|first2=Ewa|last3=Marszalek-Grabska|first3=Marta|last4=Filarowska|first4=Joanna|last5=Kotlinska|first5=Jolanta H.|date=2019-01-01|title=Assessment of spatial learning and memory in the Barnes maze task in rodents\u2014methodological consideration|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s00210-018-1589-y|journal=Naunyn-Schmiedeberg's Archives of Pharmacology|language=en|volume=392|issue=1|pages=1\u201318|doi=10.1007/s00210-018-1589-y|issn=1432-1912|pmc=6311199|pmid=30470917}}</ref>\n[[File:Hippocampus.png|thumb|Hippocampus]]\nSpatial memory corresponds to the functioning of the [[hippocampus]], while route learning involves the [[Striatum|striatal]] systems. Overall, rodents of various ages learned T-mazes within the same number of trials, but the strategies used to learn and remember mazes differed with age. Young rats predominately utilized \u201cplace\u201d strategies which rely upon [[Hippocampus|hippocampal]] functioning, while older rats relied upon \u201cresponse\u201d strategies. Using [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] imaging techniques, Barnes and her team were able to see that in normally aged brains of rodents, the size of the [[hippocampus]] did not change while the volume of [[Grey matter|cortical grey matter]] did. This animal model allowed an understanding of what the brain looks like during normal human functioning to compare it to brains that have been degenerated due to [[Alzheimer's disease|Alzheimer\u2019s disease]] (rodents do not exhibit AD). These findings demonstrate that while during normal aging the [[hippocampus]] remains the same size, its function may decrease in comparison to functions of other areas of the brain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Samson|first=Rachel D.|last2=Barnes|first2=Carol A.|date=2013|title=Impact of Aging Brain Circuits on Cognition|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3694726/|journal=The European journal of neuroscience|volume=37|issue=12|pages=1903\u20131915|doi=10.1111/ejn.12183|issn=0953-816X|pmc=3694726|pmid=23773059|via=}}</ref>\n\nLooking deeper into the tissue affected, single-cell imaging showed there were 3 main types of cells that make up the [[hippocampus]]. When observing cell activity and the number of cells of the hippocampus of rats, it was found that the [[CA1 neuron|CA1]] and [[CA3 region|CA3]] [[pyramidal cell]]s continued to be active and of the same volume. However, the number of [[granule cell]]s of the [[dentate gyrus]] continuously decreased with age; the function of these cells also declined leading Carol and her team to conclude these gyrus cells are the weak link of the hippocampal circuit involved in memory.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Barnes|first=Carol A.|date=2011-10-03|title=Secrets of aging: What does a normally aging brain look like?|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3186042/|journal=F1000 Biology Reports|volume=3|doi=10.3410/B3-22|issn=1757-594X|pmc=3186042|pmid=22003369}}</ref>\n\nA few of Barnes\u2019s latest research publication was published in 2017 are:\u00a0 \u201c[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S016643281630420X Attentional updating and monitoring and affective shifting are impacted independently by aging in the macaque monkeys]\u201d, \u201c[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28174334 Evidence for an evolutionarily conserved memory coding scheme in the mammalian hippocampus]\u201d, and \u201c[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627317305615 The aging navigational system]\u201d.\n\n=== Primate Research ===\n[[File:Brain_regions_involved_in_memory_formation.jpg|thumb|Brain regions involved in memory formation]]\nIn addition to work on rodent models, Dr. Barnes has helped advance the field of normative aging research using nonhuman primate models, specifically [[Macaque|macaque monkeys]].\u00a0 Primarily, Barnes\u2019 early work in macaques helped to tie together neurobiological data collected from rodents and functional imaging data from older humans. In the paper \u201c[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4848213/ Memory impairment in aged primates is associated with region-specific network dysfunction]\u201d Barnes and her team showed that older monkeys had significant impairment on object recognition. In addition, older monkeys displayed a lower density of inhibitory somatostatin positive [[interneuron]]s in the [[CA3 region|CA3]] sub-region of the [[hippocampus]]. These [[interneuron]]s are responsible for regulating the activity of excitatory neurons in the [[hippocampus]]. With less [[interneuron]] density, the baseline firing rate of [[CA3 region|CA3]] excitatory neurons was elevated. This finding relates to the increased hippocampal activity shown in imaging studies of older human adults. Both a decrease in [[interneuron]] density and increase baseline firing rates in the [[hippocampus]] have been associated with poor cognition.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gray|first=Daniel T.|last2=Barnes|first2=Carol A.|date=2019-12-26|title=Experiments in macaque monkeys provide critical insights into age-associated changes in cognitive and sensory function|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6936691/|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=116|issue=52|pages=26247\u201326254|doi=10.1073/pnas.1902279116|issn=0027-8424|pmc=6936691|pmid=31871147}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, in the paper \u201cEvidence for an evolutionarily conserved memory coding scheme in the mammalian hippocampus\u201d Dr. Barnes and her team found evidence that all mammals require the same quantity of neurons in the hippocampus to encode memory of a single experience. This finding suggests that tall mammals use a stable amount of neurons to encode a similar virtual reality experience. However, due to variable hippocampus size, the proportion of neurons used for the encoding of experience differ. Rodents have the smallest [[hippocampus]] and thus use 40% of their [[hippocampus]] neurons for encoding, nonhuman primates have larger hippocampus and use 4%, and finally humans have the largest [[hippocampus]] and use an estimated 2.5% for experiential encoding.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wixted|first=John T.|last2=Goldinger|first2=Stephen D.|last3=Squire|first3=Larry R.|last4=Kuhn|first4=Joel R.|last5=Papesh|first5=Megan H.|last6=Smith|first6=Kris A.|last7=Treiman|first7=David M.|last8=Steinmetz|first8=Peter N.|date=2018-01-30|title=Coding of episodic memory in the human hippocampus|url=https://www.pnas.org/content/115/5/1093|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=115|issue=5|pages=1093\u20131098|doi=10.1073/pnas.1716443115|issn=0027-8424|pmid=29339476|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nDr. Barnes has also done research to see how executive function changes with normative aging. [[Executive functions]] are the higher order process humans take part in such as attention, decision making, impulse control, and emotional control. These functions are mediated by the activity of the [[Prefrontal cortex|Prefrontal Cortex]]. Once again studying [[macaque]]s, Barnes and her team focused on two aspects of executive function, attentional monitoring and updating as well as [[Cognitive flexibility|set shifting]]. Attentional monitoring and updating allow for behavior changes with corresponding rule changes. For example, when two options are presented one is the correct choice initially; however, when the correct choice changes to the second option, attentional monitoring and updating help correct for the rule change and alter behavior in order to choose correctly. The change in behavior is mediated through a process of trial and error, which helps associate the right choice with certain behaviors. Barnes and her team found that older monkeys needed a greater number of trials to accurately account for a rule change. Suggesting, the executive system behind attentional monitoring and updating is impaired with aging. Secondly, [[Cognitive flexibility|set shifting]] is the ability to unconsciously shift attention between tasks while maintaining accuracy. In her research, Barnes presented macaque monkeys with an object recognition test of previously learned objects. She then presented interfering objects which required shifts between the object choice and evaluation of novel objects. Her results showed that older monkeys performed better on object recognition with this interference than younger monkeys. Thus set shifting abilities seem to be maintained if not enhanced with aging. The most important discovery out of these studies, however, is that the two aspects of executive function, monitoring and updating and set shifting, were shown to be independent systems that are affected differently with age. Thus, Barnes and her team suggest that changes in the [[Prefrontal cortex|Prefrontal Cortex]] can result from aging but different sub-regions within it show different patterns of aging.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gray|first=Daniel T.|last2=Smith|first2=Anne C.|last3=Burke|first3=Sara N.|last4=Gazzaley|first4=Adam|last5=Barnes|first5=Carol A.|date=2017-03-30|title=Attentional updating and monitoring and affective shifting are impacted independently by aging in macaque monkeys|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5493156/|journal=Behavioural brain research|volume=322|issue=Pt B|pages=329\u2013338|doi=10.1016/j.bbr.2016.06.056|issn=0166-4328|pmc=5493156|pmid=27368416}}</ref>\n\nA final research contribution of Carol A Barnes involves the study of spatial networks and spatial memories in aging [[macaque]]s. Barnes and her team studied brain activity in four different conditions for movement: cages, sitting, walking on a treadmill, and freely walking in space. The study found that younger macaques have distinct spatial networks for all four distinct conditions. However, older monkeys displayed less discrete activity of spatial networks. Meaning, all conditions evoked activation of the same undifferentiated network. This finding suggests dynamic network changes as a possible explanation for spatial cognition deficits. In other words, the spatial processing networks become less precise with age and may contribute to spatial memory loss or confusion.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Engle|first=James R.|last2=Machado|first2=Christopher J.|last3=Permenter|first3=Michele R.|last4=Vogt|first4=Julie A.|last5=Maurer|first5=Andrew P.|last6=Bulleri|first6=Alicia M.|last7=Barnes|first7=Carol A.|date=2016-11-30|title=Network Patterns Associated with Navigation Behaviors Are Altered in Aged Nonhuman Primates|url=https://www.jneurosci.org/content/36/48/12217|journal=Journal of Neuroscience|language=en|volume=36|issue=48|pages=12217\u201312227|doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.4116-15.2016|issn=0270-6474|pmid=27903730|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nBarnes interest of normative aging in the brain stems from her grandfather when she and her family noticed that his memory was declining.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Sherva|first=Kara|date=2015|title=Carol Barnes: A Prominent Voice in the Neuroscience of Aging, and a Proponent of Women in Neuroscience|url=https://soundideas.pugetsound.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1045&context=soundneuroscience|journal=Sound Neuroscience: An Undergraduate Neuroscience Journal|volume=2|pages=|via=}}</ref> Furthermore, Barnes is included in the [https://neurotree.org/beta/tree.php?pid=547 Neuroscience Academic Family Tree] . Listed there are her mentors and mentees.\n\n== Supporting Women and the Underprivileged in Neuroscience ==\nCarol A Barnes has been recognized by her peers and the public for her work in promoting opportunities for women and the underprivileged in neuroscience. In 2010, she received the Mika Salpeter Lifetime Achievement Award<ref name=\":0\" /> which \u201crecognizes individuals with outstanding career achievements in neuroscience who have also actively promoted the professional advancement of women in neuroscience.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfn.org/initiatives/awards|title=Awards|website=www.sfn.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore she is an active participant in the [https://msrp.medicine.arizona.edu/programs/disadvantaged-high-school-student-research-program NIH Disadvantaged High School Student Research Program], [https://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/pa-files/PAR-99-091.html Minority Access to Research Careers], and the [https://mcnair.njit.edu/ McNair Achievement Program]. Finally, in 2013 Barnes gave a keynote address at the [https://www.sfn.org/cwinrsvp Celebration of Women in Neuroscience] entitled \u201cThe Evolving Face of Neuroscience: Role of Women and Globalization.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Awards and Honors<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://embi.arizona.edu/barnes/honors-awards|title=Dr. Carol A. Barnes - Honors and Awards {{!}} Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute|website=embi.arizona.edu|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>==\n{{external|section|date=April 2020}}\n<br />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! !! Awards and Honors !! Year !! Description\n|-\n| 1|| [[https://www.nsf.gov/funding/education.jsp?fund_type=1 National science Foundation Summer Research Fellowship|National Science Foundation Summer Research Fellowship]] || 1969 || This fellowship funds student or identity programs that are focused on education developments\n|-\n| 2|| [[https://osap.gov.on.ca/OSAPPortal/en/A-ZListofAid/PRDR019245.html Ontario Graduate Fellowship|Ontario Graduate Fellowship]] || 1972-74 || For students pursuing their graduate studies at Master\u2019s and doctoral levels. This is a merit-based scholarship for students a part of the Ontario Graduate program\n|-\n| 3 || [https://www.nlm.nih.gov/ep/NRSAFellowshipGrants.html%20NIH%20National%20Research%20Service%20Award NIH National Research Service Award] || 1979-81 || For Postdoctoral students gaining research and clinical training in both MD/Ph.D. or other dual-doctoral degree training program\n|-\n| 4 || [https://www.nsf.gov/pubs/2002/nsf02178/nsf02178.htm%20NATO%20Postdoctoral%20Fellowship%20in%20Science NATO Postdoctoral Fellowship in Science] || 1981-82 ||\n|-\n| 5 || [https://researchtraining.nih.gov/programs/career-development Research Career Development Award] || 1984-89 || \n|-\n| 6 || [https://www.niddk.nih.gov/research-funding/process/apply/funding-mechanisms/k-awards/k01 ADAMHA Research Scientist Development Award, National Institute of Mental Health] || 1989-94 ||\n|-\n| 7 || [https://www.niddk.nih.gov/research-funding/process/apply/funding-mechanisms/k-awards/k01 ADAMHA Research Scientist Development Award, National Institute of Mental Health] || 1994-99 ||\n|-\n| 8 || Foreign Member, [[Royal_Norwegian_Society_of_Sciences_and_Letters|The\u00a0Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Lette]]r\u00a0(Natural Sciences) || 2004-Present || \n|-\n| 9 || MERIT Award ,[[National_Institutes_of_Health_MERIT_Award|National Advisory Council on Aging]] || 2004-14 ||\n|-\n| 10 || Regents Professor, [[Professors_in_the_United_States#Distinguished_(teaching_/_research)_professor|University of Arizona]] || 2004-14 ||\n|-\n| 11 || Endowed Chair: Evelyn F. McKnight Chair Learning and Memory in Aging || 2006-Present ||\n|-\n| 12 || Fellow,\u00a0[[American_Association_for_the_Advancement_of_Science|American Association for the Advancement of Science]] || 2009-Present || Fellows are elected annually by the AAAS Council. Fellows are recognized for their contributions to the advancement of science or its application are scientifically or socially distinguished\n|-\n| 13 || [https://www.apadivisions.org/division-6/awards/marquis%20APA%20Division%206%20D.B.%20Marquis%20Behavioral%20Neuroscience%20Award 2009 APA Division 6 D.B. Marquis Behavioral Neuroscience Award] || 2010 || \n|-\n| 14 || [https://www.apadivisions.org/division-6/awards/marquis%20APA%20Division%206%20D.B.%20Marquis%20Behavioral%20Neuroscience%20Award%20for%20Behavioral%20Neuroscience 2010 APA Division 6 D.B. Marquis Behavioral Neuroscience Award for Behavioral Neuroscience] || 2010 || \n|-\n| 15 || [https://www.sfn.org/initiatives/awards/mika-salpeter-award Mika Salpeter Lifetime Achievement Award] || 2010 || \n|-\n| 16 || [https://www.lpl.arizona.edu/graduate/awards/galileo Galileo Fellow, College of Science, University of Arizona] || 2011-Present || \n|-\n| 17 || [[Ralph_W._Gerard_Prize_in_Neuroscience|Ralph W Gerard Prize in Neuroscience]] || 2013 || \n|-\n| 18 || APA Award for Distinguished Scientific Contributions\u00a0 || 2014 || Barnes received this award as her role as director of the McKnight Brain Institute, the role in which she currently holds. This award is considered to be one of the highest awards of the Society for Neuroscience.\n|-\n| 19 || Quad-L Award  || 2017 || Barnes being one of the 7 people (including herself) who hold this award. This award is for distinguished contemporary scientists actively involved in research in regard to learning, memory or cognition\n|-\n| 20 || MOCA Local Genius Award || 2017 || \n|-\n| 21 || [[National_Academy_of_Sciences|Elected to\u00a0National Academy of Science]] || 2018 || This award is one of the highest honors. Barnes received this award for the distinguished and continuation of her original research\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnes, Carol A.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of California, Riverside alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa alumni]]\n[[Category:Carleton University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona faculty]]\n[[Category:American neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:American women neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n[[Category:Royal Norwegian Society of Sciences and Letters]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n", "name_user": "8421nguyena", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards and Honors{{Cite web|url=https://embi.arizona.edu/barnes/honors-awards|title=Dr. Carol A. Barnes - Honors and Awards {{!}} Evelyn F. McKnight Brain Institute|website=embi.arizona.edu|access-date=2020-03-28}}", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carol_A._Barnes"}
{"title_page": "En (Cyrillic)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text=the [[E|Latin letter H]]}}\n{{Cyrillic alphabet navbox|\nHeading=Cyrillic letter En|\nImage=Cyrillic letter En - uppercase and lowercase.svg|size=120px|\nuuc=041D|ulc=043D|numeral=50|sound = {{IPA|[n]}}}}\n'''En''' (\u041d&nbsp;\u043d; italics: <span styleU\"font-family: times, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-size: larger\">''\u041d&nbsp;\u043d''</span>) is a letter of the [[Cyrillic script]].\n\nIt commonly represents the [[alveolar nasal]] consonant {{IPA|/n/}}, like the pronunciation of {{angbr|n}} in \"'''n'''eat\".\n\n==Form==\nThe capital Cyrillic letter En [[Homoglyph|looks exactly the same as]] the capital [[H|Latin letter H]] but, as with most Cyrillic letters, the lowercase form is simply a smaller version of the uppercase.\n\nBy exception, the [[Romanian Cyrillic alphabet]] used N and \u0274,{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}} instead of \u041d and \u043d.\n\nCoincidentally, the Cyrillic letter I {{angbr|\u0418}}, which looks like a reversed Latin {{angbr|N}}, was derived from the [[Eta (letter)|Greek letter Eta]] {{angbr|\u0397}} while the Cyrillic letter En {{angbr|\u041d}} was derived from the [[Nu (letter)|Greek letter Nu]] {{angbr|\u039d}} which looks like a reversed Cyrillic {{angbr|\u0418}}.\n\n==Usage==\nAs used in the alphabets of various languages, En represents the following sounds:\n* [[alveolar nasal]] consonant {{IPA|/n/}}, like the pronunciation of {{angbr|n}} in \"'''n'''ice\"\n* [[dental nasal]] consonant {{IPA|/n\u032a/}}, as above but with the tip of the tongue on the teeth\n* palatalized [[alveolar nasal]] consonant {{IPA|/n\u02b2/}}, like the pronunciation of {{angbr|n}} in \"o'''n'''ion\"\n* palatalized [[dental nasal]] consonant {{IPA|/n\u032a\u02b2/}}, as above but with the tip of the tongue on the teeth\n* [[palatal nasal]] consonant {{IPA|/\u0272/}}\n\nThe pronunciations shown in the table are the primary ones for each language; for details consult the articles on the languages.\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Language !! Position in <br> alphabet !! Pronunciation\n|-\n| [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]] || align=center | 15th || {{IPA|/n\u032a/}}, {{IPA|/n\u032a\u02b2/}}\n|-\n| [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] || align=center | 14th || {{IPA|/n/}}, {{IPA|/\u0272/}}\n|-\n| [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]] || align=center | 17th || {{IPA|/n/}}\n|-\n| [[Russian language|Russian]] || align=center | 15th || {{IPA|/n\u032a/}}, {{IPA|/n\u032a\u02b2/}}\n|-\n| [[Serbian language|Serbian]] || align=center | 16th || {{IPA|/n/}}\n|-\n| [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] || align=center | 18th || {{IPA|/n\u032a/}}, {{IPA|/n\u02b2/}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Related letters and other similar characters==\n*\u039d \u03bd : [[\u039d|Greek letter Nu]]\n*N n : [[N|Latin letter N]]\n*\u040a \u045a : [[\u040a|Cyrillic letter Nje]]\n*\u0397 \u03b7 : [[\u0397|Greek letter Eta]]\n*H h : [[H|Latin letter H]]\n*\u029c : [[\u029c|Latin letter small capital H]]\n\n==Computing codes==\n\n{{charmap\n|041D|name1=Cyrillic Capital Letter Ef\n|043D|name2=Cyrillic Small Letter En\n|map1=[[KOI8-R]] and [[KOI8-U]] |map1char1=EE |map1char2=CE\n|map2=[[Code page 855]] |map2char1=D5 |map2char2=D4\n|map3=[[Code page 866]] |map3char1=8D |map3char2=AD\n|map4=[[Windows-1251]] |map4char1=CD |map4char2=ED\n|map5=[[ISO-8859-5]] |map5char1=BD |map5char2=DD\n|map6=[[Macintosh Cyrillic encoding|Macintosh Cyrillic]] |map6char1=8D |map6char2=ED\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Wiktionary-inline|\u041d}}\n*{{Wiktionary-inline|\u043d}}\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text=the [[E|Latin letter H]]}}\n{{Cyrillic alphabet navbox|\nHeading=Cyrillic letter En|\nImage=Cyrillic letter En - uppercase and lowercase.svg|size=120px|\nuuc=041D|ulc=043D|numeral=50|sound = {{IPA|[n]}}}}\n'''En''' (\u041d&nbsp;\u043d; italics: <span styleU\"font-family: times, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-size: larger\">''\u041d&nbsp;\u043d''</span>) is a letter of the [[Cyrillic script]].\n\nIt commonly represents the [[alveolar nasal]] consonant {{IPA|/n/}}, like the pronunciation of {{angbr|n}} in \"'''n'''eat\".\n\n==History==\nThe Cyrillic letter En was derived from the [[Nu (letter)|Greek letter Nu]] (\u039d&nbsp;\u03bd).\n\nThe name of En in the [[Early Cyrillic alphabet]] was {{Script|Cyrs|\u043d\u0430\u0448\u044c}} (''na\u0161\u012d''), meaning \"ours\".\n\n==Form==\nThe capital Cyrillic letter En [[Homoglyph|looks exactly the same as]] the capital [[H|Latin letter H]] but, as with most Cyrillic letters, the lowercase form is simply a smaller version of the uppercase.\n\nBy exception, the [[Romanian Cyrillic alphabet]] used N and \u0274,{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}} instead of \u041d and \u043d.\n\nCoincidentally, the Cyrillic letter I {{angbr|\u0418}}, which looks like a reversed Latin {{angbr|N}}, was derived from the [[Eta (letter)|Greek letter Eta]] {{angbr|\u0397}} while the Cyrillic letter En {{angbr|\u041d}} was derived from the [[Nu (letter)|Greek letter Nu]] {{angbr|\u039d}} which looks like a reversed Cyrillic {{angbr|\u0418}}.\n\n==Usage==\nAs used in the alphabets of various languages, En represents the following sounds:\n* [[alveolar nasal]] consonant {{IPA|/n/}}, like the pronunciation of {{angbr|n}} in \"'''n'''ice\"\n* [[dental nasal]] consonant {{IPA|/n\u032a/}}, as above but with the tip of the tongue on the teeth\n* palatalized [[alveolar nasal]] consonant {{IPA|/n\u02b2/}}, like the pronunciation of {{angbr|n}} in \"o'''n'''ion\"\n* palatalized [[dental nasal]] consonant {{IPA|/n\u032a\u02b2/}}, as above but with the tip of the tongue on the teeth\n* [[palatal nasal]] consonant {{IPA|/\u0272/}}\n\nThe pronunciations shown in the table are the primary ones for each language; for details consult the articles on the languages.\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Language !! Position in <br> alphabet !! Pronunciation\n|-\n| [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]] || align=center | 15th || {{IPA|/n\u032a/}}, {{IPA|/n\u032a\u02b2/}}\n|-\n| [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] || align=center | 14th || {{IPA|/n/}}, {{IPA|/\u0272/}}\n|-\n| [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]] || align=center | 17th || {{IPA|/n/}}\n|-\n| [[Russian language|Russian]] || align=center | 15th || {{IPA|/n\u032a/}}, {{IPA|/n\u032a\u02b2/}}\n|-\n| [[Serbian language|Serbian]] || align=center | 16th || {{IPA|/n/}}\n|-\n| [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] || align=center | 18th || {{IPA|/n\u032a/}}, {{IPA|/n\u02b2/}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Related letters and other similar characters==\n*\u039d \u03bd : [[\u039d|Greek letter Nu]]\n*N n : [[N|Latin letter N]]\n*\u040a \u045a : [[\u040a|Cyrillic letter Nje]]\n*\u0397 \u03b7 : [[\u0397|Greek letter Eta]]\n*H h : [[H|Latin letter H]]\n*\u029c : [[\u029c|Latin letter small capital H]]\n\n==Computing codes==\n\n{{charmap\n|041D|name1=Cyrillic Capital Letter Ef\n|043D|name2=Cyrillic Small Letter En\n|map1=[[KOI8-R]] and [[KOI8-U]] |map1char1=EE |map1char2=CE\n|map2=[[Code page 855]] |map2char1=D5 |map2char2=D4\n|map3=[[Code page 866]] |map3char1=8D |map3char2=AD\n|map4=[[Windows-1251]] |map4char1=CD |map4char2=ED\n|map5=[[ISO-8859-5]] |map5char1=BD |map5char2=DD\n|map6=[[Macintosh Cyrillic encoding|Macintosh Cyrillic]] |map6char1=8D |map6char2=ED\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Wiktionary-inline|\u041d}}\n*{{Wiktionary-inline|\u043d}}\n", "name_user": "188.223.213.225", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/En_(Cyrillic)"}
{"title_page": "Amaravati", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date = November 2019}}\n{{Distinguish|Amravati, Maharashtra|Amarawati}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name                   = Amaravati\n| other_name                      = Dhanyakatakam\n| settlement_type                 = [[Historical]] [[City]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]]\n| image_skyline                   = {{photomontage\n|photo1a = Dhyana Buddha at Amaravati.jpg\n|photo2a = Front view of Amaravati Gopuram.jpg\n|photo2b = I love Amaravati at Tadepalli (2018).jpg\n|photo3a = High Court of Andhra Pradesh, Amaravati (May 2019) 2.jpg\n|photo3b = Group D officer's quarters under construction in Amaravati (March 2019) 05.jpg\n|photo4a = Amaravati 1.jpg\n|photo4b = Discription plate, Amaravati stupa. at Amaravati. A (12).JPG\n|photo5a = Amaravati Stupa in AP W IMG 8075.jpg\n|spacing = 1\n|color = white\n|size = 280\n}}\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = Clockwise from top : [[Dhyana Buddha statue]]; \n [[Amaralingeswara Temple]]; [[Andhra Pradesh High Court]]; [[Amaravati Stupa]].\n| nickname                        = '''Heritage City of Andhra Pradesh''' '''Historical City of Andhra Pradesh''' \n| image_map                       = \n| map_alt                         = A map showing location of Amaravati in Andhra Pradesh, India.\n| map_caption                     = Location of Amaravati in Andhra Pradesh, India\n| pushpin_map                     = India Andhra Pradesh#India#Asia\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|16.541|N|80.515|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flagicon|India}} [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{flagicon image|Andhraseal.png}} [[Andhra Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of regions of India|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Coromandel Coast|Coromandel]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Guntur district|Guntur]]\n| established_date                = 1 September 2014 <ref>http://ccdmc.co.in/downloads/Amaravati-concept-handbook_modified.pdf</ref>\n| government_type                 = Planning agencies\n| governing_body                  = [[Andhra Pradesh Capital Region Development Authority|APCRDA]]\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"apcrda\">{{cite web|title=Declaration of A.P. Capital City Area\u2013Revised orders|url=https://crda.ap.gov.in/APCRDADOCS/GOSACTSRULES/CRDA/01~14142015MAUD_MS141.PDF|website=Andhra Nation|publisher=Municipal Administration and Urban Development Department|accessdate=21 February 2016|date=22 September 2015}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2                  = 217.23\n| area_metro_footnotes            = <ref name=\"metro\">{{cite news|last1=Subba Rao|first1=GVR|title=Capital region expands as CRDA redraws boundaries|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Vijayawada/capital-region-expands-as-crda-redraws-boundaries/article7680051.ece|accessdate=31 October 2015|work=The Hindu|date=23 September 2015|location=Vijayawada}}</ref>{{refn|The Amaravati metropolitan area also includes portions of [[Amaravathi, Guntur district|Amaravathi]], [[Guntur]], [[Vijayawada]], [[Tenali]], [[Gudivada Municipality|Gudivada]], [[Tadepalle Municipality|Tadepalle]], [[Jaggayyapeta]], [[Mangalagiri Municipality|Mangalagiri]], [[Mopidevi]], [[Nuzvid]], [[Ponnur Municipality|Ponnur]], [[Sattenapalle]], [[Challapalle]], [[Nandigama]], [[Ghantasala, Krishna district|Ghantasala]],  [[Vuyyuru]] adjoining the [[Andhra Pradesh Capital Region|APCR]].|group=upper-alpha}}\n| area_metro_km2                  = 8352.69\n| population_total                = 103000\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = <ref>{{cite news|title=CRDA eyes CSR funds to push job potential in capital city|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vijayawada/CRDA-eyes-CSR-funds-to-push-job-potential-in-capital-city/articleshow/47891827.cms|accessdate=18 August 2015|work=The Times of India|date=1 July 2015|location=Guntur}}</ref>\n| population_metro                = 5800000\n| population_metro_footnotes      = <ref>{{cite news|title=Amaravati to be divided into eight urban plan areas|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/new-capital-region-to-be-divided-into-eight-urban-plan-areas/article7063043.ece|accessdate=21 June 2016|work=The Hindu|date=3 April 2015}}</ref>\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|Pincode(s)]]\n| postal_code                     = 520 XXX, 521 XXX, 522 XXX\n| area_code                       = \n| registration_plate              = AP-7, AP-8, AP-39<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aptransport.org/html/registration-districtcodes.html|title=Registration District Codes|publisher=Andhra Pradesh Transport Department|date=2019-12-06|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n| blank2_name                     = {{nowrap|Official languages}}\n| blank2_info                     = [[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n| website                         = {{URL|https://crda.ap.gov.in/|Amaravati official website}}\n| footnotes                       = {{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n| name                            = \n| founder                         = [[N. Chandrababu Naidu]]\n| established_title1              = [[Municipal incorporation|Established]]\n| established_date1               = 22 October 2015\n| named_for                       = Amareshwara swamy\n| established_title               = Mission\n}}\n'''Amaravati''' (formerly '''Dhanyakatakam''') is the most important [[heritage]], [[Buddhist texts|holy buddhist]] and [[Historical cities|historical city]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]]. It's history dates back to 2nd Century BCE when it was the [[capital]] of [[Satavahana dynasty|Satavahana Dynasty]] ([[Andhras]]), one of the earliest greatest kings of [[India]] and the [[Ancestor|ancestral]] [[dynasty]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]]. [[Satavahana dynasty|Satavahanas]] are most respected and viewed as very prominent and greatest rulers in [[Andhra Pradesh]] [[History of Andhra Pradesh|history]] as they were the reason for the origin of [[Telugu New Year]], [[Ugadi]] from this region. Their language was [[Prakrit]] of [[Brahmi script|Brahmi Script]], which served as the base for the [[script]] of [[Telugu language|Telugu Language]]. They issued many [[Gautamiputra Satakarni|coins]] with this [[Prakrit]] language which can be found in many insciptions in this region today. They even started the [[Shaka Calendar|Satavahana Calendar Era]], The first Indian National Calendar from this region. The city was also once the [[Holy place|holy site]] of [[Mahayana Buddhism]]. It was also the center of [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] [[Culture of Buddhism|learning]] and [[Buddhist art|art]] which can be seen from the [[Amaravati Stupa]], many [[Inscriptions|Buddhist inscriptions]], [[Sculpture|sculptures]] and [[Dhyana Buddha statue|Gautam Buddha Statue]] in the city. Many other ancient [[Amaravati Marbles|Amaravati Buddhist Marbels]] and Buddhist [[remains]] from the region were unfortunately destroyed over the time and some of them were exported to Chennai Museum and [[British Museum]] during the [[British Raj|British rule]] which can be seen there today. The sculptures on the [[Amaravati Marbles|Limestone Marbels]] depict many [[Buddhist art]], [[Epigraphy|incriptions]] and [[Amaravati Stupa|buddhist stupas]] serving as an eye feast. The city along with [[Nagarjunakonda|Nagarjuna Konda]] are viewed as one of the richest [[Holy place|holy sites]] of [[Buddhism]] in the entire [[India]] and [[Andhra Pradesh]].  \n\nIt is also [[capital city|state capital]] of the Indian state of [[Andhra Pradesh]], and the primary city of the state's [[Andhra Pradesh Capital Region|Capital Region]]. Built on allotted space on the southern banks of [[Krishna River]] in [[Guntur district]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://crda.ap.gov.in/APCRDADOCS/GOSACTSRULES/Capital%20City/01~131223042015MAUD_MS97.PDF|title=Naming of the Residuary Andhra Pradesh State Capital as \"AMARAVATI\"|date=23 April 2015|website=Andhra Nation|publisher=Municipal Administration and Urban Development Department|accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> selected close to the geographical center of the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/pt/650051486971245674/pdf/Environmental-and-Social-Management-Framework.pdf|title=Overview of the Capital City and Geographical location of Amaravati|date=August 2017|website=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Akbar|first1=Syed|title=Amaravati as official capital will boost Andhra Pradesh's image|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/visakhapatnam/Amaravati-as-official-capital-will-boost-Andhra-Pradeshs-image/articleshow/53595008.cms|accessdate=1 May 2017|work=The Times of India|date=8 Aug 2016}}</ref> Amaravati is a recently constructed [[planned city]]. The city was constructed to serve as Andhra Pradesh's new capital after [[Telangana]] was split off as a separate state in 2014. The former Andhraite capital, [[Hyderabad]], is now the capital of Telangana. \n\nIn response, Amaravati was founded by [[N. Chandrababu Naidu]] in the same year 2014 as the [[Greenfield land|Greenfield administrative capital city]] of the Andhra Pradesh state, and its [[cornerstone|foundation stone]] was laid at [[Uddandarayunipalem]] by the [[Prime Minister of India]] [[Narendra Modi]] on 22 October 2015.<ref name=\"foundation\">{{citation|title=Thousands descend on Andhra village Uddandarayunipalem to watch history in making|date=22 October 2015|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/thousands-descend-on-andhra-village-uddandarayunipalem-to-watch-history-in-making/articleshow/49491280.cms|newspaper=The Economic Times}}</ref> The city is built on {{convert|217|sqkm}} of [[riverfront]] designed to have 51% green space and 10% of water bodies.<ref name=\"apcrda\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/fpmYw43wSuaTHwfTgTlpgK/Amaravati-A-capital-idea.html|title=Amaravati: A capital idea, but how feasible?}}</ref> \n\nAs of October 2016, the majority of departments and officials of the Andhra Pradesh State Government are operating from the interim [[Andhra Pradesh Secretariat]] facilities located in the [[Velagapudi]] area of Amaravati, with only a skeleton staff remaining behind in Hyderabad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-andhra-pradesh-secretariat-starts-functioning-from-interim-government-complex-at-amaravati-2260970|title=Andhra Pradesh Secretariat starts functioning from interim government complex at Amaravati  & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=3 October 2016}}</ref> From April 2016, the office of the [[Chief Minister of Andhra Pradesh]] has operated from Velagapudi. The [[Andhra Pradesh Legislature]] remained in Hyderabad until March 2017, when it relocated to newly constructed interim legislative buildings in Velagapudi.<ref>[https://www.news18.com/news/india/andhra-pradesh-holds-maiden-budget-session-in-new-capital-amaravati-1356763.html Andhra Pradesh Holds Maiden Budget Session in New Capital Amaravati]</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe name \"Amaravati\" derives from the historical [[Amaravathi (village), Andhra Pradesh|Amaravathi village]], the ancient capital of the [[Satavahana dynasty]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/After-18-centuries-Amaravati-set-to-become-a-capital-again/articleshow/49489009.cms|title=After 18 centuries, Amaravati set to become a 'capital' again|date=22 October 2015|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref>  The metropolitan areas of [[Guntur]], [[Vijayawada]] and [[Tenali]] are the major [[conurbation]]s of Amaravati.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/explained/why-amaravati-has-been-chosen-as-the-new-andhra-pradesh-capital/|title=Explained: Why Amaravati has been chosen as the new Andhra Pradesh capital|date=21 October 2015|work=The Indian Express}}</ref>\n\n''Amaravati'' translates literally as 'the place for immortals'.  It was formerly named after ''Dhanyakataka'', the location where Shakyamuni Buddha taught the Heart Essence form of the Kalachakra Dharma to the Shambala kings.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n== History ==\n[[File: Southern India, Andhra Pradesh, Amaravati, Satavahana Period - Veneration of the Buddha as a Fiery Piller - 1943.72 - Cleveland Museum of Art.tif|alt=Southern India, Andhra Pradesh, Amaravati, Satavahana Period \u2013 Veneration of the Buddha as a Fiery Piller \u2013 1943.72 \u2013 Cleveland Museum of Art|thumb|Southern India, Andhra Pradesh, Amaravati, Satavahana Period \u2013 Veneration of the Buddha as a Fiery Piller -100 BC \u2013 c. AD 200 \u2013 Cleveland Museum of Art, Ohio, United States|left]]\nThe present capital area has its historical significance of having recorded its first-ever legislation 2,200 years ago.<ref>{{cite news|title=After 2,200 years, Amaravati gets back its legislation power|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/amaravati/after-2200-years-amaravati-gets-back-its-legislation-power/articleshow/57505968.cms|accessdate=1 May 2017|work=The Times of India}}</ref> The present-day capital region includes the [[Amaravathi (village), Andhra Pradesh|ancient Amaravati]]. The area has been ruled by the [[Mauryas]], [[Satavahanas]], [[Andhra Ikshvaku|Ikshvakus]], [[Vishnukundina]], [[Pallavas]], [[Cholas]], [[Kakatiyas]], [[Delhi Sultanate]], [[Musunuri Nayaks]], [[Bahmani Sultanate]], [[Vijayanagara Empire]], Sultanate of [[Golconda]] and [[Mughal Empire]] successively before the founding of the [[Nizam of Hyderabad]] in 1724. It was ceded to [[Kingdom of France|France]] in 1750 but was captured by [[Kingdom of Great Britain|the British]] in 1759. Guntur returned to the Nizamate in 1768 but was ceded to Britain again in 1788. It was briefly occupied by [[Hyder Ali]]. It was then ruled by [[Vasireddy Venkatadri Nayudu]]. It was part of [[Madras Presidency]] during the British colonial period.\n\nAs per the [[Andhra Pradesh Reorganisation Act, 2014]], [[Hyderabad]] became the capital of the then newly formed state of [[Telangana]], post bifurcation of [[Andhra Pradesh]]. However, Hyderabad would remain as the joint capital of both states for a period not exceeding ten years. Hence, Amaravati is being built to serve as the capital of Andhra Pradesh.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Andhra Pradesh Reorganisation Act, 2014 |url=http://reorganisation.ap.gov.in/downloads/A.P.RegulationAct2014.pdf|website=AP Reorganisation Portal|publisher=The Gazette of India Extraordinary|accessdate=9 February 2015 |location=New Delhi|date=1 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe foundation for the city was laid at [[Uddandarayunipalem]] on 22 October 2015. The [[Prime Minister of India]], [[Narendra Modi]];  the  [[Chief Minister of Andhra Pradesh]], [[Nara Chandrababu Naidu]]; the [[Vice President of India]] and the Chairman of the Rajya Sabha [[Muppavarapu Venkaiah Naidu]]; then Governor [[E. S. L. Narasimhan]]; the [[Japan]]ese minister for economy trade and industry, [[Yosuke Takagi]]; and the [[Ministry of Trade and Industry (Singapore)|Singaporean Minister for Trade and Industry]], [[S. Iswaran]], laid the foundation for the city.<ref name=\"foundation\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/506499/andhra-cm-scales-down-amaravathi.html|title=Andhra CM scales down Amaravati foundation fete}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe city is being built in [[Guntur district]], on the banks of the [[Krishna River]]. The city will be {{convert|40|km}} south-west of [[Vijayawada]], {{convert|32|km}} north of [[Guntur]], {{convert|70|km}} south-east of [[Tenali]] surrounding the [[Coromandel Coast]] of [[Coastal Andhra|Coastal Andhra region]] in [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[India]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=U Sudhakar Reddy|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141031/nation-current-affairs/article/andhra-pradesh-capital-come-riverfront-guntur-district|title=Andhra Pradesh capital to come up on riverfront in Guntur district|date=31 October 2014|work=Deccan Chronicle|accessdate=1 November 2014|location=Hyderabad}}</ref>\n\n== Vision ==\n[[File:Amaravathi 3D print.jpg|thumb|Amaravati 3D Sketch Map at [[APCRDA]] Office.|alt=|left]]\n\nThe 13th Chief Minister of Andhra Pradesh [[N. Chandrababu Naidu]] envisioned Amaravati to be the people-centric pioneer [[Smart City]] of India, built around sustainability and livability principles, and to be the happiest city in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/amaravati-will-be-developed-as-the-happiest-city-in-the-world-andhra-cm/article23492961.ece|title=Amaravati will be developed as the happiest city in the world: Andhra CM|first=Ch R. S.|last=Sarma|website=@businessline}}</ref> Among the innovative features on the drawing board are navigation canals<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vijayawada/Civil-works-of-administrative-city-to-start-by-november-1-CM/articleshow/55083133.cms|title=Civil works of administrative city to start by November 1: CM|website=The Times of India}}</ref> around the city, and connecting to an island in the Krishna River. The Government has envisaged an investment needed<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/andhras-bonds-for-amaravati-oversubscribed-by-1-5-times/articleshow/65501684.cms|title=Andhra\u2019s bonds for Amaravati oversubscribed by 1.5 times|first=C. R.|last=Sukumar|date=22 August 2018|via=The Economic Times}}</ref> of {{USD|2\u20134 billion}} for the development of the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/amaravati-development-needs-2-4-billion-investment-chandrababu-naidu/articleshow/65562480.cms|title=Amaravati development needs $2\u20134 billion investment: Chandrababu Naidu|date=27 August 2018|via=The Economic Times}}</ref> \n\nThe city is being designed to have 51% [[Urban open space|green space]] and 10% of water bodies, with a plan to house some of the most iconic buildings there. It is being modeled on Singapore, with the master plan being prepared by two Singapore government-appointed consultants. Other international consultants and architects will then be brought in to give the city an international flavor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/how-andhra-pradesh-plans-to-make-its-new-capital-amaravati-a-world-class-city/articleshow/58767503.cms|title=How Andhra Pradesh plans to make its new capital Amaravati a world-class city|first=Shantanu Nandan|last=Sharma|date=21 May 2017|via=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\n== City Planning ==\n[[File:3D Model of Amaravati in APCRDA office, Vijayawada (6).jpg|thumb|3D Model of Amaravati in APCRDA office,]]\n[[File:3D Model of Amaravati in APCRDA office, Vijayawada (4).jpg|alt=Model view of Amaravati in APCRDA office|thumb|Model view of Amaravati in APCRDA office]]\nThe Andhra Pradesh State Cabinet meeting passed a resolution of 1 September 2014 to locate the Capital City in a central place of the state, around Vijayawada, and to go for decentralized development of the state with 3 Mega Cities and 14 Smart Cities. The State Government identified the Capital City area between Vijayawada and Guntur cities on the Southern bank of River Krishna upstream of Prakasam Barrage. The Amaravati Capital City has an area of 217.23 km<sup>2</sup> and is spread across 25 villages in 3 mandals (Thulluru, Mangalagiri and Tadepalli) of Guntur district. The 25 villages in the Capital City area have about 1 lakh population in about 27,000 households. The nearest cities are Vijayawada at a distance of 30 km and Guntur at a distance of 18 km. The nearest railway station is KC Canal railway station near Tadepalli and the nearest airport is Gannavaram which is at a distance of 22 km. The city is planned to spread over 217 km<sup>2</sup> area with a total cost of \u20b9 553.43 billions to the Capital Region Development Authority (CRDA) out of which state government contribution is only \u20b9 126 billion (equity \u20b9 66.29 billion and supporting grant \u20b9 59.71 billion) spread over a period of 8 years from April 2018 to March 2026 (\u20b9 5 billion in 2018\u201319, \u20b9 18 billion per year for later six years and \u20b9 13 billion in 2025\u201326).<ref name=\"amr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eenadu.net/eenadu-exclusive/newsarticle/general/1500/120008374|title=Amaravati city a self financed project |language=Telugu|access-date=18 January 2020}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Andhra Pradesh Capital Region Development Authority (APCRDA)\n|'''City area details:'''\n|'''Land utilization'''\n|-\n|Roads, public utilities, parks, natural streams, water bodies\n|27,885 acres\n|-\n|Plots for residential area allotted to the Land contributors(Farmers)\n|11,826 acres\n|-\n|For the needs of other developments presently owned by the CRDA\n|14,037 acres\n|-\n|Total area under the jurisdiction of CRDA\n|53,748 acres\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Amaravati City Land Usage\n!Land use\n!Area (Sq.&nbsp;km)\n!'''%'''\n|-\n|Residential\n|60.77\n|27.9\n|-\n|Commercial\n|20.99\n|9.34\n|-\n|Public and Semi Public\n|11.49\n|5.29\n|-\n|Open spaces and Recreation\n|52.78\n|24.29\n|-\n|Industrial\n|12.26\n|5.64\n|-\n|Water Bodies\n|25.78\n|11.87\n|-\n|Traffic and Transportation\n|23.04\n|10.61\n|-\n|Cultural Heritage\n|0.15\n|0.07\n|-\n|Seed Capital\n|10.67\n|4.91\n|-\n|Total\n|217.23\n|100\n|}\nThe contribution from the government is to be repaid by the CRDA after the year 2037. Ultimately state or union governments are not incurring any expenditure to construct the city but wholly financed by the income accrued from the sale of land for various development schemes (\u20b9 171.51 billion), loans and the local taxes (\u20b9 146.41 billion by 2037) to the CRDA. The state and union governments are expected to earn \u20b9 120 billion per annum out of which state goods and services tax (State GST) alone is \u20b9 60 billion per annum.<ref name=\"amr\" /> The entire city construction is planned by self-financing from loans and land selling with the state government's moral support. CRDA is expecting a net surplus income of \u20b9 333 billion by 2037 after meeting the total expenditure on the city. Amaravati government complex which is intended to provide world-class facilities needed for the state government and its employees' accommodation is also part of CRDA project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://crda.ap.gov.in/APCRDADOCS/DataModuleFIles/Reports/01~Amaravati%20Project%20Report%20Edition%20No4%20Status%20Feb%202019.pdf|title=Amaravati Project progress report, Edition 4, Feb 2019|access-date=18 January 2020}}</ref> The bus rapid transit system (BRTS) in Amaravati to connect with the adjacent Vijayawada and Guntur cities by world-class road network is also part of the CRDA project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/vijayawada/2018/mar/02/vijayawada-brts-planned-for-amaravati-to-tackle-vehicle-population-growth-1780930.html|title=BRTS planned for Amaravati to tackle vehicle, population growth|access-date=18 January 2020}}</ref> Both Amaravati government complex and BRTS are planned with an expenditure of \u20b9 140 billion.<ref name=\"amr\" />\n\n== Timeline ==\n[[File:Permanent Secretariat Tower 5 under construction in Amaravati (April 2019).jpg|alt=Permanent Secretariat Tower 5 under construction in Amaravati|thumb|Permanent Secretariat Tower 5 under construction in Amaravati April 2019]]\n[[File:Amaravati Secretariat in Velagapudi (January 2019) 1.jpg|alt=Amaravati Secretariat in Velagapudi|thumb|Amaravati Secretariat in Velagapudi]]\n[[File:Raft foundation works of Andhra Pradesh secretariat in Amaravati (January 2019) 4.jpg|alt=Raft foundation works of Andhra Pradesh secretariat in Amaravati |thumb|Raft foundation works of Andhra Pradesh secretariat in Amaravati ]]\n[[File:Government complex under construction near Rayapudi (January 2019) 12.jpg|alt=Government complex under construction near Rayapudi |thumb|Government complex under construction near Rayapudi ]]\n[[File:Construction equipment at Government complex in Amaravati (January 2019) 4.jpg|alt=Construction equipment at Government complex in Amaravati (January 2019|thumb|Construction equipment at Government complex in Amaravati (January 2019)]]\n[[File:NGO housing under construction in Amaravati (March 2019) 12.jpg|alt=NGO housing under construction in Amaravati (March 2019)|thumb|NGO housing under construction in Amaravati (March 2019)]]\n[[File:Panorama showing constructions along seed access road (November 2018).jpg|alt=Constructions along seed access road|thumb|Constructions along seed access road]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Date\n!Event\n|-\n|2014\n|2 June 2014\n|AP Reorganization Act comes into force.\n|-\n|\n|1 September 2014\n|Location of new Capital City finalized\n|-\n|\n|30 December 2014\n|APCRDA Act comes into effect and APCRDA established\n|-\n|2015\n|January 2015\n|Voluntary Land Pooling Scheme announced\n|-\n|\n|March 2015\n|Consent for 33,000 acres obtained from farmers\n|-\n|\n|30 March 2015\n|Submission of Perspective Plan by Singapore Govt\n|-\n|\n|25 May 2015\n|Submission of Capital City Plan (391sq.&nbsp;km) by Singapore Govt\n|-\n|\n|6 June 2015\n|Amaravati City Bhoomi Puja (Ground-breaking ceremony) by Chief Minister [[N. Chandrababu Naidu]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/news/india/naidu/articleshow/47569939.cms|title=Naidu performs Bhoomi pooja for AP capital|last=Pavan|first=P. PavanP|last2=Jun 7|first2=Bangalore Mirror Bureau {{!}} Updated:|website=Bangalore Mirror|access-date=2020-03-14|last3=2015|last4=Ist|first4=00:54}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=CM Chandrababu Naidu Performs 'Bhoomi Puja' For AP Capital City In Mandadam|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xRmwp1kvh18|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n|-\n|\n|20 July 2015\n|Submission of Seed Area Development Plan by Singapore Govt\n|-\n|\n|7 August 2015\n|Workshop with experts on Capital City master plan (3 days)\n|-\n|\n|19 October 2015\n|Workshop with experts on Capital City master plan\n|-\n|\n|October 2015\n|Amaravati Greenfield Capital City Development receives Environmental Clearance.\n|-\n|\n|22 October 2015\n|Foundation stone set by Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/modi-to-lay-foundation-stone-of-new-ap-capital-on-oct-22-264884-1999-11-30|title=PM Modi to lay foundation stone of new Andhra Pradesh capital on October 22|last=November 30|first=Press Trust of India|last2=September 27|first2=1999UPDATED:|website=India Today|access-date=2020-03-14|last3=Ist|first3=2015 19:50}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=PM Narendra Modi at the laying of foundation stone of Amaravathi, new Andhra Pradesh Capital|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7sHceWi9p4I|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n|-\n|\n|27 October 2015\n|Workshop with stake holders on Capital City Master Plan\n|-\n|\n|26 December 2015\n|Notification of Draft Detailed Master Plan for Capital City\n|-\n|2016\n|12 January 2016 to <br>21 January 2016\n|Master Plan awareness programme (Grama Sabhas) in each of the 29 villages\n|-\n|\n|23 February 2016\n|Notification of Detailed Master Plan for Capital City\n|-\n|\n|August 2016\n|First returnable layout published.\n|-\n|\n|12 October 2016\n|Andhra Pradesh interim Secretariat construction completed and inaugurated by Chief Minister Naidu in Amaravati<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/andhra-cm-chandrababu-naidu-inaugurat